<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">NOTICE OF APPEAL</TI>
<P><BOLD>THE PLAINTIFFS/APPELLANTS, JAMIE CLARK, DONALD BELANGER and STEVEN WATTS</BOLD> (collectively, the &ldquo;Plaintiffs&rdquo; or the &ldquo;Appellants&rdquo;) <BOLD>APPEAL</BOLD> to the Court of Appeal from the Order of the Honourable Mr. Justice Stinson dated June 13, 2017, made at Toronto, Ontario, striking the Appellants' negligence claim on the basis that it discloses no reasonable cause of action pursuant to Rule 21 (the &ldquo;Order&rdquo;).</P>
<P><BOLD>THE APPELLANTS ASK:</BOLD></P>
<P>1. That the deadline for delivering the Notice of Appeal and Certificate Respecting Evidence herein be extended to October 3, 2017 on consent;</P>
<P>2. That the Order be set aside and a new Order issue as follows:
<P1>a) <BOLD>THIS COURT ORDERS</BOLD> that the motion brought by the Attorney General of Ontario (the &ldquo;Attorney General&rdquo;) to dismiss the Appellants' negligence claim shall be and is hereby dismissed;</P1>
<P1>b) <BOLD>THIS COURT FURTHER ORDERS</BOLD> that the remainder of the Attorney General's motion to strike shall be and is hereby dismissed;</P1>
<P1>c) <BOLD>THIS COURT FURTHER ORDERS</BOLD> that the Attorney General shall pay the Appellants' costs of the motion to strike forthwith;</P1>
<P1>d) <BOLD>THIS COURT FURTHER ORDERS</BOLD> that the Attorney General shall pay the Appellants' costs of the appeal forthwith; and</P1></P>
<P>3. For such further and other relief as this Honourable Court may deem just.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE GROUNDS OF APPEAL</BOLD> are as follows:</P>
<P>4. The Appellants are officers with the Toronto Police Service. They commenced the underlying action, alleging negligence and misfeasance against the Attorney General, with respect to the alleged conduct of two assistant Crown Attorneys and one appellate Crown counsel, in the course of the criminal prosecution of Randy Maharaj (<BOLD>&ldquo;Maharaj&rdquo;</BOLD>) and Neil Singh (<BOLD>&ldquo;Singh&rdquo;</BOLD>), for armed robbery and forcible confinement;</P>
<P>5. The Appellants were officers in the Hold-Up Squad at the time, and conducted the investigation which led to the prosecution of the two men. The two men claimed that the Appellants assaulted them during the arrest. The allegations were patently false;</P>
<P>6. Despite the denials of the Appellants, the trial Crown Attorneys obtained a stay of the charges against Maharaj in November of 2011 as a result of those allegations;</P>
<P>7. Singh was convicted of the offences, but received a reduced sentence in June of 2012, due to the fact that the Crown conceded that he and Maharaj were assaulted at the time of their arrest by the Appellants;</P>
<P>8. Judges of the Superior Court in March and July of 2012 issued written decisions that were critical of the Appellants' conduct, specifically that they had assaulted the accused. On December 12, 2013, the Court of Appeal overturned Singh's conviction, finding, <EM>inter alia</EM>, that the Appellants had &ldquo;tortured&rdquo; the accused, Singh. As a result, the Appellants' reputations have been irreparably damaged;</P>
<P>9. The Statement of Claim alleges that the trial and appeal Crowns failed to pursue and put before the Court all of the available evidence that completely contradicted any allegations of assault. The Appellants allege, <EM>inter alia</EM>, the Crowns violated a duty of care owed to them, and thus were negligent in law;</P>
<P>10. In addition to the negligence claim, the Appellants also pleaded the tort of misfeasance in a public office, alleging that the Crown attorneys engaged in deliberate and/or unlawful conduct in their capacity as public officers, and were aware that their conduct was unlawful and likely to harm the Appellants;</P>
<P>11. The Attorney General brought a motion to strike the Statement of Claim, on the basis that:
<P1>a) It failed to disclose a reasonable cause of action with respect to the torts of negligence and misfeasance in a public office; and</P1>
<P1>b) It was statute-barred pursuant to section 4 of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM> because it was alleged that the action was commenced more than two years after the Appellants discovered the material facts on which the claim was based;</P1></P>
<P>12. Stinson J. bifurcated the motion, and the limitations period issue was argued on October 5<SUP>th</SUP>, 2016;</P>
<P>13. On January 4<SUP>th</SUP>, 2017, Stinson J. released his decision and dismissed the Attorney General's motion on the limitations issue. The Attorney General has, with the consent of the Appellants, filed a Notice of Motion for Leave to Appeal that decision. It was also agreed the motion would be held in abeyance until the remainder of the motion before Stinson J. was dealt with;</P>
<P>14. The second part of the Attorney General's motion, i.e.: to strike the Appellants' claim for no reasonable cause of action with respect to the negligence and tort of misfeasance in a public office, was heard by Stinson J. on February 21<SUP>st</SUP> and 22<SUP>nd</SUP>, 2017. On June 13<SUP>th</SUP>, 2017, Stinson J. released his decision and made the following findings:
<P1>a) Crown attorneys do not have absolute immunity from civil claims, other than claims for malicious prosecution and intentional non-disclosure;</P1>
<P1>b) Although all of the constituent elements to satisfy a cause of action exist for a police officer to sue the Crown in negligence, for policy reasons, the Court concluded that such a cause of action could not be allowed. As a result, the Appellants' claim of negligence was struck; and,</P1>
<P1>c) On the facts alleged in the Statement of Claim, the Appellants had properly pleaded the claim for the tort of misfeasance in a public office, and thus that aspect of their action was allowed to proceed;</P1></P>
<P>15. On November 29, 2016, the Court released its decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 7222</CITE></CASEREF>, which ruled on a similar motion to strike. That case considered whether Crown attorneys could be liable to police officers in negligence with respect to the provision of legal advice. In the reasons for her decision, the Honourable Justice Matheson held, <EM>inter alia</EM>:
<P1>a) It was not plain and obvious that there is no duty of care owed by Crown attorneys to the police; and,</P1>
<P1>b) The claim in negligence should not be struck at the pleadings stage for policy reasons, as a comprehensive factual record was needed to properly consider the policy ramifications of the novel claim at issue;</P1></P>
<P>16. On May 10, 2017, the Honourable Justice Marrocco granted the Defendants leave to appeal to the Divisional Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>;</P>
<P>17. In dismissing the Appellant's claim of negligence in the case at bar, the Honourable Mr. Justice Stinson committed errors of law and of mixed fact and law that warrant the intervention of this Honourable Court, including:
<P1>a) Finding that the Plaintiff's negligence claim did not novel issues;</P1>
<P1>b) finding that a <EM>prima facie</EM> duty of care could be negated by speculative policy concerns in the absence of a comprehensive (or indeed, <EM>any</EM>) factual record to substantiate those policy concerns;</P1>
<P1>c) striking the Plaintiffs' claim for negligence as against the Attorney General of Ontario at the pleadings stage for speculative policy reasons,
<P2>i. in the absence of a comprehensive factual record necessary to properly consider the policy ramifications of the novel claim at issue; and</P2>
<P2>ii. despite the existence of all constituent elements necessary to satisfy the underlying cause of action in negligence;</P2></P1>
<P1>d) failing to follow the persuasive reasoning and outcome of Madam Justice Matheson's November 29, 2016 decision dismissing a similar motion to strike in <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, which remains good law, despite leave to appeal being granted by the Divisional Court;</P1>
<P1>e) failing to award costs payable forthwith by the Attorney General to the Police Officers; and</P1>
<P1>f) such further and other grounds as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>THE BASIS OF THE APPELLATE COURT'S JURISDICTION IS:</BOLD></P>
<P>18. The Order appealed from is a final Order of a Judge of the Superior Court of Justice dismissing a claim for an amount greater than $50,000, exclusive of costs;</P>
<P>19. Leave to appeal is therefore not required;</P>
<P>20. Sections 6, 19(1)(a), 19(1.2)(a), 19(1.2)(c) and 134 of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. C.43;</P>
<P>21. Rule 61 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>. R.R.O. 1990, Reg. 194; and</P>
<P>22. Such further and other bases of appellate jurisdiction as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P>
