<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">I. NATURE OF THIS APPEAL</TI>
<P>1. The Plaintiffs/Appellants, Jamie Clark, Donald Belanger and Steven Watts (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Appellants&rdquo;</BOLD>) appeal from the decision of the Honourable Justice Stinson of the Superior Court of Justice, dated June 13, 2017, striking out the Appellants' claim in negligence.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">II. OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>2. This appeal raises an important issue concerning the relationship between agents of the Crown who prosecute criminal cases and police witnesses who investigate and prepare those cases for prosecution.</P>
<P>3. For the purposes of this appeal, there is no question that the conduct of the Crown in the carriage of the prosecution of <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Singh</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Maharaj</SOC></CASEREF> was negligent. That negligence led not only to a stay of proceedings being entered as a result of a fraud being perpetrated on the Court, but also to significant reputational and financial damages to the Appellant police officers. It must also be taken, as pleaded, that had various Crown agents exercised due care and attention in the manner in which they carried out their prosecution, adverse <EM>Charter</EM> findings and adverse legal conclusions that the Appellants had engaged in violent torturous activity against Singh and Maharaj would not have been made.</P>
<P>4. The Appellants' position is that, notwithstanding the significant and important degree of deference shown to prosecutors and a general immunity from civil liability, the Crown must be held accountable in negligence to the Plaintiffs.</P>
<P>5. The public policy argument for precluding a claim in negligence against the Crown in these circumstances should fail. Alternatively, and in any event, at this stage of the proceeding, there was an insufficient record to determine the public policy issue. The motions judge erred in law by making determinations of policy&mdash;which involve conclusions of mixed fact and law&mdash;in the absence of any evidence. He was therefore incorrect in his conclusion that, despite a finding of a <EM>prima facie</EM> duty of care, the Appellants' claim in negligence should be struck for public policy reasons.</P>
<P>6. The Appellants request that the appeal be allowed and that the action be restored, and that the Respondent's motion to strike be dismissed in its entirety.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">III. FACTS</TI>
<P>7. The Appellants rely on the Statement of Claim's more comprehensive version of facts, the most essential of which are provided below.</P>
<P>8. The Appellants, Jamie Clark (<BOLD>&ldquo;Sgt. Clark&rdquo;</BOLD>), Donald Belanger (<BOLD>&ldquo;Det. Sgt. Belanger&rdquo;</BOLD>) and Steven Watts (<BOLD>&ldquo;Det. Sgt. Watts&rdquo;</BOLD>), (collectively, the <BOLD>&ldquo;Officers&rdquo;</BOLD>), are police officers with the Toronto Police Service. They were members of the Hold-Up Squad at the relevant time.</P>
<P>9. In February 2009, the Officers investigated a very serious robbery and forcible confinement at a commercial establishment. The perpetrators had brandished a firearm, zip-tied the victim, duct-taped his mouth and forcibly confined him while stealing approximately $389,000 of copper tubing.</P>
<P>10. On or about June 11, 2009, after a thorough investigation, the Officers formulated reasonable and probable grounds to arrest Neil Singh (<BOLD>&ldquo;Singh&rdquo;</BOLD>) and Randy Maharaj (<BOLD>&ldquo;Maharaj&rdquo;</BOLD>) and charge them with various offences in connection with the crime. Upon their arrest, both accused gave statements, which were video recorded. The accused elected to have a preliminary inquiry following which they were committed to stand trial.</P>
<P>11. For the first time, over two and a half years later<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>During a June 12, 2009 bail hearing, counsel for Maharaj said that his client had suffered injuries&mdash;bumps and scratches behind his ear&mdash;during the arrest. Counsel did not allege any assaultive conduct by the Officers during the interrogations. Nor was it alleged that there was any injury to Maharaj's rib. During the preliminary inquiry, counsel asked the police witnesses about physically assaulting the accused, and the Officers categorically denied the assault had taken place.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, at the trial in the Superior Court of Justice before Justice Thorburn, the two accused brought applications to stay proceedings based on alleged physical mistreatment at the hands of the Officers following their arrest. Maharaj alleged that he had been physically assaulted before he provided his inculpatory statement. T he nature of the assault was so vicious that he alleged he had suffered a &ldquo;cracked rib&rdquo; in the process. To attempt to buttress his claim, his counsel provided the Crown with an X-ray of Maharaj's chest taken after his arrest.</P>
<P>12. The Crown assigned to the case, Sheila Cressman (<BOLD>&ldquo;Ms. Cressman&rdquo;</BOLD>), consulted Dr. Farley Moss (<BOLD>&ldquo;Dr. Moss&rdquo;</BOLD>) at Scarborough Centenary Hospital regarding the X-Ray. Dr. Moss confirmed the X-Ray showed a fractured rib, and said that this injury would cause excruciating pain if a person moved his upper arms or body. Dr. Moss said it was <BOLD><UNDER>possible</UNDER></BOLD> the rib injury occurred on the day of the arrest.</P>
<P>13. Dr. Moss was not provided with a copy of Maharaj's videotaped statement to assess whether or not it was consistent with someone having just had their rib broken, as Maharaj had alleged. During that videotaped statement, Maharaj is seen freely using his arms and carrying on in such a way that it was not possible he had sustained the rib injury at the time (this will be dealt with more fully below).</P>
<P>14. The Appellants have pleaded that Ms. Cressman failed to take further obvious and appropriate steps to investigate Maharaj's allegation. In particular, Ms. Cressman:
<P1>(a) never asked Dr. Moss to review the videotaped statement, in which Maharaj is seen making various movements with his arms that were incompatible with having a fresh rib injury;</P1>
<P1>(b) never asked Dr. Moss further questions regarding other potential time periods in which the injury could have occurred;</P1>
<P1>(c) never made inquiries of staff at Maplehurst Detention Centre (<BOLD>&ldquo;Maplehurst&rdquo;</BOLD>), where Maharaj was incarcerated during his trial, about Maharaj, even though she was in possession of Maharaj's medical records from the facility that showed no complaints about a rib injury any time after his arrest;</P1>
<P1>(d) did not properly review the transcripts of the bail hearing to understand the inconsistent injuries reported then as opposed to those reported at the time of the stay application; and</P1>
<P1>(e) did not seek further advice or comment from the Officers who had testified at the preliminary hearing and adamantly denied assaulting Maharaj.</P1></P>
<P>15. Despite her failure to take any steps to properly investigate the unsubstantiated allegation, Ms. Cressman, in consultation with senior Crown Attorney Frank Armstrong (<BOLD>&ldquo;Mr. Armstrong&rdquo;</BOLD>), decided that Maharaj's statement would not be admissible because of involuntariness and therefore there would be no case against him. Mr. Armstrong did not direct Ms. Cressman or anyone else to conduct a farther investigation into the allegation. The Crown decided to stay the charges against Maharaj on November 22, 2011.</P>
<P>16. Singh's trial commenced on November 28, 2011. Singh also sought to stay the proceedings against him on the basis of abusive police conduct. He falsely testified that he also had been assaulted by the Officers. He relied on the purported mistreatment of Maharaj at the hands of the police to buttress his claim. On the ensuing application, Maharaj provided <EM>viva voce</EM> evidence that he had been assaulted by the Officers.</P>
<P>17. Although aware that the Officers had previously testified under oath that they did not engage in any assaultive conduct and would testify to that effect if called as witnesses, Ms. Cressman called no evidence to challenge or contradict the false testimony. Rather, she essentially accepted that the alleged assaults had occurred. She did so notwithstanding that she had assured Det. Sgt. Watt that he and the other Officers would be called as witnesses. However, after the first day of hearing, Ms. Cressman informed Det. Sgt. Watt she would not require the Officers' evidence. Though Det. Sgt. Watt expressed his concern to Ms. Cressman about how this decision would adversely affect the outcome of the case and findings that might be made against the Officers, Ms. Cressman would not change her position and the Officers were prevented from testifying.</P>
<P>18. The Officers were not parties to the proceeding involving the Respondent and Singh and, to the knowledge of the Crown, had no standing to adduce evidence or make representations to the Court. The Officers relied on the Respondent to ensure that findings of illegal and improper conduct were not made against them in the absence of a full and complete record. Although the Crown could not control whether a Court might make those findings, the Crown could control whether the trial Court had all information relevant to the Officers' conduct given the potential for adverse findings against the Officers.</P>
<P>19. Ms. Cressman did not require Singh's counsel to prove the nature of the alleged assault, nor did she test the evidence in any way. She simply conceded that the assaultive conduct, as falsely alleged, had occurred and that there had been a serious <EM>Charter</EM> violation. Ms. Cressman knew at the time that doing so would have serious repercussions not only for the case she was prosecuting but for the Officers as well.</P>
<P>20. In the face of the Crown's factual and legal concessions, Justice Thorburn concluded that the conduct alleged by Maharaj and Singh had occurred as they alleged. Essentially, it was the Court's view that in the absence of any competing evidence, the only conclusion available was to accept the evidence of Maharaj and Singh, which the Court did in a judgement released on March 28, 2012.</P>
<P>21. However, Thorburn J. did not stay the proceedings. Singh was subsequently convicted by a jury of armed robbery and forceful confinement. Though Justice Thorburn dismissed Singh's stay application, she reduced Singh's sentence because of the Officers' &ldquo;brutality&rdquo; and &ldquo;thoroughly reprehensible&rdquo; behaviour in the case. The Court's findings were widely reported in the mainstream media and on the internet. Singh appealed the decision of Thorburn J. refusing to stay the proceedings to this Honourable Court.</P>
<P>22. Following the judgment, the Crown Law Office&mdash;Criminal notified the Chief of Police of their concerns about the Officers' conduct. The Special Investigations Unit (<BOLD>&ldquo;SIU&rdquo;</BOLD>) invoked its mandate to conduct an investigation. However, Maharaj refused to be interviewed or to participate in the investigation, and the SIU withdrew its mandate in July 2012.</P>
<P>23. After the SIU withdrew its mandate, the Toronto Police Service Professional Standards Unit (<BOLD>&ldquo;TPSPS&rdquo;</BOLD>) conducted a comprehensive and independent review of the allegations of misconduct against the Officers. The investigators concluded that, based on an analysis of all the evidence, the allegations that the Officers used excessive force could not be substantiated.</P>
<P>24. In and around November 2012, the Crown Law Office was made aware of these new material facts that demonstrated the serious injustice that had been done to the Officers. The Crown took no action in response.</P>
<P>25. Before Singh's appeal was argued, Det. Sgt. Watt met with Amy Alyea (<BOLD>&ldquo;Ms. Alyea&rdquo;</BOLD>), who was going to argue the appeal on behalf of the Crown. He told Ms. Alyea that an egregious mistake had occurred. He advised Ms. Alyea of the results of the TPSPS report, of which she had a copy, and of Ms. Cressman's conduct. He asked Ms. Alyea to correct the injustice that had occurred in the lower court in whatever manner was appropriate.</P>
<P>26. Despite Det. Sgt. Watt's efforts, Ms. Alyea: (i) took no steps to investigate further, (ii) took no steps to rectify and repair the damage that had been done to the Officers' reputations, and (iii) took no steps to prepare and file an application to introduce fresh evidence before the Court of Appeal. During oral arguments in the appeal, the Court asked several questions about the Officers' behaviour, but Ms. Alyea never adequately advised the Court of the new material facts the Crown had learned or of the TPSPS's exculpatory findings regarding the Officers' conduct. Any attempt made by Ms. Alyea to alert the Court to the TPSPS findings or the substance of the report fell far below what was required in the circumstances. The report was not properly be fore the Court nor had it been properly disclosed to counsel for Mr. Singh.</P>
<P>27. On December 12, 2013, the Court of Appeal released its judgment, in which it granted the appellant's stay application. The Court condemned the &ldquo;egregious nature of the police misconduct,&rdquo; which it equated with &ldquo;torture.&rdquo; It found that the alleged abusive interrogation techniques were &ldquo;calculated, prolonged and skilfully choreographed.&rdquo; The Court stated that Crown counsel was unable to provide any details of the results of the TPSPS investigation. The Court adverted several times to the fact that the Defence's allegations were uncontradicted or uncontested by the Crown. The Court found the case for a stay more compelling because the allegations of &ldquo;serious criminal conduct&rdquo; by the police had gone unchallenged.</P>
<P>28. The Court of Appeal's judgment was also widely reported in the mainstream media and on the internet. Articles about the case repeated Singh's and Maharaj's false and defamatory allegations, and condemned the Officers' behaviour.</P>
<P>29. Following the Court of Appeal judgment, the SIU re-opened their investigation. Maharaj agreed to be interviewed. The investigators reviewed all of the records and obtained opinion evidence. That investigation concluded that Maharaj's rib injury post-dated the time of arrest, and that his physical demeanour in the videotaped statement was inconsistent with his having sustained any rib injury at the time of arrest (during his video-recorded interview Maharaj is moving about in a way that would not have been possible had he suffered the cracked rib injury he alleged he had suffered at the hands of the Officers). The SIU found that the allegations by Maharaj were not substantiated.</P>
<P>30. Also following the Court of Appeal judgment, the Chief of the Toronto Police Service asked the Ontario Provincial Police (<BOLD>&ldquo;OPP&rdquo;</BOLD>) to conduct an independent review of the TPSPS investigation. The OPP review was conducted by an experienced, high-ranking investigator. On April 9, 2015, the OPP investigator concluded the TPSPS review had been thorough and she had no reason to refute its conclusions that the allegations of police misconduct were unsubstantiated.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>The Appellants Commence an Action Against the Attorney General of Ontario</EM></TI>
<P>31. As alleged in the Appellants' Statement of Claim, several months after the Court of Appeal released its judgment, the Officers retained counsel. Counsel had the opportunity to review the entire record and listen to the audio of the oral arguments that were made in the Court of Appeal.</P>
<P>32. After due consideration, counsel formed a legal opinion that they communicated to the Officers: the conduct of the Respondent may be tortious, and a novel claim in negligence and misfeasance in a public office could be pursued. It was only at this point that the Officers discovered that there was a viable claim, albeit a novel one.</P>
<P>33. The Appellants issued their Claim on June 22, 2016. In it, they claim as against the Attorney General damages for negligence and misfeasance in a public office.</P>
<P>34. In particular, the Claim alleges that Crown Attorneys owe a duty of care to investigating police officers and that this duty was breached through the conduct of Ms. Cressman, Ms. Alyea, and their superiors. The Claim also alleges that Ms. Cressman, Ms. Alyea and their superiors engaged in deliberate and unlawful conduct that they knew to be inconsistent with their professional obligations, and that they did so in bad faith, with the knowledge that this misconduct would likely injure the Officers.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>The Attorney General's Motion to Strike</EM></TI>
<P>35. The Attorney General brought a motion to strike the Claim pursuant to Rules 21 and 25 on the basis that:
<P1>(a) The action is statute-barred because the limitation period has expired: the Plaintiffs failed to commence it within two years of discovering the material facts on which the Claim is based. In particular, the Plaintiffs were aware of the material facts giving rise to their claim based on the conduct of Ms. Cressman by at least July 2012. The Plaintiffs were aware of the material facts giving rise to their claim based on the conduct of Ms. Alyea by at least December 12, 2013;</P1>
<P1>(b) The claims in negligence and misfeasance are not tenable at law. As Crown Attorneys do not owe a duty of care to investigating police officers, it is plain and obvious that the claim does not disclose a reasonable cause of action in negligence and has no reasonable prospect of success. As the Attorney General states in its factum, &ldquo;[Aside from malicious prosecution,] no other action in tort is available against a Crown Attorney&rdquo;; and</P1>
<P1>(c) The claim in misfeasance is frivolous and vexations, as it did not provide full particulars to support this cause of action.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>The Decisions of the Motions Judge</EM></TI>
<P>36. Stinson J. bifurcated the motion, and heard arguments on the limitation issue first. On January 4, 2017, Stinson J. dismissed the Attorney General's motion to strike on the basis of the limitation period argument by finding, <EM>inter alia</EM>: due to the legal and factual complexities of the case, it was not plain and obvious that the limitation issue would be decided against the Plaintiffs and the issue should only be determined after a complete factual context is placed before the Court.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Clark v. Ontario (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 43</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD><UNDER>Appellants' Book of Authorities</UNDER> (&ldquo;<UNDER>BOA</UNDER>&rdquo;). Tab 1.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>37. <UNDER>The Respondent has been granted leave to appeal Stinson J.'s decision on the limitation period issue, and that appeal has now been joined with this appeal on the negligence issue.</UNDER></P>
<P>38. On June 13, 2017, Stinson J. released his decision on the second part of the Attorney General's motion, i.e. to strike the Appellants' claim for no reasonable cause of action with respect to the claims of negligence and misfeasance in a public office.</P>
<P>39. In regard to both claims, Stinson J. held that it was not plain and obvious that Crown Attorneys have absolute immunity from civil claims, other than claims for malicious prosecution and intentional non-disclosure of exculpatory evidence. He therefore declined to strike the Officers' Claim on the basis of common-law Crown Attorney immunity.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Clark v. Ontario (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 3683</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Clark</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 77, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>40. In regard to the claim of misfeasance, Stinson J. held that the Appellants had pleaded the essential elements of the tort, and that a determination of whether the Crown Attorneys acted within the scope of their duties and did not breach any legal obligations is a matter properly determined at trial. He therefore declined to strike the claim of misfeasance.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM> at paras. 149-150, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>41. <UNDER>The Attorney General has been granted leave to appeal Stinson J.'s decision in regard to misfeasance, and that appeal has now been joined with this appeal on the negligence issue.</UNDER></P>
<P>42. In regard to the claim in negligence, Stinson J. conducted an analysis for recognizing a new private-law duty of care according to the test set out in <CASEREF><SOC>Anns v. Merton London Borough Council</SOC></CASEREF> and followed by the Supreme Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Cooper v. Hobart</SOC></CASEREF>. He found that a relationship of proximity could arise from the fact that significant interests of the Plaintiffs are engaged when they are subject to misconduct allegations on <EM>Charter</EM> motions that only Crown Attorneys are in a position to defend against. Stinson J. therefore held that it is not plain and obvious that there is no <EM>prima facie</EM> duty of care owed by trial Crown Attorneys to police officers to take reasonable care in the course of investigating and defending <EM>Charter</EM> motions alleging serious misconduct by police officers.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM> at para. 104, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>43. At the second stage of the <EM>Anns</EM> test, Stinson J. considered whether there were any policy concerns that would negate the <EM>prima facie</EM> duty of care, and made the following findings:
<P1>(a) There is no absolute requirement for an evidentiary record to assess competing policy arguments;</P1>
<P1>(b) Recognizing a duty of care in these circumstances <UNDER>would</UNDER> interfere with Crown Attorneys' ability to do their jobs by diverting them from their basic and primary responsibilities;</P1>
<P1>(c) It would alter what should be a cooperative relationship between the police and Crown Attorneys to a <UNDER>potentially</UNDER> adversarial one;</P1>
<P1>(d) It would carry the <UNDER>risk</UNDER> of increased time spent litigating criminal cases for non-core reasons; and</P1>
<P1>(e) There are alternative and more proper forums for determination of allegations of police misconduct, including police complaints processes, police disciplinary tribunals and civil actions.</P1></P>
<P>44. On the basis of these findings, Stinson J. concluded that there were important policy reasons to negate the <EM>prima facie</EM> duty of care Crown Attorneys owe to investigating police officers.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM> at paras. 29, 113, 134&ndash;137, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>45. <UNDER>On February 21, 2018, the Divisional Court issued its decision on appeal in the parallel case,</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Attorney General of Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> <UNDER>(the &ldquo;<EM>Smith Appeal</EM>&rdquo;). The Court in that case held that common-law prosecutorial immunity shielded Crown Attorneys from civil liability for simple negligence in the provision of legal advice to police officers. The Appellants in the case at bar address the Court's decision in the <EM>Smith Appeal</EM> and its relevance to this case below.</UNDER></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">III. ISSUES AND THE LAW</TI>
<P>46. The sole issue to be determined in this appeal is whether Stinson J. made errors of law and/or mixed fact and law in striking the Appellants' claim in negligence.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>The Motions Judge Erred by Ruling Without an Evidentiary Record</EM></TI>
<P>47. The Supreme Court has stated that the test applicable to a motion to strike is that,
<QUOTE><P>[I]t is plain and obvious, assuming the facts pleaded to be true, that the pleading discloses no reasonable cause of action.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2011 SCC 42</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Imperial Tobacco</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 17, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 3.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>48. A motion to strike is designed to weed out claims that are &ldquo;hopeless,&rdquo; &ldquo;certain to fail,&rdquo; or &ldquo;could not possibly succeed.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD><EM>Imperial Tobacco</EM> at para. 19;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Paton Estate v. Ontario Lottery and Gaming Commission</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 458</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Paton Estate</EM>&rdquo;) at paras. 2 and 48;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Addison Chevrolet Buick GMC Ltd. v. General Motors of Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 324</CITE><PARANUM>23</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>; <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tabs 3, 4 and 5.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>49. The motion to strike is a tool that must be used with care. This is especially the case where the Court considers novel claims. In these cases, courts must be generous and err on the side of permitting the novel but arguable claim to proceed to trial.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Imperial Tobacco</EM> at para. 21; <EM>Paton Estate</EM> at paras. 11-12, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tabs 3 and 4.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>50. When claimants assert a novel duty of care in negligence claims, any policy concerns that might negate or limit that duty of care must be adequately demonstrated. As the Supreme Court has stated, &ldquo;policy concerns raised against imposing a duty of care <UNDER>must be more than speculative; a real potential for negative consequences must be apparent.</UNDER>&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hill v. Hamilton-Wentworth Regional Police Services Board</SOC><CITE>2007 SCC 41</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Hill</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 48;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Fullowka v. Pinkerton's of Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2010 SCC 5</CITE><PARANUM>57</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Fullowka</EM>&rdquo;) (emphasis added), <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tabs 6 and 7.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>51. For that reason, this Honourable Court has repeatedly emphasized that courts should not strike claims on the basis of policy considerations without an evidentiary record. Again, this is especially the case where a novel claim is asserted. With out an evidentiary record, a court cannot analyze the strengths and weaknesses of competing policy arguments, and cannot confidently make judgments about legal and policy issues raised by the parties. To attempt to apply policy considerations without the benefit of a factual record is contrary to the principles on which case law has been understood to develop.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Haskett v. Equifax Canada Inc.</SOC><CITE>[2003] O.J. No. 771</CITE><COURTJUR>ONCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Haskett</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 52; <EM>Paton Estate</EM> at paras. 35-36 and 48;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Anger v. Berkshire Investment Group Inc.</SOC><CITE>[2001] O.J. No. 379</CITE><COURTJUR>ONCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at para. 15;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Rausch v. Pickering (City)</SOC><CITE>2013 ONCA 740</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Rausch</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 74; <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tabs 8, 4, 9 and 10.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>52. Stinson J. noted that courts have conducted evaluations of policy arguments without an evidentiary record in the context of claims against Crown Attorneys, citing the cases of <CASEREF><SOC>Nelles v. Ontario, Proulx v. Quebec (Attorney General)</SOC></CASEREF>, <CASEREF><SOC>Miazga v. Kvello Estate</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia (Attorney General)</SOC></CASEREF> as instances where the Supreme Court has engaged in this analysis. He concluded that, &ldquo;an evidentiary record is not necessarily a prerequisite to evaluating policy considerations relevant to imposing liability.&rdquo; He further held that, since courts deal with the conduct of and relationships between Crown Attorneys and police on a daily basis, they are better equipped to assess policy issues involving these justice system participants than in other, unusual contexts. He therefore engaged in an analysis of policy considerations in the case at bar without the benefit of any evidence and even without a statement of defence having been filed.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM> at para. 133, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>53. With respect, all of the cases Stinson J. cited are distinguishable from the case at bar. All of these cases involved accused persons in criminal proceedings bringing claims against prosecutors. None of them involved the relationship between Crown Attorneys and investigating police officers and a possible duty of care owed by Crown Attorneys to those police. For that reason, as will be further detailed below, the policy considerations applying to the duty of care in the case at bar are different from those in the malicious prosecution trilogy and <EM>Henry</EM>. It was inappropriate and purely speculative for Stinson J. to &ldquo;piggy-back&rdquo; policy concerns from the context of claims by accused persons to the present context.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bridgmount Development v. Tarion Warranty Corp.</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 6190</CITE><PARANUM>32-33</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 11.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>54. Moreover, the fact that courts deal with justice system participants such as Crown Attorneys and investigating police on a daily basis does not obviate the need for evidence to assess policy arguments. It is the nature of the claim, and not the frequency with which certain litigants appear before courts, that dictates the need for a factual record to understand competing policy considerations.</P>
<P>55. It is undeniable that the case at bar involves a novel claim&mdash;asserting a new kind of right and a new duty of care&mdash;and unusual circumstances. As Mathieson J. correctly noted in <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>The Crown successfully sought leave to appeal this decision to the Divisional Court (<CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 2854</CITE></CASEREF>). <UNDER>The Divisional Court issued its decision, 2018 ONSC 993, on February 21, 2018. The Appellants address the Divisional Court's decision below.</UNDER></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>Certainly, aspects of the relationship between these two parts of the criminal justice system have previously been considered, but not sufficiently to strike out this claim at the pleadings stage.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 7222</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Smith</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 11, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 12.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>56. In considering whether or not common-law immunity would bar a crossclaim by police against Crown Attorneys for the negligent provision of legal advice, Mathieson J. remarked on the inapplicability of the cases Stinson J. mentions (i.e. the malicious prosecution trilogy and <EM>Henry</EM>) to the context of relations between Crown Attorneys and police:
<QUOTE><P><UNDER>The extensive body of law about common law immunity simply does not focus on lawsuits by the police against Crown Attorneys. The <EM>Nelles</EM> trilogy and related cases all have, as a common starting point, a member of the public aggrieved by the impact of the justice system upon him or her who wishes to claim relief outside the criminal justice system.</UNDER> <EM>Proulx</EM> spoke of the individuals &ldquo;caught up in the justice system&rdquo;: at para. 4. <EM>Miazga</EM> spoke of the &ldquo;victims of a clear miscarriage of justice&rdquo;: at para. 2. This forms part of the analysis in each of the key cases. In <EM>Nelles</EM>, Lamer J. had regard, in his analysis, for the victim of the alleged malicious prosecution who wished to bring a civil claim: at para. 50. The rationale based on <CASEREF><SOC>Roncarelli v. Duplessis</SOC></CASEREF> employed by McIntyre J. in <EM>Nelles</EM> and emphasized by Charron J. in <EM>Miazga</EM> is also fundamentally focused on responsibilities to members of the public.</P>
<P>As recently confirmed by the Supreme Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Hinse v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC></CASEREF>... the high threshold in the <EM>Nelles</EM> trilogy flows from the &ldquo;choice made to preserve a balance between the right of individual citizens to be free from groundless criminal prosecutions and the public interest in the effective and uninhibited prosecution of criminal wrongdoing&rdquo;... <UNDER>The focus of these cases is the rights of individual citizens, not the rights of police</UNDER>.</P>
<P>Thus, the common law immunity grounded in the trilogy and related cases has been recognized <UNDER>only within the context of civil claims by members of the public. I am not prepared, at this preliminary stage, to divorce common law immunity from that context</UNDER>...</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Smith</EM> at paras. 136&ndash;138 (emphasis added), <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 12.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>57. In contrast to Stinson J., Mathieson J. decided not to import the policy concerns from those cases to analyze potential policy issues in the context of the relationship between Crown Attorneys and police, which, she noted, is &ldquo;sophisticated, complex and of critical importance to the justice system.&rdquo; Mathieson J. correctly observed that &ldquo;a more comprehensive factual record is needed to properly consider this novel claim,&rdquo; and held that it was not plain and obvious that the claim should be struck in the absence of such a record.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Smith</EM> at paras. 170&ndash;173, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 12.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>58. Stinson J. said that the common elements to cases where courts found an evidentiary record was required to evaluate policy arguments were, &ldquo;the factual relationship underlying the alleged duty of care was specific and unusual,&rdquo; and there was a &ldquo;novel situation and relationship.&rdquo; The case at bar meets all of these criteria. Aside from <EM>Smith</EM>, there are no reported cases of investigating police officers claiming a duty of care from Crown Attorneys. The facts of the case at bar are unusual and the claim is novel. The policy concerns applying to the relationship between the parties has not been properly assessed with a comprehensive evidentiary record.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM> at para. 121; see</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Vogler v. Lemieux</SOC><CITE>2014 ONCA 825</CITE><PARANUM>4</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>; <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tabs 2 and 13.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>59. In the absence of an evidentiary record, Stinson J.'s policy analysis was purely speculative. His Honour's importation of a policy analysis from another context to the case at bar was unfair to the Appellants. No &ldquo;real potential for negative consequences&rdquo; was demonstrated in the context of the Appellants' Claim. For these reasons, Stinson J. erred in law by striking the Appellants' claim in negligence at the second stage of the <EM>Anns</EM> test.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>The Motions Judge's Speculative Policy Analysis Was Incorrect</EM></TI>
<P>60. Stinson J.'s speculative policy analysis, importing concerns from the context of the malicious prosecution trilogy and <EM>Henry</EM> without an evidentiary record and applying them to a novel claim, was incorrect. Stinson J. erred in law by making conclusions on policy considerations that were findings of mixed fact and law, in the absence a factual basis.</P>
<BLOCK4><N>(a)</N><TI>There is No Concern of Indeterminate Liability</TI>
<P>61. Stinson J. predicted that &ldquo;the type of liability the officers are asking the court to impose would create a whole new class of potential claimants.&rdquo; This concern seems to echo the policy consideration of indeterminate liability or the potential for &ldquo;an avalanche of interlocutory civil proceedings and civil trials&rdquo; if courts were to recognize the novel duty of care that is proposed. This concern is not warranted in the circumstances here.</P>
<P>62. The class of potential claimants is clearly circumscribed: it is limited to investigating police officers on a particular case. As an accused could only allege the kind of misconduct at issue against these particular officers, it is to them alone that Crown prosecutors assume a duty to manage the risks of potential reputational harm. Since the class of persons to whom the duty would be owed would be within the knowledge and control of the Crown Attorneys, concerns of indeterminate liability do not arise.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Haskett</EM> at para. 45; <EM>Rausch</EM> at para. 81; <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tabs 8 and 10.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>63. As the absence of any reported cases demonstrates, it is also rare that an accused alleges the type of serious misconduct that led to the harm in the case at bar. Finally, the class of potential claimants would be limited by the requirement of establishing compensable injury caused by prosecutors' negligence in performing their duties.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Further concerns about potentially overbroad liability could be addressed through the formulation of the standard of care for the reasonably prudent prosecutor. See <EM>Rausch</EM> at paras. 23 and 80; <EM>Fullowka</EM> at para. 73; and <CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>2015 SCC 24</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Henry</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 88. As presented below, Crown Attorneys have duties not only to cause further investigation of allegations of serious police misconduct when it impinges on the prosecution of a case, but also <UNDER>to present</UNDER> all relevant evidence that is necessary to the narrative to the trier of fact in order to effectively prosecute a case. What is required from a prosecutor to meet the standard of care for the proposed duty in this case would parallel the requirement from <EM>Henry</EM>: the Crown would be liable if it failed to properly investigate and present information that would exculpate investigating officers from allegations of serious misconduct. The evidentiary burden for such liability could also parallel that set out by the Court in <EM>Henry</EM>: i.e. the claimant would have to prove that prosecutors were actually in possession of the information and failed to put it before the Court, or that the prosecutors were put on notice of the existence of the information and failed to obtain it. (See <EM>Henry</EM> at paras. 31 and 86). In the case at bar, the prosecutors were in possession of the information and were put on notice of the Crown Attorneys' mistakes, but failed to present the evidence to the Court.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Hill</EM> at para. 60;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Williams v. Toronto</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 666</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Williams</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 62; <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tabs 6 and 14.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>(b)</N><TI>Recognizing a Duty of Care Would Not Divert Crown Attorneys from Their Primary Duties</TI>
<P>64. Stinson J. reasoned that recognizing a duty of care in the circumstances of this case would divert prosecutors from their primary duties of assessing whether there are reasonable and probable grounds to prosecute a case, deciding whether it is in the public interest to do so, and protecting and respecting the rights of the accused. It would also add extraneous concerns of protecting police officers' reputations to the Crown Attorneys' reasons for litigating cases and would cause &ldquo;conflict and disruption&rdquo; in the relationship between prosecutors and police.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM> at paras 134-135, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 1.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>65. First, without the benefit of a full evidentiary record for this novel claim, it is not clear how Stinson J. was able to assess the risk or potential for the conflict of duties he warns about. The concerns he lists seem to be lifted from the context of cases like <EM>Henry</EM> and <CASEREF><SOC>Syl Apps Secure Treatment Centre v. B.D.</SOC></CASEREF>, and the malicious prosecution trilogy. But, in those cases there was an <UNDER>inherently adversarial</UNDER> relationship between the parties: in <EM>Henry</EM> and the trilogy, the relationship was between prosecutors and accused persons; in <EM>Syl Apps</EM>, the relationship was between Children's Aid Societies and the parents of children who had been removed from their homes. By contrast, the relationship between Crown Attorneys and investigating police is complimentary: while they perform separate functions, they are both key players in the administration of justice and must cooperate and rely on each other.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Syl Apps Secure Treatment Centre v. B.D.</SOC><CITE>2007 SCC 38</CITE><PARANUM>42</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 15.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>66. Second, the kind of prosecutorial negligence at issue in this case does not relate to the exercise of &ldquo;core&rdquo; prosecutorial discretion&mdash;&ldquo;ultimate&rdquo; decisions such as whether a prosecution should be brought, continued or ceased; whether it is in the public interest to prosecute a case; and protecting or respecting the rights of the accused. It also does not relate to routine tactical decisions at trial. The Plaintiffs allege that Crown Attorneys negligently failed to carry out their statutory duties: they failed to investigate and challenge allegations of egregious <EM>Charter</EM> violations, and they failed to put before the Court all relevant facts, thereby undercutting the effective prosecution of a crime. The Crown Attorneys knew, or should have known, that these failures would cause the Plaintiffs serious harm <UNDER>and</UNDER> would undermine the search for truth and the administration of justice.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Miazga v. Kvello Estate</SOC><CITE>2009 SCC 51</CITE><PARANUM>45</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>2015 SCC 24</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Henry</EM>&rdquo;) at paras. 61-62; <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tabs 16 and 17.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>67. Third, rather than diverting Crown Attorneys from their duties, recognizing the proposed duty of care to investigating police officers and agencies would <UNDER>harmonize</UNDER> with and buttress Crown Attorneys' duties. This is illustrated by attending to Crown Attorneys' duties and to the relationship between Crown Attorneys and investigating police.</P>
<P>68. As the Appellants pointed out to the motions judge,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Stinson J. adverted to this argument in his decision at <EM>Clark</EM>, para. 111.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the relevant statutes, Crown policies and case law set out the duties of Crown Attorneys in the prosecution of a case. These include:
<P1>(a) <UNDER>The duty to cause charges to be further investigated, and additional evidence to be collected</UNDER>, and further information that is likely to shed light on what did or did not happen to be provided, with the assistance of police, <UNDER>so that prosecutions may not fail for want of proof</UNDER>;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>This duty on Crown Attorneys parallels police officers' duty of reinvestigation when new information emerges in a case. As the Supreme Court said in <EM>Hill</EM>, &ldquo;Reasonable prudence may require [the police] to re-examine their prior theories of the case, to test the credibility of new evidence and to engage in further investigation provoked by the new evidence&rdquo; (<EM>Hill</EM> at para. 84).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(b) <UNDER>To see that all available legal proof of the facts is presented before the court</UNDER> for a determination on the merits, and that this is done fairly, but also firmly and pressed to its legitimate strength;</P1>
<P1>(c) To be firm while being fair in prosecuting the accused <UNDER>so that the Court will not be duped by defences which are not thoroughly examined</UNDER> in Court. While the criminal law leaves to the Crown Attorney many discretions as to whom and what to prosecute, and the conduct of the Crown's case, it &ldquo;does not equate a good and fair Crown Attorney with a weak lawyer&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>(d) <UNDER>To call all material witnesses essential to the unfolding of the narrative</UNDER> of events on which the Crown's case is based, so that the elements of the offence are properly proved and <UNDER>the Crown does not risk losing its case or obtaining an unreasonable verdict that is vulnerable on appeal;</UNDER><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>As the Alberta Court of Appeal said in <CASEREF><SOC>R v. L.L.</SOC><CITE>2015 ABCA 222</CITE></CASEREF>, the Crown's duty to lay before the jury all material facts includes calling important, but possibly unreliable witnesses to rebut the strong testimony of the opposing party. The prosecution is not required to &ldquo;throw in the towel&rdquo; when it encounters such obstacles (paras. 14-15), <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 17.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(e) <UNDER>To see to it that every material point is made which supports the prosecution's case or destroys the case put forward for the defence</UNDER>. The prosecutor must present the case against the prisoner relentlessly, but with scrupulous fairness.</P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. C. 49, ss. 11(a), (b); Crown Policy Manual, &ldquo;Role of the Crown&mdash;Preamble to the Crown Policy Manual&rdquo; and &ldquo;Police: Relationship with Crown Counsel&rdquo;;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. B.(M.)</SOC><CITE>2006 ONCJ 526</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>B.(M.)</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 202;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Boucher</SOC><CITE>[1955] S.C.R. 16</CITE></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Regina v. Lalonde</SOC><CITE>[1972] 1 O.R. 376</CITE><PARANUM>7</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Cook</SOC><CITE>[1997] S.C.J. No. 22</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at paras. 23, 31;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Hillis</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 451</CITE><PARANUM>42-43</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Bain</SOC><CITE>[1992] 1 S.C.R. 91</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(emphases added); <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tabs 29, 18, 19, 20, 21, 22, and 23.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>69. As in <EM>Hill, Rausch</EM> and <EM>Williams</EM>, imposing a duty of care on prosecutors to investigating officers would <UNDER>complement</UNDER>&mdash;not conflict with&mdash;prosecutors' statutory duties to the general public and would have positive policy ramifications. The duty of care to investigating officers is <UNDER>pursuant</UNDER> to prosecutors' duties to the public: to effectively prosecute crime, to cause new charges or allegations to be thoroughly investigated, and to ensure all relevant evidence is put before the court in support of a conviction. Obligating prosecutors to investigate allegations of serious police misconduct, and to challenge those allegations in court, <UNDER>enhances</UNDER> the Crown's ability to prosecute a case and uphold the proper administration of justice. Investigating officers <UNDER>share</UNDER> the public's interest in seeing Crown prosecutors reasonably and diligently perform their functions, including investigating allegations thoroughly, presenting all relevant evidence, and advocating forcefully.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Hill</EM> at paras. 36, 41&ndash;43; <EM>Rausch</EM> at paras. 67&ndash;71; <EM>Williams</EM> at paras. 67 and 69; <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tabs 6, 10, 14.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>70. The proposed duty of care in this case is co-extensive with Crown Attorneys' duties pursuant to statute, case law and their own policy manual. To require Crown Attorneys to exercise due care towards investigating police officers in the face of allegations of egregious misconduct is to require them to abide by their own policies. As this Honourable Court has said, where the complaint is that the Respondent failed to follow its own policies, the Respondent cannot claim that following its own policies would &ldquo;pose a real potential for negative policy consequences.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Heaslip Estate v. Mansfield Ski Club Inc.</SOC><CITE>96 O.R. (3d) 401</CITE><COURTJUR>ONCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at para. 28; <EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM>, s. 11(a) and (b); Crown Policy Manual, &ldquo;Police: Relationship with Crown Counsel&rdquo;; <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tabs 24 and 29.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>71. In <EM>Smith</EM>, Mathieson J. was alive to this complimentary relationship between the duties of Crown Attorneys and the proposed duty of care regarding the provision of legal advice:
<QUOTE><P>[H]ow would the availability of a tort claim for negligent legal advice interfere with the relationship between these two important parts of the criminal justice system? Why is it inconsistent with independence? The provision of competent independent legal advice to the police would, it seems to me, serve the administration of justice. How would legal responsibility for negligent advice interfere?</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Smith</EM> at para. 169, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 12.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>72. Because there was no evidentiary record substantiating the policy argument that the recognition of the proposed duty of care would have a chilling effect on Crown Attorneys and would undermine the administration of justice, Mathieson J. refused to strike the claim. By contrast, Stinson J. struck the Appellants' negligence claim on the basis of purely speculative policy arguments that run contrary to Crown Attorneys' recognized duties.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Smith</EM> at paras. 172-173, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 12.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>73. While Stinson J.'s policy concerns were purely speculative, the facts underlying this action vividly demonstrate the <UNDER>actual</UNDER> consequences of prosecutorial negligence. The Crown Attorneys' failure to thoroughly investigate the false and unsubstantiated allegations of egregious misconduct, and failure to adduce available evidence to challenge the allegations, resulted in irreparable harm to the Officers' reputations. It also tarnished the reputation of the police force. The charges against Maharaj were stayed. The conviction of Singh was overturned. The administration of justice was brought into disrepute. Had the Crown Attorneys exercised due car e to the Officers in their investigations and prosecution, it would have increased the probability that the guilty were convicted and the convictions affirmed. The administration of justice would have been served, and the unfortunate results of this prosecution could have been avoided.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Hill</EM> at para. 43, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 6.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>(c)</N><TI>Recognizing a Duty of Care Would Not Alter the Relationship Between Crown Attorneys and Investigative Police</TI>
<P>74. Stinson J. was incorrect in his speculation that recognizing a duty of care &ldquo;would alter what should be a co-operative relationship between the police and Crown Attorneys into a potentially adversarial one.&rdquo; The case at bar illustrates the converse: it is the negligence of Crown Attorneys and the failure to recognize a duty of care to investigating police that has altered the co operative relationship to an adversarial one.</P>
<P>75. There is a special relationship&mdash;one of proximity&mdash;between Crown Attorneys and investigating police officers. Case law, Crown policy manuals and independent reports recognize that, while the roles of the Crown and the police are separate and distinct&mdash;with the police primarily in an investigative role, and the Crown in a prosecutorial role&mdash;the two must be able to work together closely and rely on each other in order to enforce criminal laws effectively. The close cooperation and collaboration between the two is essential for the effective administration of justice.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. McNeil</SOC><CITE>2009 SCC 3</CITE><PARANUM>22-23</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Regan</SOC><CITE>[2002] S.C.J. No. 14</CITE><PARANUM>62 and 66</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>; <EM>B.(M.)</EM> at para. 197; Crown Policy Manual, &ldquo;Police: Relationship with Crown Counsel&rdquo;; <EM>2008 Report of the Review of Large and Complex Criminal Case Procedures</EM> at Chapter 3, Section C, p. 25; <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tabs 25, 26, 18, 29 and 30.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>76. If Crown Attorneys fail to investigate and challenge evidence that investigating police intentionally committed egregious <EM>Charter</EM> violations, the relationship of trust and mutual reliance between these players in the justice system will be broken. Police officers may be reluctant to collaborate with Crown Attorneys who do not fulfil their roles and whom they do not trust.</P>
<P>77. In any event, it is not clear precisely what the repercussions of failing to recognize a duty of care owed by Crown Attorneys to investigating officers would be, as there is no factual record. It was inappropriate for Stinson J. to speculate on the effects such a duty would have on the relationship between the parties. As Mathieson J. remarked on the subject of this relationship in <EM>Smith</EM>,
<QUOTE><P>[I]t has become apparent to me that a more comprehensive factual record is needed to properly consider this novel claim. Much of what was discussed in the <EM>Cooper-Anns</EM> analysis in <CASEREF><SOC>Hill v. Hamilton-Wentworth Regional Police Services Board</SOC></CASEREF> arose from a full record. In <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Regan</SOC></CASEREF>, there was evidence from a number of witnesses about the relevant Crown practices. The facts about the relationship between the police and Crown Attorneys in cases and in these reports are not a proper basis to strike out a claim under Rule 21(1)(b) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>.</P>
<P>The submissions regarding the <EM>Cooper-Anns</EM> test have raised important issues regarding the relationship between the police and Crown Attorneys, including policy issues... A motion for summary judgment or trial is more appropriate in this case.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Smith</EM> at paras. 171-172, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 12.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>78. In addition, the reputational interests of investigating officers in the case at bar are not &ldquo;extraneous&rdquo; to the duties of Crown Attorneys. The failure of the underlying prosecution in this case resulted directly from allegations of police abuse and <EM>Charter</EM> violations that amounted to &ldquo;torture.&rdquo; It is not difficult to see how a failure to challenge such allegations will redound to undermine prosecutions and bring the administration of justice into disrepute in both the courts and the minds of the public: this Honourable Court stated as much in the underlying appeal. Crown Attorneys have analogous reputational interests in not being accused of intentionally tampering with or suppressing evidence in the manner addressed in <EM>Henry</EM>.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R v. Singh</SOC><CITE>2013 ONCA 750</CITE><PARANUM>44 and 46</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>; <EM>Henry</EM> at para. 69; <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tabs 27 and 17.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>79. The reputational integrity of investigating police is essential to public confidence in the administration of justice. The failure to challenge such outrageous allegations and to impose a duty of care on Crown Attorneys would be an invitation to every accused to allege police misconduct in the hope that the prosecutors will negligently fail to investigate and challenge them.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>(d)</N><TI>Alternative Remedies Are Inadequate and Inappropriate</TI>
<P>80. Stinson J. incorrectly found that internal police complaints processes and tribunals are adequate and more proper forums for the determination of allegations of police misconduct.</P>
<P>81. Internal complaints processes cannot adequately remedy the wrong done to the Officers in this case. For one thing, the findings of an internal administrative process simply do not have the same force&mdash;either in the court system or in the minds of the public&mdash;as a pronouncement from the highest Court in the province that these Officers committed &ldquo;torture&rdquo; with &ldquo;prolonged and grave&rdquo; beatings that were in &ldquo;flagrant breach&rdquo; of the <EM>Charter</EM>.</P>
<P>82. The case at bar is a glaring example of the devaluation of administrative decisions. The Officers presented Crown Attorneys with the results of internal police investigations that exculpated them from the alleged misconduct. However, even the Crown Attorneys did not accord the results of these investigations sufficient weight to present them to the Court.</P>
<P>83. Finally, as internal police investigations and administrative procedures cannot provide remedies in damages, they are not an adequate alternative to recognizing a cause of action in negligence. To deny a remedy in tort for the damages the Officers have suffered would be to deny justice.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Rausch</EM> at paras. 61, 64-65; <EM>Haskett</EM> at para. 50;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Nelles v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[1989] S.C.J. No. 86</CITE><PARANUM>53-54</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>; <EM>Hill</EM> at para. 35; <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tabs 10, 8, 28 and 6.</BOLD></P1></P>
<BLOCK5><TI><UNDER><EM>The Divisional Court Decision in the</EM> Smith Appeal</UNDER></TI>
<P>84. <UNDER>The Divisional Court overturned Matheson J.'s decision in <EM>Smith</EM>. It is the Appellant's position that the case is distinguishable on the factual matrix of that case or, alternatively, the decision is wrong. In the <EM>Smith Appeal</EM>, the Divisional Court concluded that immunity from negligence for Crown prosecutors was based on two policy concerns discussed in the malicious prosecution trilogy and <EM>Henry</EM>. The Court found that the same policy concerns shielded the Crown from negligence claims when providing legal advice to police officers regarding the conduct of a police investigation.</UNDER>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Attorney General of Ontario</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 993</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Smith Appeal</EM>&rdquo;) at paras. 31&ndash;33.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><TI><UNDER><EM>The Divisional Court Decision in the</EM> Smith Appeal <EM>is Incorrect and Distinguishable</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>85. <UNDER>Neither Mathieson J. in <EM>Smith</EM> nor Stinson J. in this case found that a claim in negligence against Crown Attorneys brought by police in certain circumstances <EM>would</EM> succeed. Nor did they find that Crown Attorneys necessarily owed a duty of care to police officers. Instead, both judges found that, in the circumstances of their respective cases&mdash;which both involve <EM>novel</EM> claims&mdash;a claim in negligence was not absolutely precluded by existing case law. This was be cause prior cases that considered claims of negligence against Crown prosecutors arose in very different contexts.</UNDER></P>
<P>86. <UNDER>Contrary to the finding of the Divisional Court, there is no basis to conclude that, because Crown Attorneys may be diverted from their duties or engage in defensive lawyering if they were exposed to civil suits from accused persons, they would likewise be diverted or engage in defensive lawyering if they were liable to investigating police officers in specific situations. There was no evidence in <EM>Smith</EM> to support this conclusion. The Court did not engage in any analysis of <EM>how</EM> or <EM>why</EM> Crown Attorneys would be diverted from their duties or would engage in defensive lawyering. The Court did not explain how the potential for a conflict of duties in the context of the inherently adversarial relationship between the parties from cases like <EM>Nelles</EM> and <EM>Henry</EM> translates to the context of the relationship between police and Crown Attorneys. Instead. The Court based its conclusion, without any evidence, on the suppositions that there was a &ldquo;risk&rdquo; of diverting Crown Attorneys from their duties and exposing them to civil liability &ldquo;could&rdquo; lead to defensive lawyering.</UNDER></P>
<P>87. <UNDER>As argued above, the Court of Appeal has repeatedly stressed that courts should not strike claims&mdash;especially novel claims&mdash;on the basis of policy considerations without an evidentiary record. Similar speculative policy concerns were raised in <EM>Nelles</EM> and <EM>Henry</EM>, and yet the law evolved to encompass those novel claims. Policy determinations are conclusions of mixed fact and law. Without a factual basis, a court cannot properly analyze the strengths and weaknesses of competing policy arguments in novel contexts, and cannot confidently adjudicate the merits of a case. As there is no factual record at the pleadings stage, no &ldquo;real potential for negative consequences&rdquo; was demonstrated. The Divisional Court erred in law by basing a conclusion of mixed fact and law on law and unfounded speculation.</UNDER></P>
<P>88. <UNDER>Even if the Divisional Court in the <EM>Smith Appeal</EM> did not err in law, its conclusions are not applicable to the circumstances in the case at bar. The policy concerns underlying prosecutorial immunity do not, <EM>prima facie</EM>, militate against the police officers' claims in this case.</UNDER></P>
<P>89. <UNDER>As argued above, in this case. Crown Attorneys would not be diverted from their duties because the proposed duty of care <EM>harmonizes</EM> with and compliments their prosecutorial duties in the effective administration of justice. In other words. Crown Attorneys would be liable to officers where their breach of the duty of care is also a breach of their duties to prosecute fairly and effectively. Obligating Crown Attorneys to investigate allegations of serious police misconduct that could undermine an effective prosecution, and to challenge those allegations in court, enhances the Crown's ability to prosecute a case and accords with all of the duties ascribed to Crown Attorneys pursuant to statute, case law and Crown policy manuals. Indeed, the Court of Appeal's judgment in the underlying appeal perfectly illustrates how the Crown Attorneys' failure to take care with respect to the officers' reputations breached their prosecutorial duties. The Crown Attorneys' failure to adequately investigate and call available rebuttal evidence resulted in the charges being staved and the administration of justice being brought into disrepute.</UNDER></P>
<P>90. <UNDER>The imposition of the proposed duty of care would not have a chilling effect or cause prosecutors to act defensively. First, Crown prosecutors are indemnified from <EM>personal</EM> civil liability in the course of exercising their professional duties. This significantly reduces the prospect that their fear of civil liability will make them more defensive in prosecuting cases. Second, because the proposed duty to investigating police is co-extensive with its prosecutorial duties, as argued above, the Respondent cannot claim that following its own policies and performing its duties would &ldquo;pose a real potential for negative policy consequences.&rdquo; Third, because the proposed duty of care compliments their prosecutorial duties, the likelihood that similar situations will arise&mdash;where Crown Attorneys simply concede egregious, systemic and intentional <EM>Charter</EM> violations without doing an adequate investigation or presenting available rebuttal evidence&mdash;is extremely small. The lack of judicial precedent on this speaks to the rarity of these circumstances, and not to the supposed impregnability of prosecutorial immunity.</UNDER>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Hill</EM> at paras. 56-57, 59;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Heaslip Estate v. Mansfield Ski Club</SOC><CITE>96 O.R. (3d) 401</CITE><PARANUM>28</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>91. <UNDER>In any event, arguments about the &ldquo;risk&rdquo; of diversion from duties and the possibility of a chilling effect are purely speculative. To establish any likelihood of such consequences requires that this Claim be allowed to proceed so that an evidentiary record on these policy issues can be established. Additionally, there is no risk that prosecutors would feel compelled, for fear of a negligence claim, not to concede any <EM>Charter</EM> breach whatsoever even if it is patently obvious there was a <EM>Charter</EM> breach. The officer who engages in conduct which clearly establishes a Charter breach would have no claim against a Crown for conceding the same. The claim of negligence would only arise against the Crown who not only fails in her duties but also where it is established that, had she complied with her duties, the <EM>Charter</EM> claim would not have been conceded.</UNDER></P>
<P>92. <UNDER>Moreover, unlike the <EM>Smith Appeal</EM>, in the case at bar there is a countervailing policy consideration: the erosion of public confidence in the administration of justice. It is abundantly clear from the judgment of this Honourable Court in the underlying appeal that the alleged, uncontradicted and egregious misconduct eroded public confidence in the administration of justice:</UNDER>
<QUOTE><P><UNDER>In my opinion, this is one of those rare cases [in which the &ldquo;misconduct is so egregious that the mere fact of going forward in the light of it will be offensive&rdquo; because the &ldquo;exceedingly serious abuse could [bring] such continuing disrepute upon the administration of justice&rdquo;].</UNDER></P>
<P><UNDER>The conduct [alleged here] goes to the heart of the integrity of the justice system... This case calls for the imposition of a stay...</UNDER></P>
<P><UNDER>... What occurred here was the administration of a calculated, prolonged and skillfully choreographed investigative technique developed by these officers to secure evidence. This technique involved the deliberate and repeated use of intimidation, threats and violence, coupled with what can only be described as a systematic breach of the constitutional rights of detained persons...</UNDER></P>
<P><UNDER>... What took place here sullies the reputations of the many good officers in our country, whose work is integral to the safety and security of our society...</UNDER></P>
<P><UNDER>... Just as the fabrication of evidence by the police violates the integrity of the administration of justice, so too does the police misconduct in question here...</UNDER></P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Singh</SOC><CITE>2013 ONCA 750</CITE><PARANUM>39&ndash;49</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>93. <UNDER>The gravity of the alleged misconduct and its serious, negative effect on the public perception of the administration of justice and the integrity of the justice system distinguish the circumstances of this case from those in the <EM>Smith Appeal</EM>.</UNDER></P>
<P>94. <UNDER>Another characteristic that distinguishes this case from <EM>Smith</EM> is that the Appellants have alleged bad faith conduct on the part of the Attorney General in their Claim, and on this basis have also pleaded the tort of misfeasance in a public office. The Crown Attorneys' bad faith is not essential to the Appellants' negligence claim. However, an inference of bad faith can be drawn from the allegation that the Crown Attorneys acted outside the scope of their prosecutorial duties by failing to investigate the grave allegations made by the accused and to call available rebuttal evidence in both the underlying trial and appeal. Striking the negligence claim at this stage will not end the proceedings against the defendant. This also favours not striking the claim at this time.</UNDER></P>
<P>95. <UNDER>Finally, in the case at bar, the Appellants suffered serious harm <EM>personally</EM> as a result of the Crown Attorneys' misconduct. This harm included having their reputations grievously and irreparably damaged when this Honourable Court identified them personally as responsible for torture and egregious and flagrant breaches of the accused's <EM>Charter</EM> rights in the underlying appeal. The Appellants deserve some vindication and compensation for these damages, which cannot be compensated for through any alternative administrative process.</UNDER></P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Conclusion</EM></TI>
<P>96. This Honourable Court has repeatedly stated that courts should not assess policy considerations that would negate or limit a novel claim in tort in the absence of a comprehensive evidentiary record. The motions judge in this case erred in law by importing policy considerations from another context to make findings of mixed fact and law without a factual basis, and then incorrectly dismissed the Appellants' claim in negligence.</P>
<P>97. Stinson J.'s policy concerns were purely speculative and are outweighed by countervailing policy concerns. The Respondent did not demonstrate a <UNDER>real potential for negative policy consequences</UNDER>.</P>
<P>98. For these reasons, it was not plain and obvious that the Appellants' claim in negligence had no reasonable prospect of success, and it should be allowed to proceed to trial.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">IV. ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>99. For the above reasons, the Appellants seek:
<P1>(a) An Order dismissing the Respondents' motion to strike with costs;</P1>
<P1>(b) An Order granting the Appellants the costs of this Appeal;</P1>
<P1>(c) Such further and other relief as this Honourable Court deems just.</P1></P>
