<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. The appellants' appeal should be dismissed. Based on the jurisprudence of this Honourable Court and that of the Supreme Court of Canada in its quartet of decisions on Crown Attorney liability, the motion judge could come to no other reasonable conclusion than to dismiss the appellants' claim in negligence.</P>
<P>2. Policy considerations negating a private law duty of care can be, and routinely are, determined on preliminary motions without a full evidentiary record, even where such claims are &ldquo;novel&rdquo;. This is particularly so with respect to the liability of Crown Attorneys, where there is a substantial body of case law considering the policy implications of imposing a private law duty of care.</P>
<P>3. In this case, it is clear that imposing a private law duty of care against Crown Attorneys to an entirely new class of claimants&mdash;investigating police officers&mdash;would insert extraneous considerations into their determinations of whether and how to proceed with a prosecution. Further, it has the potential to invite a flood of litigation from police officers dissatisfied with how a Crown Attorney proceeds with respect to charges they have laid. This would divert Crown Attorneys from their important public duties. The Supreme Court has noted that such concerns are &ldquo;very real&rdquo;, not speculative, as alleged by the appellants. These considerations outweigh the fact that the appellants would be denied the ability to collect damages if a duty of care is not imposed.</P>
<P>4. While the motion judge ultimately came to the correct, and inevitable result, it is the Attorney General's position that he did err in failing to find that the existing jurisprudence regarding Crown Attorney liability was dispositive of the issues on the motion. Further, the motion judge erred by failing to consider the conflict between the alleged private law duty of care and the public duties owed by Crown Attorneys at the proximity stage of the <EM>Anns</EM> analysis. Had he done so, based on his findings with respect to the second stage of the <EM>Anns</EM> test, he would have found that there was no proximity. The Attorney General requests that this Court exercise its error correcting function to correct these errors in the motion judge's analysis.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>Response to the Appellants' Version of the Facts</TI>
<P>5. Although the appellants have not attributed the facts set out in their factum to particular paragraphs of their Statement of Claim (Claim), the Attorney General accepts that the facts do emanate from the Claim with the following exceptions:
<P1>i) The appellants did not plead that the review conducted by the Toronto Police Service Professional Standards Unit (TPSPS) was &ldquo;independent&rdquo;, as alleged in paragraph 23 of their factum. In fact, TPSPS were investigating their own officers;</P1>
<P1>ii) The allegation at paragraph 26 of the appellants' factum that &ldquo;[a]ny attempt made by Ms. Alyea to alert the Court to the TPSPS findings or the substance of the report fell far below what was required in the circumstances. The report was not properly before the Court nor had it been properly disclosed to counsel for Mr. Singh&rdquo; was not pleaded in the Claim. This allegation against Ms. Alyea in the appellants' factum appears to be a response to the finding of the motion judge that the appellants have no viable claim against Ms. Alyea because they cannot establish causation with respect to her conduct.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Statement of Claim, paras. 31&ndash;33, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 6; Transcript, <CASEREF><SOC>R v. Singh</SOC></CASEREF>, Ontario Court of Appeal, October 18, 2013, Exhibit &ldquo;G&rdquo; to the Howe Affidavit, Respondent's Compendium, Tab 1 at p. 65-66; Reasons for Decision, June 13, 2017, <CASEREF><SOC>Clark et al v. Ontario</SOC><PARANUM>93</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>iii) The allegation at paragraph 32 of the appellants' factum that &ldquo;[a]fter due consideration, counsel formed a legal opinion that they communicated to the Officers: the conduct of the Respondent may be tortious, and a novel claim in negligence and misfeasance in public office could be pursued. It was only at this point that the Officers discovered that there was a viable claim, albeit a novel one&rdquo; is not pleaded in the Claim. The issue of the &ldquo;novelty&rdquo; of the Claim was raised for the first time in response to the Attorney General's motion to strike based on the expiry of the applicable limitation period.</P1></P>
<P>6. With respect to paragraph 11 of the appellants' factum, it is correct that the accused did not bring an application to stay the prosecutions against them based on the involuntariness of their confessions until trial. However, as noted at footnote one of the appellants' factum and paragraphs 10 and 11 of the Claim, counsel for Mr. Maharaj noted on the record at the bail hearing that his client had visible injuries resulting from his arrest and again raised the issue of violence against Mr. Maharaj at the preliminary inquiry.
<P1>Statement of Claim, paragraph 11, Appeal Book and Compendium (Appeal Book), Tab 6</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>Additional Facts on Which the Attorney General Relies</TI>
<P>7. It is correct as alleged at paragraph 19 of the appellants' factum that Ms. Cressman determined that she would not call any evidence in response to the allegations by either Mr. Singh or Mr. Maharaj and stayed the charges against Mr. Maharaj. However, she also advised the Court that the evidence demonstrated that whatever happened to Mr. Singh was not as extreme as he suggested, but that the evidence did meet the low threshold required to establish a <EM>Charter</EM> breach. She suggested the proper remedy with respect to the charges against Mr. Singh, was not a stay of proceedings, but a reduction of sentence.
<P1>Statement of Claim, paras. 21 - 22, Appeal Book, Tab 6</P1>
<P1>Transcript, <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Singh</SOC></CASEREF>, March 27, 2012, Exhibit C to the Howe Affidavit, Respondent's Compendium, Tab 2 at p. 170 and 173</P1></P>
<P>8. Neither the appellants nor the Toronto Police Association moved to intervene in the appeal of Justice Thorburn's decision to this Court.
<P1>Judgment, <CASEREF><SOC>R v. Singh</SOC></CASEREF>, Ontario Court of Appeal, dated December 13, 2013, Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo; to the Howe Affidavit, Respondent's Compendium, Tab 3</P1></P>
<BLOCK4><N>i)</N><TI>Decision of the Motion Judge on the Negligence Issue</TI>
<P>9. The motion judge made six key findings on the negligence issue:
<P1>1) The novelty of the Claim was not dispositive of the motion;</P1>
<P1>2) That competing policy considerations could be determined on a motion to strike without an evidentiary record, particularly where the civil liability of Crown Attorneys was being considered;</P1>
<P1>3) That existing case law regarding Crown Attorney liability was not dispositive of the issues on the motion;</P1>
<P1>4) There was proximity between the police officers and the trial Crowns;</P1>
<P1>5) There is no viable claim against the appellate Crown as the facts as pleaded do not give rise to causation and no viable claim against the trial Crowns with respect to the stay of proceedings against Mr. Maharaj; and</P1>
<P1>6) A cause of action in negligence was negated by residual policy considerations.</P1></P>
<BLOCK5><N>1)</N><TI>Novelty of the Claim is not Dispositive</TI>
<P>10. The appellants argued that the Court should err on the side of allowing their action to proceed because it was novel. The motion judge rejected this argument and, relying on the Supreme Court of Canada decision in <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco</SOC></CASEREF>, found that the novelty of a claim is &ldquo;not determinative&rdquo; on a motion to strike. A claim should not be struck for its novelty alone, but a claim does not get a &ldquo;free pass&rdquo; to proceed just because it is novel. Instead of focusing on the novelty of a claim, a Court must determine whether, assuming the facts pleaded are true, there is a reasonable prospect that the claim will succeed, reading the claim generously and erring on the side of permitting a novel but arguable claim to proceed to trial.
<P1>Reasons for Decision, June 13, 2017, <CASEREF><SOC>Clark et al v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, Appeal Book, Tab 6, at paras. 24&ndash;29</P1></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N>2)</N><TI>Policy Considerations can be Determined Without a Full Evidentiary Record</TI>
<P>11. The appellants also argued that a full evidentiary record was required to determine the policy issues raised by their Claim. The motion judge also rejected this argument, finding that while there were some cases suggesting that Courts should be reluctant to strike claims that raise competing policy considerations, &ldquo;Courts can and do consider competing policy considerations on preliminary motions&rdquo; and &ldquo;the case law indicates that there is no absolute requirement for an evidentiary record to assess competing policy arguments&rdquo;. With respect to claims against Crown Attorneys in particular, the motion judge found:
<QUOTE><P>The four Supreme Court decision [sic] I have just mentioned (<EM>Nelles, Proulx, Miazga</EM>, and <EM>Henry</EM>) all demonstrate that, in the context of claims against Crown Attorneys, an evidentiary record is not necessarily a prerequisite to evaluating policy considerations relevant to imposing liability. Courts deal with the conduct of and relationships between Crown Attorneys and the police on a day-to-day basis. As such they are far better equipped to weigh policy issues involving these justice system participants&mdash;without the need for an evidentiary record&mdash;than situations involving casino regulators, municipalities and tenants, or credit reporting agencies, [the situations in the cases relied on by the appellants]. I therefore do not consider the absence of an evidentiary record a bar to completing the final phase of the &ldquo;<EM>Anns</EM> test&rdquo; in the present case.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Reasons for Decision, June 13, 2017, <CASEREF><SOC>Clark et al v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, Appeal Book, Tab 6, at paras. 28&ndash;29, 133</P1></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N>3)</N><TI>Existing Case Law on Crown Attorney Liability not Dispositive of the Issues on the Motion</TI>
<P>12. The motion judge found that the existing case law regarding Crown Attorney liability, which makes clear that there is no cause of action against a Crown Attorney in negligence <EM>vis a vis</EM> a person whom they have prosecuted, was not dispositive of the issues on the motion because the jurisprudence did not specifically consider whether there would be a cause of action in negligence against Crown Attorneys by police officers. In so doing, the motion judge relied on the decision of the Superior Court of Justice in <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>In short, I have reviewed the case law and agree with Matheson J.'s observations in <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC><PARANUM>136</PARANUM></CASEREF> that &ldquo;[t]he extensive body of law about common law immunity simply does not focus on lawsuits by the police against Crown Attorneys&rdquo; and (at para. 138) that &ldquo;the common law immunity grounded in the trilogy and related cases has been recognized only within the context of civil claims by members of the public.&rdquo;</P>
<P>The existing case law focuses on the duties owed by Crown Attorneys to accused persons. The cases also set out broader principles that are applicable to Crown Attorney civil liability more generally. That said, for the reasons that follow, in my view it is not plain and obvious that the existing case law on Crown Attorney civil liability definitively bars <UNDER>all</UNDER> claims by <UNDER>all</UNDER> persons against Crown Attorneys other than claims by former accused persons for malicious prosecution or intentional non-disclosure. Instead, since I do not find that the existing case law is dispositive, I find it necessary to review it to identify generally applicable principles that will assist in the &ldquo;<EM>Anns</EM> test&rdquo; analysis later in these reasons.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Reasons for Decision, June 13, 2017, <CASEREF><SOC>Clark et al v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, Appeal Book, Tab 6, at paras. 39-40</P1></P>
<P>13. However, while the motion judge noted that leave to appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> had been granted by the Divisional Court, he did not note that leave had been granted on the basis that there was &ldquo;good reason to doubt the correctness of the decision&rdquo;. <UNDER>In the appeal decision of the Divisional Court in <EM>Smith</EM>, released after the motion judge's decision in this case, a unanimous panel overturned the decision of the motion judge in <EM>Smith</EM>, finding errors in her reasoning and analysis. Thus, the motion judge's analysis in <EM>Smith</EM> no longer has any authoritative weight and should not inform the determination of the issues before this Court.</UNDER>
<P1>Reasons for Decision, June 13, 2017, <CASEREF><SOC>Clark et al v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, Appeal Book, Tab 6, at para. 36</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 7222</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, (motion decision), Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 12</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 2854</CITE><COURTJUR>Div. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, (leave decision) Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 1, paras. 13&ndash;16</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 993</CITE><COURTJUR>Div. Ct</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (appeal decision) Appellants' Supplemental Brief of Authorities, paras. 24&ndash;38</P1></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N>4)</N><TI>Crown Attorneys in a Proximate Relationship with the Appellants</TI>
<P>14. With respect to the first stage of the <EM>Anns</EM> analysis, the Attorney General conceded that it was foreseeable that a decision a Crown Attorney makes in the conduct of a prosecution may have a negative impact on an individual (i.e. a police officer, witness or complainant). However, foreseeability is not sufficient to establish a duty of care. A proximate relationship must first exist. The Attorney General argued that there was no proximate relationship between the Crown Attorneys and the appellants &ldquo;because such a relationship would be in direct conflict with the public nature of a Crown Attorney's duties, which are derived from statutes such as the <EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM> and <EM>Ministry of the Attorney General Act&rdquo;</EM>. While recognizing that a duty of care can also arise based on specific interactions between a government actor and a claimant where the government actor may have made representations on which a claimant relied, the Attorney General did not deal with this issue in depth because the appellants did not plead that there were representations and reliance in their Claim. The appellants did however raise this issue in defence to the motion even though it had not been pleaded, arguing that the alleged duty of care arose from either a combination of statutory duties and specific interactions or simply specific interactions.
<P1>Reasons for Decision, June 13, 2017, <CASEREF><SOC>Clark et al v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, Appeal Book, Tab 6, at paras. 101&ndash;104</P1></P>
<P>15. The motion judge found that it was not plain and obvious that the trial Crowns were not in a proximate relationship with the appellants. He found that a Crown Attorney may owe a duty to officers facing serious allegations of misconduct to take reasonable care to investigate such allegations and to adduce material evidence arising from those investigations in Court. He agreed with the Attorney General that, standing alone, the statutory duties of the Attorney General and Crown Attorneys appear to be public in nature and do not impose a private law duty of care with respect to investigating police officers, but the question before him was whether a duty of care is made out from a combination of statutory duties and specific interactions (or just specific interactions) and whether such a duty would conflict with a Crown Attorney's &ldquo;overarching duty to the public&rdquo;. Nevertheless, the motion judge did not conduct any analysis with respect to the &ldquo;conflict&rdquo; between a Crown Attorney's public duties and the alleged private law duty of care at the proximity stage of the <EM>Anns</EM> test. The duty of care cases of the Supreme Court have found that a conflict between public duties and the imposition of a private law duty of care is a compelling policy reason for refusing to find proximity.
<P1>Reasons for Decision, June 13, 2017, <CASEREF><SOC>Clark et al v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, Appeal Book, Tab 6, at paras. 101, 106</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2011 SCC 42</CITE><PARANUM>44</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 3</P1></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N>5)</N><TI>No Viable Claim Against the Appellate Crown or Arising from the Withdrawal of the Charges Against Mr. Maharaj</TI>
<P>16. The motion judge found that there was no viable claim against the appellate Crown counsel because causation was not made out on the facts as pleaded. The motion judge also found there could be no liability against the trial Crowns with respect to the decision to withdraw the charge against Mr. Maharaj because the decision to withdraw or proceed with a prosecution was solely within the discretion of a Crown Attorney and there is no duty to take the interests of police into account when making that decision.
<P1>Reasons for Decision, June 13, 2017, <CASEREF><SOC>Clark et al v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, Appeal Book, Tab 6, at paras. 101&ndash;104</P1></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N>6)</N><TI>Policy Considerations Negate a Duty of Care</TI>
<P>17. Despite having found that the trial Crown Attorneys were in a proximate relationship with the appellants, the motion judge found that residual policy considerations negated any duty of care. He found that the policy considerations set out in the Supreme Court quartet were applicable in this case: namely that the spectre of civil liability against Crown Attorneys could divert them from their duties by having to defend against a litany of civil claims, and could make them more defensive in their approach. If recognized, the duty of care alleged by the appellants would create a whole new class of potential claimants and Crown Attorneys would be required to consider the reputational interests of investigating police officers when making decisions about the conduct of a prosecution. The recognition of this duty of care would also divert Crown Attorneys from their basic responsibility to assess whether there are reasonable grounds to prosecute a case and to decide whether it is in the public interest to do so while protecting and respecting the rights of the accused. Finding a duty of care would impose considerations extraneous to their responsibilities as Crown Attorneys and would consequently divert them from those important functions.
<P1>Reasons for Decision, June 13, 2017, <CASEREF><SOC>Clark et al v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, Appeal Book, Tab 6, at paras. 133-135</P1></P>
<P>18. Finally, the motion judge also found that there were alternative and more proper forums for the determination of allegations of police misconduct, such as the police complaints process, disciplinary proceedings or civil actions against the police where the police could fully respond to such allegations.
<P1>Reasons for Decision, June 13, 2017, <CASEREF><SOC>Clark et al v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, Appeal Book, Tab 6, at para. 136</P1></P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;RESPONSE TO THE APPELLANTS' ISSUES</TI>
<P>20. It is the Attorney General's position that the motion judge was correct in finding that policy considerations negate a duty of care in this case; was correct in finding that novelty is not determinative on a motion to strike; and was correct in determining that even though the appellants' claim in negligence was &ldquo;novel&rdquo; it should be dismissed.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 21</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Paton Estate v. Ontario Lottery and Gaming Corporation</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 458</CITE><PARANUM>12</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 4</P1></P>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>Standard of Review</TI>
<P>21. A motion judge assessing whether a statement of claim discloses a reasonable cause of action is engaged in a purely legal analysis and therefore the standard of review on appeal is correctness. Because the standard of review is correctness, this Court is free to replace the opinion of the motion judge with its own.
<P1><EM>Paton Estate</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> at para. 10</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Housen v. Nikolaisen</SOC><CITE>[2002] S.C.J. No. 31</CITE><PARANUM>8, 10 and 28</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 2</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>Novelty of a Claim is Not a &ldquo;Free Pass&rdquo; on a Motion to Strike</TI>
<P>22. The motion judge was correct in determining that the novelty of a claim was not a complete answer to a motion to strike. While a claim should not be struck for its novelty alone, a claim does not get a &ldquo;free pass&rdquo; to proceed simply because it is novel. Instead of focusing on the novelty of a claim, a Court must determine whether, assuming the facts pleaded are true, there is a reasonable prospect that the claim will succeed, reading the claim generously and erring on the side of permitting a novel, but arguable claim to proceed to trial. The Court must evaluate a claim, novel or otherwise, in the context of the facts pleaded and the applicable jurisprudence. The motion judge's approach was endorsed by the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco</SOC></CASEREF> and by this Court in <EM>Paton Estate</EM>.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 21</P1>
<P1><EM>Paton Estate</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 12 and 49.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>Evidentiary Record Not Required to Determine the Policy Issues in this Case</TI>
<P>23. The motion judge was also correct in finding that he could determine the policy issues in this case without a full evidentiary record even though the cause of action was &ldquo;novel&rdquo;.</P>
<P>24. Whether the policy considerations required to ascertain whether a duty of care exists can be determined without a full evidentiary record is decided on a case-by-case basis. The Courts hearing the cases cited by the appellants determined that a full evidentiary record was required in those cases. However, in other cases, the Supreme Court and this Court have determined no evidentiary record is required to determine whether policy considerations negate a duty of care.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Syl Apps Secure Treatment Centre v. B.D.</SOC><CITE>[2007] S.C.J. No. 38</CITE></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 15</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Odhavji v. Woodhouse</SOC><CITE>[2003] 3 S.C.R. 263</CITE></CASEREF>, Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 3</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Arora v. Whirlpool Canada LP</SOC><CITE>2013 ONCA 657</CITE><PARANUM>90&ndash;94</PARANUM><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>leave to appeal denied</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>[2013] S.C.C.A. No. 489</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>, Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 4</P1></P>
<P>25. This is particularly so with respect to the civil liability of Crown Attorneys, where the Supreme Court has given extensive consideration to the policy implications of actions in negligence against Crown Attorneys on appeals arising from motions to strike. <UNDER>While the appellants argue at paragraphs 86 and 87 of their factum that the appeal decision in</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> <UNDER>is wrongly decided because there was &ldquo;no evidence&rdquo; that the policy considerations set out in <EM>Henry</EM> would be engaged if a duty of care is imposed in that case, it is clear from the Supreme Court jurisprudence that evidence is not required to determine whether or not a Crown Attorney is liable for a particular cause of action.</UNDER>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Nelles v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[1989] S.C.J. No. 86</CITE></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 28</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>[2015] 2. S.C.R. 214</CITE></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 17</P1></P>
<P>26. In <CASEREF><SOC>Arora v. Whirlpool Canada LP</SOC></CASEREF>, this Court recognized that its dicta in <CASEREF><SOC>Haskett v. Equifax Canada Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>, relied on by the appellants, was not a hard and fast rule which applied in every case, and &ldquo;in certain circumstances...a policy analysis can be conducted on a pleadings motion&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>It is notable that Feldman J.A., who authored the Court's decision in <EM>Haskett</EM>, was also on the panel that determined <EM>Arora</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> For example, where there is no <EM>genuine</EM> legal or factual issue, a trial and complete record are not required.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Arora v. Whirlpool Canada LP</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 92</P1></P>
<P>27. Moreover, where the Court already has the benefit of a significant body of jurisprudence to assist in answering the question before the Court, an evidentiary record is less likely to be required. Given the significant body of case law regarding Crown Attorney liability emanating from the Supreme Court and from this Court, the motion judge and this Court are well placed to analyse the strengths and weaknesses of competing policy arguments without the need for a full evidentiary record.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Arora v. Whirlpool Canada LP</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 92</P1></P>
<P>28. In determining whether a full evidentiary record is required, it is important for the Court to consider, what, in a particular case, an evidentiary record could reasonably be expected to add to the Court's determination. In this case, the appellants repeatedly state that a full evidentiary record is required to determine the policy issues, but do not state how evidence would actually assist the Court in this determination or provide any &ldquo;meaningful indication of the nature of the policy evidence [they] would lead if the matter proceeded to trial&rdquo;. The facts pleaded, which are comprehensive and detailed when it comes to the Crown Attorneys' actions, must be taken as true and assumed to be provable&mdash;evidence establishing those facts will add nothing to the Court's determination of the policy issues. Further, there is extensive case law regarding the policy issues engaged with respect to the civil liability of Crown Attorneys. The issue on this appeal is not whether the appellants <UNDER>can</UNDER> prove their factual assertions. Instead, the <UNDER>issue</UNDER> is that even if all of their assertions are accepted as true, their claims would fail because of the risk of indeterminate liability and the resulting diversion of Crown Attorneys from their important public duties <UNDER>if a duty of care were imposed</UNDER>. An evidentiary record cannot cure this defect.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Arora v. Whirlpool Canada LP</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 90&ndash;92</P1>
<P1><EM>Paton Estate (dissent)</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 146</P1></P>
<P>29. Moreover, deciding policy issues on a motion to strike can have a beneficial effect on access to justice. As the Supreme Court held in <CASEREF><SOC>Syl Apps Secure Treatment Centre v. D. (B.)</SOC></CASEREF>, the benefit of testing the viability of a novel claim on a motion to strike is obvious: &ldquo;If there is no legally recognized duty of care... there is no legal justification for a protracted and expensive trial.&rdquo; Access to justice would not be served by forcing these parties on to an even more costly trial.
<P1><EM>Syl Apps Secure Treatment Centre</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 19</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Arora v. Whirlpool Canada LP</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 93-94</P1></P>
<P>30. Both <CASEREF><SOC>Nelles v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC></CASEREF> dealt with &ldquo;novel&rdquo; claims&mdash;in <EM>Nelles</EM>, the Supreme Court found, for the first time, that Crown Attorneys could be subject to the tort of malicious prosecution and in <CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court determined, for the first time, that the state should be liable for the constitutional tort of the intentional failure to disclose exculpatory evidence to an accused person.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Nelles v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM></P1></P>
<P>31. The determination by the Supreme Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Nelles v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> that Crown Attorney liability should be strictly circumscribed and that Crown Attorneys should be immune from suit for any cause of action other than malicious prosecution was a matter of policy. While the Court found that individuals who were the victims of deliberate or malicious conduct by a Crown Attorney should have some recourse, the Court was careful to state that the inherent difficulty in proving an action for malicious prosecution created the appropriate balance of interests. The Court was also careful to note that an action in malicious prosecution did not involve errors in judgment, negligence or second-guessing the discretionary decisions of prosecutors. Only where malice or the deliberate misuse of the office of the Crown Attorney could be proven would liability lie. This high threshold was required to ensure Crown Attorneys were not diverted from their important duties by a flood of litigation.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Nelles v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 48&ndash;56</P1></P>
<P>32. These policy considerations were reiterated by the Supreme Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Proulx v. Quebec</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Miazga v. Kvello Estate</SOC></CASEREF> and more recently in <CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC></CASEREF>. In <EM>Proulx</EM>, the Court affirmed the findings in <EM>Nelles</EM> and stated:
<QUOTE><P>Under our criminal justice system, prosecutors are vested with extensive discretion and decision-making authority to carry out their functions. Given the importance of this role to the administration of justice, courts should be very slow indeed to second-guess a prosecutor's judgment calls when assessing Crown liability for prosecutorial misconduct.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>The Court further noted that liability would not be established if the conduct of a Crown Attorney was reckless, negligent or even grossly negligent. Liability would only lie if there was evidence of a willful and intentional effort on the Crown Attorney's part to abuse or distort its proper role within the criminal justice system.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Proulx v. Quebec</SOC><CITE>[2001] 3 S.C.R. 9</CITE><PARANUM>4 and 35</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 5</P1></P>
<P>33. The Court in <EM>Miazga</EM> came to a similar conclusion, finding that only malicious conduct could lead to liability and that mistakes made because of &ldquo;inexperience, incompetence, negligence, or even gross negligence&rdquo; were not actionable.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Miazga v. Kvello Estate</SOC><CITE>2009 SCC 51</CITE><PARANUM>49, and 80-81</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 16</P1></P>
<P>34. As noted above, in <EM>Henry</EM>, the Supreme Court created a new cause of action in addition to malicious prosecution because it found that the disclosure of evidence did not come within the purview of discretionary decisions made by Crown Attorneys, but instead was a constitutional obligation. Nevertheless, the Court found that the policy concerns raised in the malicious prosecution trilogy are not confined to the malicious prosecution realm. Instead, those concerns have a broader reach and are implicated wherever there is a risk of undue interference with the ability of prosecutors to freely carry out their duties in furtherance of the administration of justice.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columba</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 76</P1></P>
<P>35. The Court in <EM>Henry</EM> determined that lowering the threshold for Crown Attorney liability to a negligence standard ignored &ldquo;the basic realities of conducting a criminal prosecution&rdquo; and that &ldquo;a duty of care paradigm risks opening up a Pandora's box of potential liability theories&rdquo;. The Court noted that the problems with a negligence-based standard are even more apparent when considering how this lower threshold would operate at the pleadings stage: the lower the threshold, the greater the number of claims that would have to be defended. The mere fact of having to respond to an onslaught of litigation, even if ultimately unsuccessful, would influence the actions of prosecutors and divert them from properly performing their important public functions. It would be far too easy for a claimant with a weak claim to plead facts disclosing a cause of action for negligence&mdash;<EM>simpliciter</EM> or gross&mdash;and thus drive prosecutors into civil court.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC><PARANUM>43, 92-93</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>36. In summary, the Court found that imposing liability in negligence on Crown Attorneys:
<P1>i) Would undermine the ability of prosecutors to discharge their important public duties, with adverse consequences for the administration of justice;</P1>
<P1>ii) May influence the decision-making of prosecutors and make them more &ldquo;defensive&rdquo; in their approach. The public interest is not well served when Crown counsel are motivated by fear of civil liability, rather than their sworn duty to fairly and effectively prosecute crime; and,</P1>
<P1>iii) Would open up the floodgates of civil liability and force prosecutors to spend undue time and energy defending their conduct in court instead of performing their duties.
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC><PARANUM>40-41 and 72&ndash;74</PARANUM></CASEREF></P2></P1></P>
<P>37. Further, rather than being &ldquo;speculative&rdquo; as alleged by the appellants, the Court found these concerns to be &ldquo;very real&rdquo; and that they provided &ldquo;compelling reasons&rdquo; why the liability of Crown Attorneys in negligence should not be imposed.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC><PARANUM>41</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>38. This Court and the Ontario Superior Court of Justice have also repeatedly determined that there is no cause of action in negligence against a Crown Attorney.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Thompson v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[1998] O.J. No. 3917</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 56, Respondent's Book of Authorities, at Tab 6</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. Gilkinson</SOC><CITE>[2005] O.J. No. 5347</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 7, Respondent's Book of Authorities, at Tab 7</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Miguna v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[2005] O.J. No. 5346</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 11, Respondent's Book of Authorities, at Tab 8</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Baltovich v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[2014] O.J. No. 5767</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.&mdash;Master</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras. 35&ndash;37, Respondent's Book of Authorities, at Tab 9</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Brummell v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[2014] O.J. No. 4809</CITE><PARANUM>47, and 52-53</PARANUM><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>aff'd</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>[2014] O.J. No. 5566</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>, Respondent's Book of Authorities, at Tab 10</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ciavarella v. Schwartz</SOC><CITE>[2014] O.J. No. 4390</CITE><PARANUM>2 and 22</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Respondent's Book of Authorities, at Tab 11</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Fragomeni v. Greater Sudbury (City) Police Service</SOC><CITE>[2015] O.J. No. 3798</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras. 80&ndash;82, Respondent's Book of Authorities, at Tab 12</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI>The Motion Judge's Policy Analysis Was Correct, Not Speculative</TI>
<P>39. In determining that policy considerations negated a duty of care in this case, the motion judge relied on dicta of the Supreme Court in the malicious prosecution trilogy and <EM>Henry</EM>. He found that increasing the spectre of civil liability to negligence claims against Crown Attorneys by an entirely new class of claimants could divert Crown Attorneys from their duties by requiring them to defend against a litany of civil claims, and could make them more defensive in their approach. The motion judge found that the duty of care alleged would require Crown Attorneys to consider, in each case, whether the reputational interests of the police dictated a certain approach. It would also divert Crown Attorneys from their basic responsibilities in assessing whether there are reasonable grounds to prosecute a case and deciding whether it is in the public interest to do so while protecting and respecting the rights of the accused. Finding a duty of care would impose considerations extraneous to their responsibilities. The motion judge was correct in these findings as the Supreme Court in <EM>Henry</EM> recognized these as real and compelling concerns.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM></P1></P>
<P>40. While the appellants attempt to dismiss the substantial body of case law regarding Crown Attorney liability for negligence in one fell swoop by relying on the fact that it deals only with Crown Attorney liability <EM>vis a vis</EM> individuals they have prosecuted, and not <EM>vis a vis</EM> investigating police officers, the fact that the claimant is different does not change the policy analysis. <UNDER>Further, in the appeal decision in</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF><UNDER>, a unanimous panel of the Divisional Court found that Matheson J. was in error when she took the same approach. The Court also implicitly rejects the approach taken by the motion judge on the motion below, which it found &ldquo;essentially follows the analysis of the motion judge&rdquo; in <EM>Smith</EM>.</UNDER>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> (appeal decision), supra, at paras. 24&ndash;38</P1></P>
<P>41. The same policy considerations which upheld a Crown Attorney's immunity from suit save for claims for malicious prosecution and intentional wrongful non-disclosure apply and are, in fact, even more salient with respect to the appellants for two reasons. First, if Crown Attorneys are found to have a duty of care to investigating police officers as alleged in the Claim, they face the potential of litigation whenever a police officer is dissatisfied with the way a Crown Attorney handles a case (i.e. when a Crown Attorney determines there is no reasonable prospect of conviction and withdraws charges laid by police), or at least whenever a Crown Attorney decides he or she must concede a <EM>Charter</EM> breach by the police. Defending such claims would cause significant diversion from their duties. Secondly, such a duty of care would force a Crown Attorney to consider the possibility of civil litigation by investigating officers when making decisions with respect to a prosecution. The only factors that a Crown Attorney should be required to consider are whether there is a reasonable prospect of conviction, whether it is in the public interest to prosecute and whether the rights of the accused are being protected during the process. The imposition of a duty of care, which does not strike the important balance of interests between claimants and Crown Attorneys as in malicious prosecution or the intentional failure to disclose cases, risks distorting criminal prosecutions by inserting extraneous factors.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>E.</N><TI>Reliance <UNDER>on the Decision of the Superior Court of Justice in</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> is Misguided</TI>
<P>42. In attempting to negate all previous case law regarding Crown Attorney liability as irrelevant, the appellants rely heavily on the decision of the motion judge in <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>. <EM>Smith</EM> <UNDER>was</UNDER> the only Canadian case to find that a Crown Attorney may owe a private law duty of care to a police officer, <UNDER>or to anyone, and has now been overturned by a unanimous panel of the Divisional Court.</UNDER>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, (motion decision), supra, at paras. 136&ndash;138</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, (Div. Ct. leave decision), <EM>supra</EM></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, <UNDER>(Div. Ct. appeal decision), <EM>supra</EM>.</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>43. <UNDER>The Divisional Court found that the motion decision in <EM>Smith</EM> was wrongly decided because:</UNDER></P>
<P>1) <UNDER>The motion judge erred in finding that the existing case law with respect to Crown Attorney liability was not applicable because it dealt with the rights of individual citizens and not the police (as did Stinson J. on the motion below). The Divisional Court found that it was plain and obvious that given existing appellate authority on prosecutorial immunity, which required malice or intentional nondisclosure to find liability, the claim in negligence would fail.</UNDER></P>
<P>2) <UNDER>The motion judge erred in drawing a distinction between existing jurisprudence and the case before her on the basis of the identity of the complainant. There was no justification for the conclusion that the scope of prosecutorial immunity should be different when the police, rather than a member of the public, was claiming negligence.</UNDER></P>
<P>3) <UNDER>The scope of immunity of Crown Attorneys does not depend on the function performed. The Divisional Court noted that <EM>Nelles</EM> and <EM>Henry</EM> make clear that the functional approach to determining Crown Attorney liability is &ldquo;both impractical and unsound&rdquo;. Even if the functional approach were applicable, all actions taken within the sphere of core prosecutorial discretion would be protected by immunity.</UNDER></P>
<P>4) <UNDER>The motion judge erred in her conclusions regarding the policy considerations at issue in determining the question before her. The Divisional Court found that the policy considerations articulated by the Supreme Court in <EM>Henry</EM> and the malicious prosecution trilogy were implicated whenever there is a risk of undue interference with the ability of prosecutors to carry out their duties, which it found there was in the case before it. Unlike the motions judge, the Divisional Court found that the policy considerations could be determined on the basis of the existing Supreme Court jurisprudence, and did not require additional evidence. The policy considerations discussed in the Supreme Court's jurisprudence lead to the conclusion that there should not be a further exception to immunity for civil claims.</UNDER>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> (appeal decision), <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 24&ndash;38</P1></P>
<P>44. <UNDER>Because the Divisional Court decided the appeal on the basis of prosecutorial immunity, it found it unnecessary to deal with the second issue on the appeal: whether Crown Attorneys owe a duty of care to the police, and as a result expressed no opinion on the motion judge's duty of care analysis. However, the Attorney General submits that the motion judge erred in the analysis of the duty of care.</UNDER> Her Honour did not conduct any analysis of why a police officer who relies on legal advice <UNDER>from a</UNDER> Crown is in a closer or more proximate relationship to a Crown Attorney than a person whom a Crown Attorney has prosecuted who could lose their liberty as a result of a Crown Attorney's actions. <UNDER>Further</UNDER>, there was no analysis of why the reasonably foreseeable harm of a lawsuit if a police officer were to rely on negligent legal advice is more deserving of protection than the reasonably foreseeable harm of wrongful incarceration.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> (appeal decision), <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 39</P1></P>
<P>45. <UNDER>It is the Attorney General's position that the Divisional Court's decision on the <EM>Smith</EM> appeal is correctly decided and well-founded on binding appellate jurisprudence. In any event, it is also the Attorney General's position that the duty of care alleged by the motion judge in</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> <UNDER>is completely distinguishable from the duty of care alleged in this case.</UNDER><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>In <EM>Smith</EM>, the motion judge found that proximity between the officers and the Crown Attorneys was supported by four factors which are not present in this case:
<P1>i) In pleading that they had relied on the legal advice given by the Crown Attorneys in good faith and made decisions about the investigation based on that advice, the police met the representations and reliance aspect of the proximity test. In this case, the appellants did not plead representations and reliance (although they relied on this aspect Although they have not pleaded representations and reliance, the appellants did rely on this aspect of the proximity test in defence to the motion to strike by alleging that they relied on the Crown Attorneys. However, this is insufficient to sustain an argument in representations and reliance. In order to establish representations and reliance, one must plead that representations were made on which a party relied to his or her detriment either by failing to take action or taking a certain action as a result of the representations and suffered harm as a result. <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>.</P1>
<P1>ii) The previous recognition of the existence of solicitor-client privilege as between the police and the Crown in the case law, specifically in <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Campbell</SOC></CASEREF>. In this case, there has been no previous recognition of any duty of care akin to the private law relationship between a Crown Attorney and a witness/investigating police officer alleged in the Claim;</P1>
<P1>iii) The recognition that Crown Attorneys are subject to the same ethical obligations as other lawyers in the Supreme Court's decision in <EM>Krieger</EM> and that ethical obligations include the provision of competent legal advice to a client. There is no ethical obligation akin to what is being alleged in the Claim; and</P1>
<P1>iv) There was insufficient evidence regarding the policy implications of how a tort claim for negligent legal ad vice would interfere in the relationship between the two important parts of the justice system. In this case, it is submitted that the policy implications are evident. The duty alleged would require a Crown to consider the interests of the police in deciding on whether or how to proceed with a prosecution and this would engage all the policy considerations set out in <EM>Henry</EM>.</P1></P>
<P>Consequently, the decision of Matheson J. in <EM>Smith</EM> is not a relevant or applicable authority on the issue of whether proximity should be recognized in this case.
<P1><EM>Smith (S.C.J.)</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 148, 163, 166-167</P1></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>46. <UNDER>In any event, even if the duty of care alleged in</UNDER> <EM>Smith</EM> <UNDER>was analogous to the duty alleged in this case</UNDER>, the <EM>Anns</EM> test must still be applied rigorously. In <CASEREF><SOC>Childs v. Desormeaux</SOC></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court warns against imposing a duty of care based on analogy:
<QUOTE><P>The differences just discussed mean that the existence of a duty on the part of commercial providers of alcohol cannot be extended by simple analogy to the hosts of a private party. The duty proposed in this case is novel. We must therefore ask whether a duty of care is made out on the two-stage Anns test.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Childs v. Desormeaux</SOC><CITE>[2006] 1 S.C.R. 643</CITE><PARANUM>23</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 13</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>F.</N><TI>Duty of Care Would Conflict With, Not Complement, a Crown Attorney's Duties</TI>
<P>47. The appellants assert that finding a duty of care in this case would not conflict with the duties of Crown Attorneys, but rather that a duty of care <UNDER>&ldquo;harmonizes with and compliments</UNDER>&rdquo; their duties. The motion judge considered and rejected this argument, finding that &ldquo;Crown Attorneys should not have to consider the interests of police officers in deciding whether to bring or stay proceedings, both because such a duty would conflict with core prosecutorial discretion and because any harm would be too remote&rdquo;. The motion judge was correct in making this finding. <UNDER>To require Crown Attorneys to essentially act as the defence counsel for police officers as suggested at paragraph 89 of the appellants' factum would create a direct conflict with a Crown Attorney's public duty to the administration of justice.</UNDER>
<P1>Reasons for Decision, June 13, 2017, <CASEREF><SOC>Clark et al v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, Appeal Book, Tab 6, at para. 110</P1></P>
<P>48. In paragraph 67 of their factum, the appellants list a number of alleged duties of Crown Attorneys. To the extent that these duties have been recognized, each has been found to be owed to <EM>the accused</EM> and to <EM>the administration of justice</EM>&mdash;not to the police or other participants in the justice system. The appellants have not proffered any authority, civil or criminal, which supports the proposition that a Crown Attorney owes a police officer any duty of any kind in the conduct of a prosecution.</P>
<P>49. The appellants have also failed to cite any authority in which it has been found that a Crown Attorney may not, or should not, concede a <EM>Charter</EM> breach by police and no authority which indicates that a Crown Attorney must oppose applications for a declaration that an accused's <EM>Charter</EM> rights have been breached. As noted by the appellants, the Crown owes a duty to the accused to be scrupulously fair. A Crown Attorney owes no duty to a police officer in the course of a criminal prosecution.</P>
<P>50. The appellants suggest that the alleged duty would complement a Crown Attorney's duty &ldquo;to ensure all relevant evidence is put before the Court in support of a conviction&rdquo;. It is clear from many of the authorities cited by the appellants that it is not the role of the Crown Attorney to secure a conviction. It is a Crown Attorney's duty to prosecute only where there is a reasonable prospect of conviction and it is in the public interest to prosecute. Surely, it cannot be the duty of a Crown to proceed with a prosecution where they have determined a <EM>Charter</EM> breach has raised an issue of involuntariness with respect to a confession.</P>
<P>51. In any event, the appellants' argument that the alleged duty of care would complement rather than conflict with a Crown Attorney's duties is built on the erroneous premise that the duties of Crown Attorneys set out at paragraph 67 of their factum are somehow owed to police. It is clear they are instead owed to the accused and to the public at large.</P>
<P><UNDER>51. a. Further, the appellants' argument at paragraph 90 of their factum that the policy considerations articulated in <EM>Henry</EM> and <EM>Nelles</EM> would not be engaged in this particular case must be rejected. In <EM>Henry</EM>, the Supreme Court found that such policy considerations are engaged whenever the expansion of Crown Attorney liability is being considered. Moreover, it is the very fact that Crown Attorneys would be forced to consider the interests of police in exercising their prosecutorial discretion that engages the policy considerations.</UNDER></P>
<P>52. The public nature of a Crown Attorney's duties, which are derived from statutes such as the <EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM> and <EM>Ministry of the Attorney General Act</EM>, were recognized by the Supreme Court in <EM>Miazga</EM>:
<QUOTE><P>In exercising their discretion to prosecute, Crown prosecutors perform a function inherent in the office of the Attorney General that brings the principle of independence into play. Its fundamental importance lies, not in protecting the interests of individual Crown attorneys, but in advancing the public interest by enabling prosecutors to make discretionary decisions in fulfilment of their professional obligations without fear of judicial or political interference, thus fulfilling their <EM>quasi-</EM> judicial role as &ldquo;ministers of justice&rdquo;:..L'Heureux-Dub&ea; J. acknowledged the importance of limiting judicial oversight of Crown decisions in furtherance of the public interest:
<QUOTE><P>[T]he Attorney General is a member of the executive and as such reflects, <UNDER>through his or her prosecutorial function, the interest of the community to see that justice is properly done</UNDER>. The Attorney General's role in this regard is not only to protect the public, but also to honour and express the community's sense of justice. Accordingly, <UNDER>courts should be careful before they attempt to &ldquo;second-guess&rdquo; the prosecutor's motives when he or she makes a decision</UNDER>.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>Thus, the public good is clearly served by the maintenance of a sphere of unfettered discretion within which Crown attorneys can properly pursue their professional goals. (citations omitted)</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Miazga v. Kvello Estate</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 47 and 48</P1></P>
<P>53. In Ontario, the duties of the Attorney General are set out in section 5 of the <EM>Ministry of the Attorney General Act</EM> and include: the duty to see that the administration of public affairs is in accordance with the law; to superintend all matters connected with the administration of justice in Ontario; to advise the Government upon all matters of law connected with legislative enactments and legislation; to advise the heads of the ministries and agencies of Government upon all matters of law; and to conduct and regulate all litigation for and against the Crown and to superintend all matters connected with judicial offices.
<P1><EM>Ministry of the Attorney General Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c M.17, <EM>s</EM>. 5</P1></P>
<P>54. The duties of a Crown Attorney are set out in section 11 of the <EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM> and include aiding in the local administration of justice and performing duties assigned to them by law, including: examining informations setting out offences and ensuring relevant evidence with respect to such matters are brought before the Courts in a timely way; conducting prosecutions with respect to indictable and summary conviction offences; conducting summary conviction appeals; superintending private prosecutions; advising justices of the peace regarding offences; and conducting bail hearings and ensuring sureties are in place. These duties, along with those of the Attorney General, are public in nature and relate to the administration of criminal justice.
<P1><EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c C.49, <EM>s. 11</EM></P1></P>
<P>55. Moreover, one need look no further than the appellants' allegation about what the trial Crown Attorneys in this case <EM>should</EM> have done to see the conflict. Ms. Cressman was advised that the accused were going to bring <EM>Charter</EM> applications to stay their prosecutions based on the fact that their confessions were involuntary due to violence perpetrated against them by the appellants and was presented with evidence of a rib injury and allegations of other injuries such as cuts and bruises. The doctor viewing the test showing the rib injury said it was possible that the rib injury could have occurred the day of the arrest. Ms. Cressman then determined, after consulting with a senior Crown Attorney, that given the low threshold required to establish involuntariness, the confessions would be found to be involuntary. She then further determined that without the confession, she did not have a reasonable prospect of conviction against Mr. Maharaj and did not proceed against him. However, she determined that she did have a reasonable prospect of conviction against Mr. Singh, proceeded with that prosecution and dealt with the <EM>Charter</EM> breach on sentencing.</P>
<P>56. However, the appellants allege, that even given the evidence of injuries that she had, and the low threshold required to establish involuntariness, Ms. Cressman should have opposed the <EM>Charter</EM> applications, maintained the prosecution against Mr. Maharaj, searched for evidence to support the police and called them as witnesses for the purpose of defending their reputations&mdash;all regardless of her duties to the accused, and to the administration of justice and contrary to the requirement that she determine that there was a reasonable prospect of conviction before proceeding. Essentially, the appellants suggest that Ms. Cressman should have acted as their defence counsel. The conflict is clear. A Crown Attorney simply cannot be required to take the interests of the police into account in deciding how to conduct a prosecution.</P>
<P>57. The appellants cite a number of authorities discussing the relationship between Crown Attorneys and the police with respect to criminal prosecutions. While it is clear that the Crown and police must work together, it is toward the goal of furthering the administration of justice, a quintessentially public duty. There is no indication that the relationship gives rise to a private law duty of care or a responsibility to consider the interests of the other in deciding what action to take in an investigation or a prosecution. The interests considered are that of the administration of justice. Further, as set out in the Crown Policy Manual excerpts relied on by the appellants, it is clear that the roles of police and the Crown are distinct and public in nature:
<QUOTE><P>Although Crown counsel work closely with police, the separation between police and Crown roles is of fundamental importance to the proper administration of justice ... Crown counsel will proceed with prosecutions which present a reasonable prospect of conviction and where the prosecution is in the public interest. A distinct line between these two functions, which allows both the police and Crown counsel to exercise discretion independently and objectively, forms part of a system of checks and balances.</P>
<P>...</P>
<P>Police: Relationship to Crown Counsel</P>
<P>Police have the sole responsibility for charging decisions except where the consent of the Attorney General is required by statute. Crown counsel are solely responsible for determining whether a charge is to proceed once it is laid.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>There is nothing in the relationship between Crown Attorneys and the police that indicates there is any private law duty of care owed.
<P1>Crown Policy Manual Excerpts, Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 29</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>G.</N><TI>Lack of a Comparable Remedy does not Guarantee the Imposition of a Duty of Care</TI>
<P>58. It is the Attorney General's position that the motion judge was correct in determining that there were &ldquo;alternative and more proper forums for determination of allegations of police misconduct, including police complaints processes, police disciplinary tribunals and civil actions&rdquo; each of which focus &ldquo;on the types of allegations the officers in this case face and affords a proper opportunity to participate and respond to such allegations, separate and apart from the criminal process&rdquo;.
<P1>Reasons for Decision, June 13, 2017, <CASEREF><SOC>Clark et al v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, Appeal Book, Tab 6, at para. 136</P1></P>
<P>59. While the appellants allege in their factum that &ldquo;the findings of an internal administrative process simply do not have the same force&rdquo; as a pronouncement of a Court in the justice system or in the minds of the public, this is completely speculative. The evidence gathered in, and findings of, the investigations into the appellants have not been made public so it cannot be assumed what effect they would have in the minds of the public.</P>
<P>60. In any event, the existence of another remedy in law is only one factor of many to be considered in determining whether a duty of care should be imposed:
<QUOTE><P>This brings us to the second stage of the Anns test. As the majority of this Court held in Norsk, at p. 1155, residual policy considerations fall to be considered here. These are not concerned with the relationship between the parties, but with the effect of recognizing a duty of care on other legal obligations, the legal system and society more generally. Does the law already provide a remedy? Would recognition of the duty of care create the spectre of unlimited liability to an unlimited class? Are there other reasons of broad policy that suggest that the duty of care should not be recognized?</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Cooper v. Hobart</SOC><CITE>[2001] 3 S.C.R. 537</CITE><PARANUM>37</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Respondent's Book of Authorities, Tab 14</P1></P>
<P>61. While it is correct that the alternative remedies available to the appellants do not afford an opportunity for damages, the availability of damages is not a prerequisite to finding that there is another available remedy. For example, in <CASEREF><SOC>Syl Apps Secure Treatment Centre v. B.D.</SOC></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court determined that the ability to launch an appeal with respect to child protection proceedings provided an adequate remedy such that imposing a duty of care, and a cause of action for damages, was not required. In this case, the Attorney General submits that broad policy considerations and the spectre of indeterminate liability far outweigh the fact that the appellants will be denied a means to obtain damages.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ADDITIONAL ISSUES RAISED BY THE RESPONDENT</TI>
<P>62. Although the Attorney General was ultimately successful on the negligence issue, it is submitted that the motion judge made two errors in his analysis:
<P1>1) By failing to find that the existing case law regarding Crown Attorney liability was dispositive of the negligence issue; and</P1>
<P1>2) By finding there was proximity between the appellants and the Crown Attorneys.</P1></P>
<P>The Attorney General requests that this Court exercise its error correcting function with respect to those errors.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Housen v. Nikolaisen</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 8, 10 and 28</P1></P>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>Existing Case Law Should Have Been Dispositive of the Issues on the Motion</TI>
<P>63. As noted above, the case law of the Supreme Court and this Court makes clear that there is no cause of action in negligence against a Crown Attorney <EM>vis a vis</EM> an accused person. It is submitted that there is no principled basis why this jurisprudence should not apply where the claimant is an investigating police officer. As noted above, the policy considerations for negating a duty of care in the malicious prosecution trilogy and <EM>Henry</EM> are even more salient where the claimant is an investigating police officer.</P>
<P>64. In coming to the conclusion that the existing case law was not dispositive of the issues on the motion, the motion judge relied heavily on <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> and did not conduct any analysis as to why the Supreme Court dicta regarding negligence did not have the same force with respect to the appellants. Although the motion judge noted that leave to appeal from the <EM>Smith</EM> decision had been granted, he did not note that it was on the basis that there was good reason to doubt the correctness of the decision. <UNDER>And of course, as noted above, this approach was found to be in error by the Divisional Court on the <EM>Smith</EM> appeal.</UNDER></P>
<P>65. In <EM>Nelles</EM>, the Supreme Court rejected the American approach to prosecutor liability which held that prosecutors enjoyed absolute immunity from liability where the functions they performed were quasi-judicial in nature, but could be liable with respect to &ldquo;administrative&rdquo; or &ldquo;investigative&rdquo; functions. The line between these functions turned out to be difficult to draw in practice and the Supreme Court rejected the American approach as unprincipled; and instead it imposed liability for all functions only where the strict test for malicious prosecution was met.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Nelles v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 15&ndash;27</P1></P>
<P>66. In finding that the existing case law which soundly rejects a cause of action in negligence against Crown Attorneys did not apply where the claimant was someone other than an accused, the motion judges in this case and in <EM>Smith</EM> essentially applied a functional approach. Although they accepted that a Crown Attorney could not be liable in negligence <EM>vis a vis</EM> an accused person, they found that a Crown Attorney may be liable when performing a function other than deciding whether to initiate or continue a prosecution, i.e. when providing legal advice or when determining whether or not to concede an alleged <EM>Charter</EM> breach by police. This does not accord with the principals first articulated in <EM>Nelles</EM> and reiterated in <EM>Proulx, Miazga</EM> and <EM>Henry</EM>. Further, as noted above, the motion judge in this case and <EM>Smith</EM> performed no analysis as to <EM>why</EM> the appellants should be afforded a remedy not available to a former accused person.</P>
<P>67. It is submitted that the motion judge erred in failing to find the existing case law was not dispositive of the issues on the motion, and in going on to perform the <EM>Anns</EM> analysis to determine whether a duty of care exists.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>Motion Judge Erred in Finding Proximity Between the Appellants and the Crown Attorneys</TI>
<P>68. The motion judge also erred in finding that there was proximity between the police and the Crown Attorneys. Specifically, the motion judge failed to consider whether there was a conflict between the public nature of the duties of a Crown Attorney and the private law duty of care alleged at the proximity stage of the duty of care analysis. Had he done so, it is submitted the motion judge would not have found a proximate relationship.</P>
<P>69. To establish &ldquo;proximity&rdquo; a plaintiff must prove that a defendant had a sufficiently close and direct, or &ldquo;proximate&rdquo;, relationship to them such that the failure to take reasonable care might foreseeably cause loss or harm to the plaintiff.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 39</P1></P>
<P>70. Proximity and foreseeability are two aspects of one inquiry: the inquiry into whether the facts disclose a relationship that gives rise to a <EM>prima facie</EM> duty of care at common law. Foreseeability is the touchstone of negligence law. However, not every foreseeable outcome will attract a commensurate duty of care. Foreseeability must be grounded in a relationship of sufficient closeness, or proximity, to make it just and reasonable to impose an obligation on one party to take reasonable care not to injure the other. For example, a government actor may reasonably foresee that some of his or her decisions made in the public interest may negatively impact an individual. However, this is not enough to create a duty of care. A relationship of proximity must first exist.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 41</P1></P>
<P>71. Legislation plays an important role in determining whether a government actor owes a <EM>prima facie</EM> duty of care. An alleged duty of care may arise explicitly or by implication from the statutory scheme. It may also arise where the alleged duty of care arises from interactions between the claimant and the government, which is not negated by statute. The first situation will be rare as most statutes are &ldquo;aimed at public goods&rdquo; and do not lend themselves to an inference that the legislature intended to create a private law duty of care. Where an alleged duty of care is found to conflict with an overarching statutory or public duty there is also a compelling policy reason for refusing to find proximity. Such a conflict exists where the imposition of the proposed duty of care would prevent the defendant from effectively discharging its statutory duties:
<QUOTE><P>In <EM>Cooper</EM>, for example, a duty to individual investors on the part of the Registrar of Mortgage Brokers was rejected because it was found to &ldquo;potentially conflict with the Registrar's overarching duty to the public&rdquo;...Similarly, in <EM>Edwards</EM> a private law duty of care on the part of the Law Society to the victim of a dishonest lawyer was rejected at the proximity stage since &ldquo;[d]ecisions made by the Law Society require the exercise of legislatively delegated discretion and involve pursuing a myriad of objectives consistent with public rather than private law duties&rdquo; ... In both cases, the serious negative policy consequences of these conflicting duties were found to justify denying a finding of proximity. (citations omitted)</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras.43 -44</P1></P>
<P>72. The second situation where proximity might exist is where a duty of care arises due to a series of specific interactions between a government actor and the claimant. In these cases, the government actor may have made representations on which a claimant relied to their detriment (either by failing to do something based on the representation or taking some action because of the representation). Through this conduct the government actor may have entered into a special relationship with the plaintiff sufficient to establish proximity. However, even in these cases the governing statute is still relevant to the analysis&mdash;if the finding of proximity would conflict with the state's general public duty established by statute it is unlikely that a finding of proximity would arise. In this case, the appellants have not pleaded that there were representations on which they relied to their detriment. However, on the motion below they argued that specific interactions did give rise to a duty of care.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras.45, 51&ndash;55</P1>
<P1>Reasons for Decision, June 13, 2017, <CASEREF><SOC>Clark v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, Appeal Book, Tab 6, at para. 98</P1></P>
<P>73. Where a statute establishes only general duties to the public and no private law duties to particular individuals no private law duty of care will be imposed.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras.50</P1></P>
<P>74. In this case, the appellants allege that the Crown Attorney with carriage of the prosecutions against Mr. Singh and Mr. Maharaj owed them a duty of care because:
<QUOTE><P>41. Any careless, negligent and/or unlawful decisions made by a crown attorney, during the course of a prosecution, could result in irreparable harm to the livelihood and reputation of the investigating police officers. The prosecution is conducted under the sole discretion of the crown attorney, and a police officer is powerless to ensure that there is no injustice to themselves or the administration of justice. As a result, this foreseeability and proximity establishes a prima face duty of care that the crown attorney has to the investigating police officers.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 41, Appeal Book, Tab 6</P1></P>
<P>75. However, this does not accord with the established jurisprudence with respect to a finding of proximity. As noted above, it may well be that a Crown Attorney could foresee that a decision he or she makes in the course of a prosecution in the public interest may have a negative impact on an individual associated with a prosecution (i.e. a police officer, witness or complainant). However, foreseeability is not sufficient to establish a duty of care. A proximate relationship must first exist. It is the Attorney General's position that a proximate relationship cannot be found to exist between an investigating police officer and a Crown Attorney because such a relationship would be in direct conflict with the public nature of a Crown Attorney's duties, which are derived from statutes such as the <EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM> and <EM>Ministry of the Attorney General Act</EM>, and which have been set out in detail above.</P>
<P>76. The motion judge failed to consider this potential conflict at the proximity stage of the duty of care analysis. Instead, the motion judge considered the potential conflict at the second stage of the analysis, where he found that such a conflict existed and negated a duty of care. It is submitted that the motion judge found proximity based on reasonable foreseeability alone. Had the motion judge examined the potential for a conflict in duties at the correct stage of the analysis he would not have found a proximate relationship existed. Although the Attorney General was ultimately successful on the negligence issue, this is an important issue with respect to the development of Crown Attorney liability and should be corrected.
<P1>Reasons for Decision, June 13, 2017, <CASEREF><SOC>Clark et al v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, Appeal Book, Tab 6, at paras. 89&ndash;105</P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;ORDER REQUESTED</TI>
<P>77. The Attorney requests an Order dismissing the appeal, with costs.</P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED.</BOLD></P>
