<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">NOTICE OF APPEAL</TI>
<P><BOLD>THE APPELLANT,</BOLD> the Attorney General of Ontario (hereafter, the <BOLD>&ldquo;Attorney General&rdquo;</BOLD>), appeals to the Divisional Court from the judgment of the Honourable Mr. Justice Stinson, dated January 4, 2017, made in Toronto, Ontario.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE APPELLANT ASKS</BOLD> that the judgment be set aside and an Order be made:</P>
<P>1. Allowing the Appellant's motion to strike out and dismiss the Respondents' Statement of Claim on the basis that it is statute-barred by section 4 of the <EM>Limitations Act 2002</EM>, S.O. 2002, c 2 4, Sch. B;</P>
<P>2. The costs of the appeal; and,</P>
<P>3. Such further and other relief as this Honourable Court deems just.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE GROUNDS OF APPEAL ARE AS FOLLOWS:</BOLD></P>
<BLOCK2><TI>Background</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>The Claim</TI>
<P>1. The Respondents, officers with the Toronto Police Service, commenced the underlying action alleging negligence and misfeasance against the Attorney General for the alleged conduct of two Assistant Crown Attorneys and one appellate Crown Counsel in the course of the criminal prosecution of Randy Maharaj and Neil Singh for armed robbery.</P>
<P>2. The Respondents, who conducted the investigation which led to the prosecution, allege that the prosecutors were negligent or acted deliberately in failing to rebut allegations by the accused individuals that the Respondents assaulted them following their arrest.</P>
<P>3. Prosecutors obtained a stay of the charges against Mr. Maharaj in November 2011, but proceeded against Mr. Singh. Mr. Singh was convicted, but received a reduced sentence in July 2012 due to the alleged conduct of the Respondents.</P>
<P>4. The Superior Court issued decisions which were critical of the Respondents' conduct on March 28, 2012 and July 27, 2012. On December 12, 2013, the Court of Appeal overturned Mr. Singh's conviction on the basis of the alleged abuse and issued reasons critical of the Respondents. These decisions, including the criticism of the Respondents, were the subject of contemporaneous media coverage.</P>
<P>5. On June 22, 2016, the Respondents commenced this action against the Attorney General by issuing the Statement of Claim (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Claim&rdquo;</BOLD>).</P>
<P>6. The Respondents Claim admits that they knew the salient material facts relating to their claim against the trial Crown Attorneys prior to the argument of Mr. Singh's appeal on October 18, 2013. The Claim also suggests the Respondents knew the material facts relating to the claim against the appellate Crown counsel on, or around, December 12, 2013. Finally, the Claim states that the Respondents waited several months after the Court of Appeal released its decision on December 12, 2013 before seeking legal advice regarding their claim.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>The motion to strike</TI>
<P>7. The Attorney General brought a motion to strike the Claim on the basis that it was plain and obvious that it is statute-barred pursuant to s. 4 of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM> because it was commenced more than two years after the respondents discovered the material facts on which the Claim is based.</P>
<P>8. The Attorney General also moved to strike the claim because it fails to disclose a reasonable cause of action. The motion was bifurcated and the limitations issue was heard on October 25, 2016 before the Honourable Justice Stinson (the <BOLD>&ldquo;motion judge&rdquo;</BOLD>).</P>
<P>9. On the limitation issue, the Attorney General asserted that it was plain and obvious that the respondents were aware of the material facts giving rise to the Claim in relation to the Assistant Crown Attorneys at trial by July 2012, the date of the last trial ruling.</P>
<P>10. The Attorney General argued that the Respondents were aware of the material facts giving rise to the Claim as against the appellate Crown Counsel by December 12, 2013, the date of the Court of Appeal's ruling.</P>
<P>11. While the Respondents served notice of their intention to commence a claim against the Attorney General on October 20, 2015, they did not commence the Claim until June 22, 2016, almost four years after the last trial decision, in July 2012, and more than two years and six months after the Court of Appeal's decision, in December 2013.</P>
<P>12. In response to the motion, the Respondents asserted that the matter could not be resolved on a Rule 21 motion because the Claim raised live factual issues regarding the limitation period. In particular, the Respondents asserted that they did not know that a lawsuit was the appropriate means to seek a remedy, an element of discoverability under section 5(1)(a)(iv) of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM>, until they met with counsel &ldquo;several months after&rdquo; the release of the Court of Appeal's decision and &ldquo;discovered their cause of action&rdquo;. They also argued that they required legal advice to discover their claim because it was &ldquo;novel&rdquo;, although this is not pleaded in the Claim.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>The decision of the motion judge</TI>
<P>13. On January 4, 2017, the motion judge released his decision dismissing the Attorney General's motion on the limitations issue. The motion judge held that the action was not one of the exceptional cases in which a limitations issue could be decided on a Rule 21 motion because the underlying issues in the action were factually and/or legally complex.</P>
<P>14. The motion judge held that although, generally, &ldquo;the failure to appreciate the legal significance of discoverable facts does not stop a limitation period from running&rdquo; an exception exists where a plaintiff is asserting a novel cause of action.</P>
<P>15. Based on the recognition of this exception, the motion judge held that because the Respondents are asserting a new kind of right&mdash;i.e. the existence of a duty of care owed by prosecutors to investigating police officers&mdash;it was inappropriate to determine in a Rule 21 motion the question of whether the Respondents should have known that a lawsuit was an appropriate means to seek a remedy before they obtained legal advice.</P>
<P>16. The motion judge did not address the admission by the Respondents in the Claim that they did not seek legal advice until several months after the release of the Court of Appeal's decision.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Honourable Motion Judge Erred</TI>
<P>17. Stinson J. erred in law by:
<P1>i. Failing to apply the proper legal test on a motion to strike based on the expiry, of a limitation period before a statement of defence is filed;</P1>
<P1>ii. Finding that there is an exception to the general rule that discoverability is dependent on when a claimant knew the material facts necessary to commence an action, and not when that claimant received legal advice regarding the legal significance of those facts, where the claim asserted is &ldquo;novel&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>iii. Finding that a motion to strike based on an expired limitation period should not be granted where underlying issues in the action, not related to the limitations issue, are factually or legally complex;</P1>
<P1>iv. Misapplying and misinterpreting <CASEREF><SOC>Portuguese Canadian Credit Union Ltd. V. CUMIS General Insurance</SOC><YEAR>2010</YEAR><CITE>104 O.R. (3d) 16</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, which did not deal with a motion to strike on the basis of a limitation period; and</P1>
<P1>v. Failing to consider or conduct any analysis of the legal effect of the Respondents' admission in the Claim that they did not seek legal advice until several months after the Court of Appeal's decision.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Other Grounds</TI>
<P>18. Rules 21, 25 and 62.02 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, R.R.O. 1990, O. Reg 194;</P>
<P>19. Such further and other grounds as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE BASIS OF THE APPELLATE COURT'S JURISDICTION IS:</BOLD>
<P1>i. Sections 19(1)(b) and 134 of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, R. S.O. 1990 c. C43 and Rule 62.02(8) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> R.R.O. 1990, O. Reg 194.</P1>
<P1>ii. The Order of the Honourable Mr. Justice Stinson dated January 4, 2017 is interlocutory; and</P1>
<P1>iii. Leave to appeal from the decision of the Honourable Mr. Justice Stinson was granted by the Divisional Court on January 26, 2018.</P1></P>
