<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">NOTICE OF APPEAL</TI>
<P><BOLD>THE APPELLANT,</BOLD> the Attorney General of Ontario (hereafter, the <BOLD>&ldquo;Attorney General&rdquo;</BOLD>), appeals to the Divisional Court from the judgment of the Honourable Mr. Justice Stinson, dated June 13, 2017, made in Toronto, Ontario.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE APPELLANT ASKS</BOLD> that the judgment be set aside and an Order be made:</P>
<P>1. Allowing the Appellant's motion to strike out and dismiss the Respondents' allegations of misfeasance in public office for the failure to disclose a reasonable cause of action and for the failure to plead the constituent elements of the tort of misfeasance in public office;</P>
<P>2. The costs of the appeal; and,</P>
<P>3. Such further and other relief as this Honourable Court deems just.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE GROUNDS OF APPEAL ARE AS FOLLOWS:</BOLD></P>
<BLOCK2><TI>Background</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>The Claim</TI>
<P>1. The Respondents, officers with the Toronto Police Service, commenced the underlying action alleging negligence and misfeasance in public office (&ldquo;misfeasance&rdquo;) against the Attorney General for the alleged conduct of two Assistant Crown Attorneys and one appellate Crown Counsel in the course of the criminal prosecution of Randy Maharaj and Neil Singh for armed robbery.</P>
<P>2. The Respondents, who conducted the investigation which led to the prosecution, allege that the prosecutors were negligent or acted deliberately in failing to rebut allegations by Mr. Singh and Mr. Maharaj that the Respondents had assaulted them following their arrest.</P>
<P>3. Prosecutors obtained a stay of the charges against Mr. Maharaj in November 2011, but proceeded against Mr. Singh. Mr. Singh was convicted, but received a reduced sentence in July 2012 due to the alleged conduct of the Respondents.</P>
<P>4. The Superior Court issued decisions in the criminal proceedings which were critical of the Respondents' conduct on March 28, 2012 and July 27, 2012. On December 12, 2013, the Court of Appeal overturned Mr. Singh's conviction on the basis of the alleged abuse and issued reasons critical of the Respondents. These decisions, including the criticism of the Respondents, were the subject of contemporaneous media coverage.</P>
<P>5. On June 22, 2016, the Respondents commenced this action against the Attorney General by issuing the Claim.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>The motion to strike</TI>
<P>6. The Attorney General brought a motion to strike the Claim on the basis that it is statute-barred pursuant to s. 4 of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM> because it was commenced more than two years after the Respondents discovered the material facts on which the Claim is based.</P>
<P>7. The Attorney General also moved to strike the claim on the basis that it fails to disclose a reasonable cause of action because Crown Attorneys are not liable for negligence and misfeasance, particularly with respect to the Respondents in this matter (investigating police officers). Stinson J. bifurcated the motion and the limitations issue was heard on October 25, 2016.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>The decision of the motion judge on the limitations issue</TI>
<P>8. On January 4, 2017, Stinson J. released his decision dismissing the Attorney General's motion on the limitations issue. He held that the action was not one of the exceptional cases in which a limitations issue could be decided on a Rule 21 motion because the underlying issues in the action were factually and/or legally complex. He further held that because the claim was novel, it could not have been discovered until the Respondents sought legal advice.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI>The motion to strike on the failure to disclose a reasonable cause of action issue</TI>
<P>9. On this portion of the motion, the Attorney General took the position that there was no cause of action against a Crown Attorney in negligence or misfeasance based on the quartet of the Supreme Court of Canada dealing with Crown Attorney liability (<CASEREF><SOC>Nelles v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[1989] 2 S.C.R. 170</CITE></CASEREF>, <CASEREF><SOC>Proulx v. Quebec</SOC><CITE>[2001] 3 S.C.R. 9</CITE></CASEREF>, <CASEREF><SOC>Miazga v. Kvello Estate</SOC><CITE>[2009] 3 S.C.R. 339</CITE></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>[2015] 2 S.C.R. 214</CITE></CASEREF>) and the dicta of the Court of Appeal for Ontario in <CASEREF><SOC>Thomson v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[1998] O.J. No. 3917</CITE></CASEREF>, <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. Gilkinson</SOC><YEAR>2005</YEAR><CITE>205 O.A.C. 188</CITE></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Miguna v. Ontario</SOC><YEAR>2005</YEAR><CITE>205 O.A.C. 257</CITE></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Brummell v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[2014] O.J. No. 5566</CITE></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>10. Alternatively, with respect to the negligence allegations, the Crown argued there was no duty of care owed by Crown Attorneys to investigating police officers because there was no proximity and residual policy considerations negated a duty of care.</P>
<P>11. Alternatively, with respect to the misfeasance allegations, the Attorney General argued that courts are loath to review the discretionary and tactical decisions made by Crown Attorneys in the criminal context short of flagrant impropriety and the civil court should be equally or more loath to do so in the civil context.</P>
<P>12. Further, the Attorney General argued that the residual policy considerations negating a duty of care in negligence also negate the imposition of liability for misfeasance, particularly in a case such as this, where the Respondents were not the subjects of the prosecution.</P>
<P>13. Finally, Ontario argued that the pleadings with respect to negligence and misfeasance were bald and otherwise did not conform to the rules of pleading.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>E.</N><TI>The decision of the motion judge on the failure to disclose a reasonable cause of action issue</TI>
<P>14. On June 13, 2017, Stinson J. issued his decision on the part of the motion to strike based on the failure to. disclose a reasonable cause of action. Stinson J. struck the allegations in negligence, but allowed the action to continue with respect to some of the allegations of misfeasance.</P>
<P>15. Stinson J. found that the claim in misfeasance was different from the claim in negligence because misfeasance was a recognized cause of action, whereas the negligence claim was an attempt to extend the liability of Crown Attorneys to a new sphere. As a result, he held that his analysis would be different, and would be limited to a review of the claim to determine whether it contains sufficient allegations that, if proven, would establish the cause of action.</P>
<P>16. Stinson J. found that the ability of the criminal court to review the discretionary and tactical decisions of a prosecutor was not as circumscribed as the Attorney General argued and was not a basis to find that the claim in misfeasance was untenable. He further found that the allegations in the statement of claim, if proven, could give rise to liability in misfeasance. With respect to the existence of an unlawful act, a required element in a claim for misfeasance, Stinson J. agreed with the Respondents that a breach of the Crown Attorney's duties and oath of office under the <EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM> R.S.O. 1990 c. C.49 could qualify.</P>
<P>17. In arriving at his decision on misfeasance, Stinson J. did not conduct any analysis with respect to the policy considerations regarding the expansion of Crown Attorney liability set out in <EM>Nelles</EM> or <EM>Henry</EM> on which he relied to strike the negligence claim. Stinson J. made no finding as to whether those policy considerations had any bearing on his decision to expand Crown Attorney liability to include claims in misfeasance. Stinson J. allowed the claim for misfeasance in public office to continue in respect of allegations of prosecutorial misconduct absent any allegations of malice, which the Courts have consistently required to establish liability in all cases alleging civil liability for non<EM>-Charter</EM> claims for damages.</P>
<P>18. In deciding the motion, Stinson J. refused to consider any documents incorporated by reference into the Claim, or conduct any analysis of the law which permits the consideration of such evidence on a Rule 21 motion.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Honourable Motion Judge Erred</TI>
<P>19. Stinson J. erred in law by:
<P1>i) Declining to consider the documents incorporated by reference in the statement of claim in deciding the motion, even though the consideration of such evidence is permissible on a Rule 21 motion;</P1>
<P1>ii) Finding that the Supreme Court quartet and the Court of Appeal decisions in <EM>Thomson, Gilbert, Miguna</EM> and <EM>Brummell</EM> were not dispositive of the issues on the motion;</P1>
<P1>iii) Finding that the misfeasance claim differed from the negligence claim in that it was a recognized cause of action against Crown Attorneys and therefore required a different analysis;</P1>
<P1>iv) Failing to analyze the policy considerations set out in <EM>Nelles</EM> and <EM>Henry</EM> regarding the expansion of the Crown Attorney liability in the context of the claim for misfeasance;</P1>
<P1>v) Relying on <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[2016] O.J. No. 6163</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, when this Court found that there is good reason to doubt the correctness of that decision and granted leave to appeal (<CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[2017] O.J. No. 2370</CITE></CASEREF>); and,</P1>
<P1>vi) Failing to find that the elements of the cause of action of misfeasance were not properly pleaded in the claim, and failing to strike a non<EM>-Charter</EM> claim for damages alleging prosecutorial misconduct absent allegations of malice.</P1></P>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>Other Grounds</TI>
<P>20. Rules 21, 25 and 62.02 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, R.R.O. 1990, Reg 194;</P>
<P>21. Such further and other grounds as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE BASIS OF THE APPELLATE COURT'S JURISDICTION IS:</BOLD>
<P1>i. Sections 19(1)(b) and 134 of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, R. S.O. 1990 c. C43 and Rule 62.02(8) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> R.R.O. 1990, O. Reg 194.</P1>
<P1>ii. The Order of the Honourable Justice Stinson regarding the misfeasance allegations dated June 13, 2017 is interlocutory; and</P1>
<P1>iii. Leave to appeal from the decision of the Honourable Mr. Justice Stinson was granted by the Divisional Court on January 26, 2018.</P1></P>
