<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. This is an appeal by the Attorney General of Ontario (Ontario) from the January 4, 2017 decision of the Honourable Mr. Justice Stinson, which dismissed Ontario's motion to strike out the respondents' statement of claim and dismiss their action due to the expiry of the applicable limitation period.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Pursuant to the March 7, 2018 Order of this Court, this appeal is to be heard at the same time as both parties' appeals from the June 13, 2017 decision of Stinson J. arising out of Ontario's motion to strike out the respondents' statement of claim on the basis that it fails to disclose a reasonable cause of action.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Ontario submits that Stinson J. erred in declining to strike the claim as being statute-barred and the appeal should be granted.</P>
<P>2. The respondents are police officers with the Toronto Police Service (TPS) and were the investigating police officers with respect to a complaint of armed robbery and forcible confinement which took place in 2009. Two individuals were charged. The Deputy Crown Attorney and Assistant Crown Attorney (Crowns) assigned to the prosecutions stayed the charges against one of the accused (Mr. Maharaj) because he alleged that his confession was involuntary as a result of an assault by two of the respondents. The other accused (Mr. Singh) was convicted, but his sentence was reduced when the trial judge found that he had also been assaulted by one of the respondents while another stood by and did not intervene. The trial Crowns exercised their prosecutorial discretion not to challenge the allegations of assault and not to call the investigating police officers to testify at Mr. Singh's trial,</P>
<P>3. Subsequent to the trial, the Professional Standards Unit of the TPS (PSU) investigated the complaints of assault. Neither Mr. Singh or Mr. Maharaj, nor the respondents, agreed to be interviewed as part of the investigation. The PSU found that the allegations of assault could not be substantiated. At the hearing of Mr. Singh's appeal, Crown counsel with carriage of the appeal advised this Court of the existence of the PSU report, but the Court declined to consider it. This Court found that the trial judge had erred in failing to stay Mr. Singh's conviction due to the conduct of the respondents and overturned his conviction.</P>
<P>4. The respondents later commenced an action alleging that Ontario is liable to them in negligence and misfeasance in public office because of the conduct of the three Crowns with carriage of the prosecutions and the appeal. The respondents al lege that the Crowns were negligent and misfeasant in failing to further investigate the claims of assault and for not calling evidence (including their testimony) to refute the allegations. They further allege that the Crown should have brought a fresh evidence application to file the PSU report with this Court on Mr. Singh's appeal.</P>
<P>5. Ontario moved to strike the action on the basis that the action was statute-barred and there was no issue of discoverability. It is plain and obvious from the allegations in the Claim that the respondents knew all of the material facts necessary to pursue their Claim more than two years prior to the issuance and service of the Claim; and because the action fails to disclose a reasonable cause of action and fails to plead the necessary material facts to support the causes of action alleged.</P>
<P>6. Stinson J. bifurcated Ontario's motion to strike and determined he would decide the limitations issue first. Stinson J. dismissed Ontario's motion to strike based on the limitation period, finding that:
<P1>1) A motion to strike based on the expiry of a limitation period before a statement of defence was filed was not available where the underlying issues in the action were factually or legally complex; and</P1>
<P1>2) There was an &ldquo;arguable exception&rdquo; to the general rule that a claim was discovered on the day that the material facts giving rise to the claim were known for &ldquo;novel&rdquo; claims. Where a claim was novel, a claim may not be discovered until legal advice regarding a possible cause of action is received by the claimant.</P1></P>
<P>7. Ontario submits its appeal from the limitations decision should be granted because Stinson J. erred:
<P1>1) <BOLD>By applying the wrong test on the motion.</BOLD> The test on a motion to strike based on the expiry of a limitation period before the close of pleadings is whether it is plain and obvious that there are no other facts that could be pleaded to alter the conclusion that the limitation period has expired and there is no issue of discoverability, and not whether the underlying issues in the action are factually or legally complex;</P1>
<P1>2) <BOLD>By finding that there is an arguable exception to the general rule of discoverability for &ldquo;novel&rdquo; claims.</BOLD> This Court has repeatedly held that a limitation period commences when a person has knowledge of the material facts to support his or her claim, not when they appreciate the legal significance of those facts. A person who is asserting a novel claim is in the same position as anyone else who does not appreciate the legal significance of the material facts giving rise to their claim; and</P1>
<P1>3) <BOLD>By failing to consider or conduct an analysis regarding the respondents' admission that they did not seek legal advice about a possible claim until several months after this Court's decision on the appeal in</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Singh</SOC></CASEREF>. The law is dear that claimants must act with diligence and must not &ldquo;sleep on their rights&rdquo;. Stinson J. failed to consider this case law or to conduct an analysis of the law in relation to the respondents' admission.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;FACTS<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>On a motion to strike, and any appeal therefrom, the Court must assume that the facts pleaded in the Claim are true. The facts pleaded may be disputed should the action proceed.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>CRIMINAL PROSECUTION GIVING RISE TO THE ACTION</TI>
<P>8. The respondents investigated a complaint into an armed robbery which took place in February 2009. On June 11, 2009, the officers arrested Neil Singh and Randy Maharaj. Mr. Singh was interviewed and provided an exculpatory statement to the respondents Mr. Watts and Mr. Clark. Mr. Maharaj confessed to the crime to the respondents Mr. Watts and Mr. Belanger.
<P1>Statement of Claim, paras. 7&ndash;9, Appeal Book and Compendium of the Attorney General (Appeal Book), Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>9. At his bail hearing on June 12, 2009, Mr. Maharaj's lawyer put on the record that his client had been injured during his arrest and had very visible bumps and scratches.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 10, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>10. The preliminary hearing for both accused was held between July 16, 2010 and November 9, 2010. The respondents were called as witnesses. Counsel for Mr. Maharaj questioned the respondents about his client's accusations of being assaulted (kicked in the head and beaten) during his arrest. They denied the assault. Mr. Singh and Mr. Maharaj were committed to stand trial.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 11, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>11. The trial commenced on November 28, 2011. Deputy Crown Attorney Sheila Cressman had carriage of the prosecution. In advance of the trial, counsel for Mr. Maharaj brought an application to stay the proceedings against him and to exclude his confession, relying on doctrines of abuse of process and voluntariness based on the allegation that he was assaulted by two of the respondents prior to his confession.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 13, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>12. Counsel for Mr. Maharaj advised Ms. Cressman that Mr. Maharaj received a serious rib injury due to an alleged assault by police after his arrest and before he gave his statement. Mr. Maharaj does not appear to have complained about this specific issue when he was admitted to Maplehurst Correctional Centre (Maplehurst) prior to trial. Counsel for Mr. Maharaj provided Ms. Cressman with a CD containing an X-ray purporting to support his allegations. Ms. Cressman spoke to Dr. Moss, a doctor at the hospital where Mr. Maharaj had been treated who told her that he had viewed the X-rays with a thoracic surgeon and that it was possible that the injuries could have occurred on the day of Mr. Maharaj's arrest. Dr. Moss also advised that such an injury could result in pain if a person were to move their arms or upper body. In his videotaped statements, Mr. Maharaj is seen moving his arms. Ms. Cressman did not seek Dr. Moss's opinion regarding whether the movements on the video were consistent with the injury having occurred on the day of the arrest.
<P1>Statement of Claim, paras. 13&ndash;17, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>13. Ms. Cressman consulted with senior Assistant Crown Attorney Frank Armstrong, who agreed that Mr. Maharaj's statement would not be admissible as it could not be proven to be voluntary due to all of the injuries he had allegedly suffered. As a result, on November 22, 2011, Mr. Armstrong stayed the charges against Mr. Maharaj.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 18, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>14. On November 28, 2012, the trial of Mr. Singh proceeded before the Honourable Madam Justice Thorburn. Mr. Singh was convicted of armed robbery with a firearm and forcible confinement. Mr. Singh's counsel brought a <EM>Charter</EM> application to stay the conviction, relying on the evidence of his client and that of Mr. Maharaj. Mr. Maharaj testified he had been assault ed by the respondents Mr. Belanger and Mr. Clark. Mr. Singh testified that he had been assaulted by Mr. Clark while Mr. Watts stood by and did not intervene. In the Claim, the respondents allege the testimony of Mr. Maharaj and Mr. Singh was false.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 19, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1>
<P1>Judgment, Thorburn J., <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Singh</SOC><PARANUM>1-2</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Exhibit D to the Affidavit of Matthew Howe, sworn September 19, 2016 (Howe Affidavit), Appeal Book, Tab 14D</P1></P>
<P>15. Ms. Cressman determined that she would not call any evidence in response to the allegations. She advised the Court that the evidence demonstrated that whatever happened to Mr, Singh was not as extreme as he suggested, but that the evidence did meet the low threshold required to establish a <EM>Charter</EM> breach. She suggested the proper remedy was not a stay of proceedings, but a reduction of sentence.
<P1>Statement of Claim, paras. 21 - 22, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1>
<P1>Transcript, <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Singh</SOC></CASEREF>, March 27, 2012, at p. 92, Exhibit C to the Howe Affidavit, Appeal Book, Tab 14C</P1></P>
<P>16. On March 28, 2012, Justice Thorburn dismissed Mr. Singh's stay application. Justice Thorburn noted that the evidence of the accused had not been contradicted and found that while a stay was not warranted, Mr. Singh's sentence should be reduced due to the assault he suffered at the hands of the respondents.
<P1>Judgment, Thorburn J., <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Singh</SOC><PARANUM>46&ndash;51</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Exhibit D to the Howe Affidavit, Tab 14D</P1>
<P1>Statement of Claim, paras. 23 - 24, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>17. In paragraphs 24 to 28 of their Claim the respondents set out in great detail what occurred after Justice Thorburn's ruling, including:
<P1>1) That their reputations had been irreparably harmed by extensive media coverage which focussed on whether or not the officers had faced any ramifications for their &ldquo;misconduct&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>2) That after having viewed the videotaped statement of Mr. Maharaj on the night of his arrest in which he raised and moved his arms, Dr. Moss opined such movement would have been painful if the rib injury had occurred that day, and that while it was possible for the injury to have occurred on the arrest date, he believed the injury must have been older than that, and in fact, had already healed at the time of the videotaped interview.</P1>
<P1>3) That Mr. Maharaj had not complained of a rib injury while incarcerated at Maplehurst Detention Centre and none had been observed by the doctor who examined him while he was there.
<P2>Statement of Claim, at paras. 24&ndash;27, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P2></P1></P>
<P>18. With respect to Ms. Cressman, the respondents allege that &ldquo;[subsequent to Justice Thorburn releasing her reasons, the officers learned some disturbing facts with respect to Ms. Cress man's conduct&rdquo;:
<P1>i) Her only reason for contacting Dr. Moss, was to confirm in her mind, whether it was possible that the injury he suffered could have occurred on the arrest day, she did not ask any questions to prove further when the injury had likely occurred;</P1>
<P1>ii) She never met with Dr. Moss to show him the video of Mr. Maharaj's interview with the officers. Had she done so, Dr. Moss would have advised her, as he advised the investigators, that because of the movement of Mr. Maharaj during the interview, it would have been highly unlikely that he would have received his injuries at the time he said he did;</P1>
<P1>iii) She had the transcripts from Mr. Maharaj's bail hearing but did not properly review those transcripts to understand the inconsistent injuries reported then as opposed to what was reported at the time of the stay application;</P1>
<P1>iv) She had the medical records from Maplehurst as well as all the statements from all the medical staff, but did not do anything with the fact that those records and interviews clearly showed that Mr. Maharaj never complained of rib injuries at the time;</P1>
<P1>v) She did not call the officers to testify and allow them the opportunity to deny the allegations of abuse as they had done so under oath at the preliminary hearing;</P1>
<P1>vi) She did not call any witnesses or evidence to refute any of the allegations brought forward by Mr. Maharaj and Mr. Singh. She simply conceded a Charter breach, which left to the trial judge Justice Thorburn no choice but to rule in the way she did.&rdquo;
<P2>Statement of Claim, at para. 28, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P2></P1></P>
<P>19. The Claim contains an admission that the respondents had learned these &ldquo;disturbing facts&rdquo; about Ms. Cressman sometime after Justice Thorburn released her decision, on March 28, 2012, and before October 18, 2013, the date that Mr. Singh's appeal was argued before this Court:
<QUOTE><P>32. Before the appeal was argued, Det. Sgt. Watt met with Amy Alyea (&ldquo;Ms. Alyea&rdquo;) who was going to argue the appeal on behalf of the Crown. He advised Ms. Alyea that an egregious mistake had occurred. He advised her of what the officers had learned about Ms. Cressman's conduct. Despite this, Ms Alyea and the senior crown's [sic] she reported to: (i) took <UNDER>no</UNDER> steps to investigate further, (ii) took <UNDER>no</UNDER> steps to rectify and repair that damage that had been done to the officers' reputations or (iii) took<UNDER>no</UNDER> steps to prepare and file an application to introduce fresh evidence before the Court of Appeal.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 32, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>20. Further, although no specific time frame is given for when the respondents learned that their reputations &ldquo;were irreparably harmed&rdquo;, media articles about the rulings of Justice Thorburn were published on May 24, 2012 and July 28, 2012.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 31, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1>
<P1>Newspaper Articles, Exhibits <EM>&ldquo;J&rdquo;</EM> and &ldquo;K&rdquo; to the Howe Affidavit, Appeal Book, Tabs 14J and 14K</P1>
<P1>Judgment, <CASEREF><SOC>R v. Singh</SOC></CASEREF>, Ontario Court of Appeal, dated December 13, 2013, Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo; to the Howe Affidavit, Appeal Book, Tab 14H</P1></P>
<P>21. Mr. Singh appealed his conviction and sentence. Before the appeal was heard, the Crown Law Office&mdash;Criminal notified the Chief of the TPS about concerns regarding the respondents' conduct. The Special Investigations Unit (SIU) was notified and invoked its mandate. However, Mr. Maharaj refused to be interviewed or participate in the investigation and the SIU withdrew its mandate. However, between July 4, 2012 and October 31, 2012, the PSU conducted a review of the allegations of misconduct and use of excessive force. In a written report, the PSU concluded the use of excessive force &ldquo;could not be substantiated&rdquo;. Neither Mr. Singh or Mr. Maharaj, nor the respondents, were interviewed as part of the PSU investigation.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 29-30, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1>
<P1>Toronto Police Service Court Review, dated October 31, 2012, Exhibit &ldquo;F&rdquo; to the Howe Affidavit, Appeal Book, Tab 14F</P1></P>
<P>22. The Claim alleges that prior to the argument of Mr. Singh's appeal, the respondent Mr. Watt spoke to the appellate Crown counsel with carriage of the appeal and advised her about what the respondents had learned about Ms. Cressman's alleged failure to investigate the allegations of assault and the contents of the PSU report. The Claim states that despite this knowledge, the appellate Crown, either negligently or deliberately, failed to advise the Court about the new material facts she had learned about the trial Crowns' conduct and the &ldquo;exculpatory findings&rdquo; with respect to the respondents, and she did this to protect her colleagues. However, the transcript of the hearing before this Court reveals that Ms. Alyea advised the Court of the existence of the PSU report and repeatedly offered to provide it for the Court's review, but the panel hearing the appeal ultimately declined to consider it.
<P1>Statement of Claim, paras. 31&ndash;33, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1>
<P1>Transcript, <CASEREF><SOC>R v. Singh</SOC></CASEREF>, Ontario Court of Appeal, December 13, 2013, at pgs, 62 - 63, Exhibit &ldquo;G&rdquo; to the Howe Affidavit, Appeal Book, Tab 14G</P1></P>
<P>23. Neither the respondents nor the Toronto Police Association moved to intervene in the appeal of Mr. Singh's conviction.
<P1>Judgment, <CASEREF><SOC>R v. Singh</SOC></CASEREF>, Ontario Court of Appeal, dated December 13, 2013, Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo; to the Howe Affidavit, Appeal Book, Tab 14H</P1></P>
<P>24. On December 12, 2013, this Court released its decision setting aside the conviction because it found that Mr. Singh was a victim of conduct &ldquo;which might well be characterized as &lsquo;torture&rsquo;&rdquo; at the hands of the respondent Mr. Clark. In the Claim, the respondents allege that this was a result of the failure of the Crown to apprise the Court of the &ldquo;new material facts that established that Mr. Maharaj and Mr. Singh had most certainly fabricated the allegations of assault by the officers&rdquo;.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 35, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1>
<P1>Judgment, <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Singh</SOC></CASEREF>, December 12, 2013 at pg. 16, Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo; to the Howe Affidavit, Tab 14 H</P1></P>
<P>25. The Claim states that the decision of this Court was widely reported in the mainstream media and on the internet and that it became the subject of conversations and communication among Crown Attorneys, the judiciary and the criminal defence bar. Articles regarding the decision appeared in the media on December 12 and 13, 2013.
<P1>Statement of Claim, paras. 36 - 37, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1>
<P1>Newspaper Articles, Exhibits &ldquo;A&rdquo; and &ldquo;L&rdquo; to the Howe Affidavit, Tabs 14A and 14L</P1></P>
<P>26. The Claim states that after the release of this Court's decision, the SIU re-opened their investigation and that this time Mr. Maharaj agreed to be interviewed. The Claim states that the SIU investigators reviewed all the records, including the videotape of Mr. Maharaj, and determined the rib injury post-dated the time of arrest and his physical demeanour during his videotaped statement was inconsistent with having sustained any rib injury. As such, the allegations were not substantiated. The report is not in evidence and it is unclear whether the report dealt with the allegations of abuse by Mr. Maharaj beyond the rib injury or with the allegations of Mr. Singh. It does not appear that the respondents were interviewed as part of the investigation.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 38, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1>
<P1>Howe Affidavit, para. 5, Appeal Book, Tab 14</P1></P>
<P>27. On May 26, 2014, the Chief of the TPS asked the Ontario Provincial Police (OPP) to conduct an independent review of the review conducted by the PSU. In her report dated April 9, 2015, the OPP investigator concluded she had no reason to refute the conclusion of the PSU that the allegations could not be substantiated. It is unclear whether any additional witnesses were interviewed or evidence gathered. Ontario does not have a copy of this report.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 39, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1>
<P1>Howe Affidavit, para. 5, Appeal Book, Tab 14</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>THE RESPONDENTS' ACTION</TI>
<P>28. On October 20, 2015, the respondents served notice that they intended to commence an action against Ontario due to the alleged negligence and misfeasance in public office committed by Ms. Cressman, Mr. Armstrong, Ms. Alyea and &ldquo;senior officials in the Crown Law Office&mdash;Criminal&rdquo;, pursuant to section 7(1) of the <EM>Proceedings Against the Crown Act</EM> (PACA) which requires 60-days' notice before a claim against the Crown is commenced. The Notice attached a draft claim.
<P1>Notice, <EM>Proceedings Against the Crown Act</EM>, s. 7(1), served October 20, 2015, Exhibit &ldquo;I&rdquo; to the Howe Affidavit, Tab 14I Section 7(1)(2), <EM>Proceedings Against the Crown Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. P. 27</P1></P>
<P>29. However, the respondents did not issue and serve their claim until June 22, 2016, some eight months after serving their PACA notice. The Claim alleges that Crown Attorneys have a duty of care to investigating police officers and may be found liable in negligence and misfeasance. The respondents allege that but for the negligent and misfeasant conduct of the trial and appellate Crowns, the Superior Court and this Court would not have made the findings they did and the respondents' reputations would not have been damaged.
<P1>Statement of Claim, paras. 42 - 43, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>30. Finally, the respondents recognized that there was a limitations issue with respect to their Claim. They plead at paragraph 50:
<QUOTE><P>50. Several months after the Court of Appeal released its judgement in December of 2013, the officers retained counsel, who had the opportunity to review the entire record, and to listen to the audio of the oral arguments that were made in the Court of Appeal. It was only then that the officers were made fully aware of the tortious conduct of the defendant, and discovered their causes of action in negligence and malfeasance in a public office.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 50, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>ONTARIO'S MOTION TO STRIKE</TI>
<P>31. Ontario brought a motion to strike out the action pursuant to Rules 21 and 25 on the basis that the action is statute-barred because the limitation period had expired. The Claim makes clear that the respondents knew all of the material facts necessary to pursue their Claim more than two years prior to the commencement of the Claim. Ontario also moved to strike the Claim on the basis that it failed to disclose a reasonable cause of action and failed to plead the material facts necessary to support the causes of action alleged. Stinson J. bifurcated the motion and determined he would decide the limitations issue first.</P>
<BLOCK4><TI>Motion on the Limitations Issue</TI>
<P>32. Ontario argued that this case was one in which a motion to strike based on the expiry of a limitation period could be determined before a statement of defence was filed because it was plain and obvious from a review of the Claim that no additional facts could be asserted that would alter the conclusion that the limitation period had expired before the Claim was commenced. Ontario focused on three key parts of the Claim.</P>
<P>33. The first was the admission in paragraphs 28 and 32 that the respondents had learned about Ms. Cressman's alleged misconduct sometime between the time of Justice Thorburn's decision on March 28, 2012 and the hearing of the appeal of that decision on October 18, 2013. Having failed to commence the action until June 22, 2016, the respondents had missed the limitation period for a claim arising from the conduct of the trial Crowns by at least eight months.</P>
<P>34. Second, while Ontario acknowledged that the Claim did not plead the exact date that the respondents became aware of the alleged misconduct of the appellate Crown, Ontario argued that the decision allowing Mr. Singh's appeal would have come to the respondents' attention on the date it was released, December 12, 2013, or very soon thereafter (with which Stinson J. agreed) and the limitation period would have therefore expired on December 12, 2015. However, pursuant to section 7(2) of PACA, where Notice pursuant to section 7(1) is served within the limitation period, the limitation period will be extended to the end of seven days after the expiration of the Notice period. In this case, because the Notice was served on October 20, 2015, the limitation period was extended to December 27, 2015. As a result, the respondents missed the deadline to commence a claim arising from the conduct of the appellate Crown by approximately six months.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Section 7(2) of the <EM>Proceedings Against the Crown Act</EM> states: Where a notice of a claim is served under subsection (1) before the expiration of the limitation period applying to the commencement of an action for the claim and the sixty-day period referred to in subsection (1) expires after the expiration of the limitation period, the limitation period is extended to the end of seven days after the expiration of the sixty-day period.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<P1>Endorsement, Stinson J., January 4, 2017, at para. 10, Appeal Book, Tab 9</P1></P>
<P>35. Finally, Ontario took the position that paragraph 50 of the Claim, which states that the respondents had not retained legal counsel until several months after the Court of Appeal decision on Mr. Singh's appeal, did not save the Claim from being statute-barred because the binding appellate authority was clear that a limitation period begins to run from the date that all materials facts are known to a claimant, not on the date on which legal advice with respect to the legal significance of those facts is received.
<P1>Factum of the Moving Party, Motion to Strike, at para. 53, Appeal Book, Tab 12</P1></P>
<P>36. In response, the respondents argued that the motion should be dismissed because striking a claim on the basis of a limitation period under Rule 21 before a statement of defence was filed should only be done in the rarest of cases, and this was not one of those cases. They also argued that there were live factual issues on the limitations issue which were expressly raised in the Claim and precluded determination of the question on a pleadings-based motion.
<P1>Endorsement, Stinson J., January 4, 2017, at para. 12, Appeal Book, Tab 9</P1></P>
<P>37. Finally, the respondents argued, although it was not pleaded in their Claim, that they did not know that a lawsuit was an appropriate means to seek a remedy until they received legal advice because the cause of action they were al leging was novel. They premised this argument on a brief statement by the Honourable Madam Justice Low of the Superior Court of Justice in <CASEREF><SOC>Boyce v. Toronto</SOC></CASEREF>, a 2011 decision:
<QUOTE><P>Section 5(1)(a)(iv) [of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM>] does not import an idiosyncratic limitation period calibrated by the claimant's familiarity with or ignorance of the law. The test is an objective one. While <UNDER>it is possible to envisage that a new kind of right might arise that has not been hitherto protected, thus making it arguable that a civil proceeding might not be seen objectively as an appropriate means to seek to remedy,</UNDER> a battery causing personal injury is a classic example of the kind of wrong that is appropriate for redress by court action. A citizen is presumed to know the law of the land. [Emphasis added.]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Boyce v. Toronto (City) Police Services Board</SOC><CITE>2011 ONSC 53</CITE><PARANUM>23</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Ontario's Book of Authorities (Book of Authorities), Tab 1</P1>
<P1>Endorsement, Stinson J., January 4, 2017, at paras. 18&ndash;20, Appeal Book, Tab 9</P1></P>
<P>38. The respondents did not argue that they did not know the material facts giving rise to their Claim during the limitation period, nor did they identify what specific additional facts could be asserted with respect to the limitations issue.
<P1>Factum of the Responding Party, Appeal Book, Tab 13</P1></P>
<P>39. On January 4, 2017, Stinson J. dismissed Ontario's motion to strike based on the limitation period. His Honour found that this was not one of the exceptional cases in which the limitations issue could be decided on a rule 21 motion because the underlying issues in the action were factually and/or legally complex. Stinson J, did not find that the limitations issue itself was factually or legally complex, although he stated that there could be additional, unspecified facts pleaded on the limitations issue.
<P1>Endorsement, Stinson J., January 4, 2017, at para. 12, Appeal Book, Tab 9</P1></P>
<P>40. Further, Stinson J. found that although, generally, &ldquo;the failure to appreciate the legal significance of discoverable facts does not stop a limitation period from running&rdquo;, the &ldquo;arguable exception&rdquo; in <EM>Boyce</EM> applied because the respondents were asserting a new or novel cause of action. Consequently, the limitation period may not have started to run until the receipt of legal advice. Finally, Stinson J. did not address the admission made by the respondents in their Claim that they did not seek legal advice until several months after the release of the Court of Appeal's decision allowing Mr. Singh's appeal.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Ontario's motion to strike the Claim for failing to disclose a reasonable cause of action in negligence and misfeasance was heard on February 21 and 22, 2017. On June 13, 2017, Stinson J. released his decision striking the claims in negligence and allowing the allegations in misfeasance to continue. On January 26, 2018, the Divisional Court granted Ontario's motions for leave to appeal the limitations and misfeasance decisions, both of which were interlocutory decisions. The respondents appealed Stinson J.'s negligence decision as of right to this Court. On March 7, 2018, this Court ordered that Ontario's appeals be heard at the same time as the respondents' appeal on the negligence issue.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<P1>Endorsement, Stinson J., January 4, 2017, at paras. 16 and 19&ndash;22; Appeal Book, Tab 9</P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;LAW &amp; ARGUMENT</TI>
<P>41. The sole issue to be determined on this appeal is whether Stinson J. erred in dismissing Ontario's motion to strike out the respondents' Claim on the basis that the applicable limitation period had expired. It is Ontario's position that Stinson J. erred:
<P1>1) By applying the wrong test on the motion;</P1>
<P1>2) By finding that there is an exception to the general rule of discoverability for &ldquo;novel&rdquo; claims; and,</P1>
<P1>3) By failing to consider or conduct any analysis regarding the respondents' admission that they did not seek legal advice until several months after the Court of Appeal's decision on the appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Singh</SOC></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<BLOCK3><N>1)</N><TI>MOTION TO STRIKE BASED ON A LIMITATION PERIOD IS AVAILABLE IN THIS CASE</TI>
<P>42. In <CASEREF><SOC>Beardsley v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, this Court determined that while, generally, the expiration of a limitation period is a defence to be pleaded rather than the basis for a motion to strike, where it is plain and obvious that no additional facts could be pleaded that would alter the conclusion that the limitation period had expired such a motion is appropriate. Further, the Court found it would be unduly technical to require a defence to be delivered where the plain and obvious test is met.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Beardsley v. Ontario</SOC><YEAR>2001</YEAR><CITE>[2001] O.J. No. 4574</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at paras. 21-22, Book of Authorities, Tab 2</P1></P>
<P>43. In <CASEREF><SOC>Golden Oaks Enterprises Inc. v. Lalonde</SOC></CASEREF>, this Court recently considered the effect of the enactment of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM> on its <EM>dicta</EM> in <EM>Beardsley</EM>, and ultimately concluded that because the basic limitation period in the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM> is now premised on the discoverability rule, discoverability had to form part of the test on a motion to strike based on the expiry of a limitation period.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Golden Oaks Enterprises Inc. v. Lalonde</SOC><CITE>[2017] O.J. No. 3188</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 45, Book of Authorities, Tab 3</P1></P>
<P>44. <EM>Golden Oaks</EM> involved an appeal from a motion to strike out certain claims in a complex bankruptcy matter. One of the bases of the motion to strike was that certain causes of action pleaded were statute-barred. A determination of the limitations issue required a determination of whether the respondent was a person advancing a claim through a predecessor right under section 12 of the <EM>Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act</EM>, and whether the limitation period began to run when the trustee in bankruptcy had knowledge of the claim or when the bankrupt had knowledge of the claim. The motion judge found that the claims were not statute-barred because they had only been discoverable in May 2014, less than two years before the Claim was issued.
<P1><EM>Golden Oaks</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 21</P1></P>
<P>45. The issue before this Court on the appeal was whether the decision below was final, such that this Court could hear the appeal. Although the appellants did not rely on rule 21.01(1)(a) in their Notice of Motion, they argued that they had relied on it in their factum and in oral submissions on the motion, and were in fact seeking a determination on a question of law regarding the limitation period from the motion judge and that the motion judge had made findings in that regard.
<P1><EM>Golden Oaks</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 14&ndash;21</P1></P>
<P>46. However, this Court found that the appeal was interlocutory for three reasons. First, the Notice of Motion did not refer to rule 21.01(1)(a) and the formal Order from the motion simply dismissed the motion, with no reference to a determination of a question of law. Second, although the motion judge had referred to the appellant's arguments regarding rule 21.01(1)(a) in his reasons, the Court was not persuaded that his reasons intended to make a binding determination on the limitations issue. Finally, and most relevant to this appeal, the Court found that it was not satisfied that the motion judge had the authority to make a binding determination under rule 21.01(1)(a) in that case.
<P1><EM>Golden Oaks</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 25&ndash;51</P1></P>
<P>47. The Court stated that the test set out in <EM>Beardsley</EM> for motions to strike based on a limitation period before the close of pleadings &ldquo;has likely been overtaken by the enactment of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM>&rdquo;. The Court also stated &ldquo;we are also of the view that the comment in <EM>Beardsley</EM> was never intended to apply to a case that is factually or legally complex&rdquo;. The Court did not cite any authority for these conclusions and it is unclear to what extent, if any, the Court heard argument on these issues. The Court noted that in stating the test, the Court in <EM>Beardsley</EM> gave the example of a matter &ldquo;where it is clear that the discoverability rule did not apply&rdquo;. Because the basic limitation period in the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM> is now premised on the discoverability rule, the Court questioned whether there was any situation in which a limitations issue could be determined on a rule 21.01(1)(a) motion unless pleadings are closed and it is clear the facts are undisputed.
<P1><EM>Golden Oaks</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 42&ndash;45</P1></P>
<P>48. The Court concluded that in any event, <EM>Beardsley</EM> was not intended to apply to the situation before <EM>them</EM>&mdash;where the fact situation involving the limitation period was not straightforward and required factual determinations, and because the claim was novel in that the trustee in bankruptcy was purporting to act in a representative capacity for unsecured creditors, which was a novel role for a trustee.
<P1><EM>Golden Oaks</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 46</P1></P>
<P>49. In conclusion, the Court in <EM>Golden Oaks</EM> appears to suggest that the <EM>Beardsley</EM> test will apply where there is an undisputed fact situation in which the cause of action has accrued and to which the discoverability rule did not apply, which was unlike the case before them.
<P1><EM>Golden Oaks</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 49</P1></P>
<P>50. As noted above, the extent to which the Court heard argument from the parties on the issue of the effect of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM> on the test in <EM>Beardsley</EM> or the jurisdiction of the motion judge is unclear. In this regard, it may be that the Court's conclusions are <EM>obiter</EM>. In any event, <EM>Golden Oaks</EM> cannot be viewed as overturning <EM>Beardsley</EM> because a five-member panel of this Court would be required to overturn a previous decision of the Court. Certainly, <EM>Golden Oaks</EM> cautions that motions to strike on the basis of a limitation period before the close of pleadings are the exception, not the rule, and will not be permitted where discoverability is an issue. However, the decision does not stand for the proposition that such motions can never be brought.</P>
<P>51. The current test for a motion to strike on the basis of an expired limitation period prior to the close of pleadings was summarized by Perell J. in <CASEREF><SOC>Kaynes v. B.P. P.L.C.</SOC></CASEREF>, where His Honour had the opportunity to consider <EM>Golden Oaks</EM> (also cited as <CASEREF><SOC>Salewski v Lalonde</SOC></CASEREF>) and <EM>Beardsley</EM>:
<QUOTE><P>On a rule 21.01(1)(a) motion, the court may determine a limitations issue before a statement of defence is filed, where discoverability is not in issue and no additional facts could be pleaded that would alter the conclusion that a limitation period has expired: <CASEREF><SOC>Beardsley v. Ontario</SOC><YEAR>2001</YEAR><CITE>57 O.R. (3d) 1</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 21; <CASEREF><SOC>Salewski v Lalonde</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 515</CITE><PARANUM>43&ndash;46</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Amrane v.York University</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 7847</CITE><COURTJUR>Div. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras. 14-15; <CASEREF><SOC>Maynards Industries Ltd v. Cincinnati Industrial Auctioneers Inc</SOC><CITE>2011 ONSC 2656</CITE><PARANUM>34</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Kaynes v. BP, P.L.C.</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 5172</CITE><PARANUM>17</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 4</P1></P>
<P>52. The test for such a motion is met in this case. The limitations issue in this case is straightforward and discoverability is not at issue because there are no additional facts that could be pleaded that would alter the conclusion that the respondents knew all of the material facts necessary to commence an action more than two years before their Claim was commenced.</P>
<P>53. Paragraphs 28 and 32 of the Claim make clear that the respondents learned the material facts on which they rely to support their claim against the trial Crowns after March 28, 2012 (Justice Thorburn's decision) and before the argument of Mr. Singh's appeal at this Court (October 18, 2013). Giving the respondents the benefit of the latest date, by commencing their claim on June 22, 2016, they missed the limitation period with respect to a claim against the Attorney General based on the conduct of the trial Crowns by approximately eight months. With respect to the conduct of the appellate Crown, the decision on Mr. Singh's appeal was released on December 12, 2013 and, as found by Stinson J., &ldquo;it is a reasonable inference that [it] came to the respondents' attention at that time or soon thereafter&rdquo;. As such, the limitation period would normally have expired on December 12, 2015. However, the limitation period was extended by section 7(2) of <EM>Proceedings Against the Crown Act</EM> until December 27, 2015. Consequently, the respondents missed the limitation period against the appellate Crown by approximately six months.
<P1>Endorsement, Stinson J., January 4, 2017, at para. 10, Appeal Book, Tab 9</P1>
<P1>Statement of Claim, Appeal Book at paras. 28 and 32, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>54. The respondents state in paragraph 50 of their Claim that they did not &ldquo;discover&rdquo; their claim until they received legal advice. On the motion below, they argued that this was because the Claim was novel (although this was not pleaded in the Claim). However, as will be explored more fully below, the legal advice received by the respondents did not provide them with further material facts regarding their Claim. Instead, it provided them with information about the legal effect of those facts. In those circumstances, the receipt of legal advice does not extend the limitation period, Therefore, the &ldquo;novelty&rdquo; of the respondents' Claim does not alter when the claim was &ldquo;discovered&rdquo;.</P>
<P>55. Consequently, this case does not have the complexity or novelty present in <EM>Golden</EM> Oaks and it is submitted that the limitations issue can be determined without the delivery of a Statement of Defence or Reply. The limitations issue in this case is strictly a legal question: does the novelty of the respondents' claim extend the limitation period?</P>
<P>56. Stinson J. did not have the benefit of <EM>Golden Oaks or Kaynes</EM>, both of which were released after his decision on the limitations issue. However, it is submitted that His Honour erred in the test he <EM>did</EM> apply by failing to apply <EM>Beardsley</EM> and instead finding that a motion to strike on the basis of an expired limitation period should not be permitted where the underlying issues in an action are factually or legally complex. In so doing, he relied on the following statement in the Superior Court's decision in <EM>Portuguese Canadian Credit Union Ltd</EM>.:
<QUOTE><P>... I do not accept the submission of the Credit Union that its Rule 21 motion falls within the category of cases alluded to in <EM>Beardsley</EM> &ldquo;where, it is plain and obvious from a review of a statement of claim that no additional facts could be asserted&rdquo;. In <EM>Beardsley</EM> the possibility of bringing a Rule 21.01(1)(a) motion before the close of pleadings was discussed in the context of a determination as to whether an action was statute-barred&mdash;for example, such as in cases where the injuries suffered in a car accident occurred on a date certain and nothing more could be said about that fact. That type of case is a far cry from the complex claim asserted in this proceeding. [Footnote omitted.]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Portuguese Canadian Credit Union Ltd. (Liquidator of) v CUMIS Genera/Insurance</SOC><CITE>2010 ONSC 6107</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 33, Book of Authorities, Tab 5</P1>
<P1>Endorsement, Stinson J., January 4, 2017, at paras. 18&ndash;20, Appeal Book, Tab 9</P1></P>
<P>57. However, this was a misinterpretation and misapplication of <EM>Portuguese Canadian Credit Union</EM>. That case involved a motion under rule 21 for the determination of two complex questions of law before the close of pleadings, was not a motion to strike based on a limitation period, and did not deal with limitation periods in any way. In the paragraph relied on by Stinson J., the Court found that a rule 21 motion to strike before the close of pleadings <EM>may be appropriate in circumstances where it is plain and obvious from the statement of claim that the action had been commenced beyond the limitation period</EM>, but it was not appropriate in the case before the Court because the legal questions raised by the motion, which had nothing to do with a limitation period, were too complex.
<P1><EM>Portuguese Canadian Credit Union</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 33</P1></P>
<P>58. Stinson J. therefore erred in relying on <EM>Portuguese Canadian Credit Union</EM>. He further erred by relying on this Court's statement in <CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Real Estate Assn. v. American Home Assurance Co.</SOC></CASEREF> that &ldquo;the exception in <EM>Beardsley</EM> must be confined to cases that involve no legal or factual complexities.&rdquo; In so finding, this Court was referring to a case in which the <EM>limitations issue</EM> was factually or legally complex, not the underlying issues in the action.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Real Estate Assn. v. American Home Assurance Co.</SOC><CITE>2015 ONCA 389</CITE><PARANUM>2</PARANUM></CASEREF>, aff'ing December 19, 2014 decision of Belobaba J. CV-12-466984 (unreported) Book of Authorities, Tabs 6 and 7</P1></P>
<P>59. Stinson. J. made no reference to the specific paragraphs in the Claim in which the respondents set out when they learned the material facts necessary to commence their action and did not apply the plain and obvious test to those paragraphs. While the respondents argued that they should have the opportunity to plead additional facts about the limitation period in reply to a limitations defence, they failed to articulate what facts could be pleaded that would alter the conclusion that the limitation period expired. As such, it is Ontario's position that the motion judge's decision with respect to the limitation period cannot stand. Certainly, the limitation period issue must now also be assessed in the light of the dicta in <EM>Golden Oaks</EM> and <EM>Kaynes</EM>. When that test is applied to the case before this Court, it is plain and obvious that the limitation period expired before the Claim was commenced, and that there is no genuine issue of discoverability. The action should be struck as being statute-barred.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>2)</N><TI>THE MOTION JUDGE ERRED IN FINDING THERE IS AN EXCEPTION TO THE DISCOVERABILITY RULE FOR &ldquo;NOVEL&rdquo; CLAIMS</TI>
<P>60. This Court has determined that a claim is &ldquo;discovered&rdquo; within the meaning of section 5(1)(a) of the Limitations <EM>Act, 2002</EM> when an individual has knowledge of the material facts underlying their claim and <UNDER>not</UNDER> when they appreciate the legal significance of those facts.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Nicholas v. McCarthy T&ea;trault</SOC><CITE>[2008] O.J. No. 4258</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras. 26&ndash;31 (S.C.J.), Ontario's Book of Authorities, Tab 8, aff'd [2009] O.J. No. 4061 (C.A.) at para 1, Book of Authorities, Tab 9</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Unegbu v. WFG Securities of Canada Inc.</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 6408</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras. 12-13, Ontario's Book of Authorities, Tab 10, aff'd 2016 ONCA 501, Book of Authorities, Tab 11</P1></P>
<P>61. However, in examining the issue of discoverability in the context of the respondents' claim, Stinson J. found:
<QUOTE><P>Generally, the failure to appreciate the legal significance of discoverable facts does not stop a limitation period from running. However, there is an arguable exception for novel claims. In <CASEREF><SOC>Boyce v. Toronto (City) Police Services</SOC><CITE>2011 ONSC 53</CITE><PARANUM>23</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Low J. stated:
<QUOTE><P>Section 5(1)(a)(iv) [of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM>] does not import an idiosyncratic limitation period calibrated by the claimant's familiarity with or ignorance of the law. The test is an objective one. While <UNDER>it is possible to envisage that a new kind of right might arise that has not been hitherto protected, thus making it arguable that a civil proceeding might not be seen objectively as an appropriate means to seek to remedy,</UNDER> a battery causing personal injury is a classic example of the kind of wrong that is appropriate for redress by court action. A citizen is presumed to know the law of the land. [Emphasis added.]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>Aside from the limitation issues addressed in this endorsement, the balance of the defendant's Rule 21 motion asserts that this case involves &ldquo;a new kind of right ... that has not been hitherto protected&rdquo;: i.e. the duty owed (if any) by Crown attorneys to police officers who are engaged as participants and witnesses in the criminal justice process. On this basis, the exception posited by Low J. in <EM>Boyce</EM> is engaged.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Endorsement, Stinson J., January 4, 2017, at para. 19, Appeal Book, Tab 9</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Boyce v. Toronto (City) Police Services</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 23</P1></P>
<P>62. Stinson J. erred in finding that there is an &ldquo;arguable exception&rdquo; to the general rule that a claim is discovered when a claimant knows the material facts necessary to commence a claim where the right being asserted is &ldquo;novel&rdquo;, and that in such a case the running of the limitation period will be stopped until the claimant learns the legal significance of those material facts.</P>
<P>63. Stinson J.'s ruling was in error for four reasons:
<P1>i) The comment in <EM>Boyce</EM> regarding novel claims was <EM>obiter</EM> and has no precedential value;</P1>
<P1>ii) The comment in <EM>Boyce</EM> does not accord with the prevailing appellate authority which states that a limitation period begins to run with knowledge of material facts and not with knowledge of the legal significance of those facts, without exception;</P1>
<P1>iii) The statement in <EM>Boyce</EM> misinterprets s. 5(1)(a)(iv) of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM> by focusing on the claimant's knowledge of their prospects rather than the process; and</P1>
<P1>iv) The respondents' case also differs significantly from the medical malpractice cases in which it was found that an expert opinion was required to learn additional material facts necessary to commence a claim.</P1></P>
<BLOCK4><N>i)</N><TI>The Statement Regarding Novel Claims in Boyce was <EM>obiter</EM></TI>
<P>64. The statement made by Low J. in <CASEREF><SOC>Boyce v. Toronto</SOC></CASEREF> regarding novel claims is <EM>obiter</EM> and has no precedential value. The cause of action at issue in <EM>Boyce</EM>, battery, was not novel and no argument was made that the limitation period should be extended on that basis. Low J. did not reference any case law or conduct any analysis of the issue before making the <EM>obiter</EM> statement.</P>
<P>65. Rather, Low J. made the statement as an explanatory device, emphasizing that it was obvious that a lawsuit would objectively be seen as an appropriate means to seek a remedy in the case before her, a personal injury caused by battery, pursuant to sections 5(1)(a)(iv) and 5(b) of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM>.</P>
<P>66. That the statement was not intended to depart from established jurisprudence is further demonstrated by the fact that it has not been relied on in any case other than the decision below. It is submitted that in these circumstances Low J.'s statement should not be elevated to establish an &ldquo;arguable exception&rdquo; to the longstanding general rule governing discoverability discussed below.
<P1><EM>Boyce</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 23</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>ii)</N><TI>The Limitation Period Runs with the Knowledge of Material Facts, not the Appreciation of the Legal Significance of those Facts</TI>
<P>67. Low J.'s statement does not accord with binding appellate authority regarding discoverability. This Court has repeatedly held that a limitation period commences when a person has knowledge of the material facts to support his or her claim, not when they appreciate the legal significance of those facts.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Lochner v. Toronto (City) Police Services Board</SOC><CITE>2015 ONCA 626</CITE><PARANUM>7</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 12</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Unegbu v. WFG Securities of Canada Inc.</SOC><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> supra, at paras. 12-13, aff'd (C.A.)</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Nicholas v. McCarthy T&ea;trault</SOC><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 26&ndash;31, aff'd (C.A.) at para 1</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Lawless v. Anderson</SOC><CITE>[2011] O.J. No. 519</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> 21&ndash;28, 36, Book of Authorities, Tab 13</P1></P>
<P>68. In <CASEREF><SOC>Nicholas v. Tetrault</SOC></CASEREF>, a solicitor's negligence action, the plaintiff admitted that she knew the material facts underlying her claim against her former lawyer approximately nine years before commencing her claim. However, she argued that it was not until her new lawyer advised her shortly before she commenced her claim that she may have an action in negligence against her former lawyer that she &ldquo;discovered&rdquo; her claim and the limitation period began to run. The Court rejected that argument, finding:
<QUOTE><P>The discoverability principle governs the commencement of a limitation period and stipulates that a limitation period begins to run only after the plaintiff has the knowledge, or the means of acquiring the knowledge, of the existence of the facts that would support a claim for relief... Thus, a limitation period commences when the plaintiff discovers the underlying material facts or, alternatively, when the plaintiff ought to have discovered those facts by the exercise of reasonable diligence.</P>
<P><UNDER>The circumstance that a potential claimant may not appreciate the legal significance of the facts does not postpone the commencement of the limitation period if he or she knows or ought to know the existence of the material facts, which is to say the constitute elements of his or her cause of action. Error or ignorance of the law or legal consequences of the facts does not postpone the running of the limitation period</UNDER>... [citations omitted; emphasis added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Nicholas v. McCarthy T&ea;trault</SOC><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, supra, at paras. 26&ndash;31, aff'd (C.A.), <EM>supra</EM>, at para 1</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Unegbu v. WFG Securities of Canada Inc.</SOC><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 12-13, aff'd (C.A.) at para. 4</P1></P>
<P>69. In <CASEREF><SOC>Unegbu v. WFG Securities of Canada Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>, this Court upheld the motion judge's findings with respect to whether the limitation period begins to run upon knowledge of the material facts or upon the receipt of legal advice establishing the legal significance of those facts. The motions judge stated:
<QUOTE><P>It is important to note that s. 5(2) of the Act imposes a presumption that a claimant knows of the claim on the day the act or omission upon which the claim is based took place, unless the contrary is proved.</P>
<P>A party is not required to commence an action before they know that they have a &ldquo;substantial chance&rdquo; of success: see <CASEREF><SOC>Everding v. Skrijel</SOC></CASEREF>. However, <BOLD>the fact that a party does not appreciate the legal significance of the facts does not stop the limitation clock if that party knew of the material facts founding their claim:</BOLD> see <CASEREF><SOC>Nicholas v. McCarthy T&ea;trault</SOC></CASEREF>. The inquiry into the &ldquo;discovery&rdquo; of a claim is factual and the findings will vary from case to case. In <CASEREF><SOC>Lawless v. Anderson</SOC></CASEREF> the court explained that, &ldquo;The question to be posed is whether the prospective plaintiff knows enough facts on which to base an allegation of negligence against the defendant.&rdquo; [citations omitted]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Unegbu</EM> (S.C.J.), <EM>supra</EM> at paras. 12-13</P1></P>
<P>70. The Court rejected the plaintiff's claim that her case was similar to medical malpractice cases in which the courts had held that the limitation period did not start to run until the receipt of a medical opinion regarding the standard of care (which Courts have held provides a claimant with additional material facts relating to his or her claim and will be explored more fully below):
<QUOTE><P>The facts of this case could hardly be more different. On the plaintiff's own evidence, she believed the defendants had committed a wrong. There was no need for any advice of a technical nature to inform her that she had a cause of action. <BOLD>Even if I were to accept that the plaintiff did not realise that she could launch legal proceedings to recover her losses, the limitation period commences on the day upon which a reasonable person with the plaintiff's abilities and in her circumstances ought to have known of her remedy through a court action.</BOLD> I find that any reasonable person in the plaintiff's position ought to have known by May 2009, at the very latest, that a cause of action existed within the meaning of s. 5 of the Act. For the same reason, <BOLD>the plaintiff cannot rely on her ignorance of the law to postpone the commencement of the limitation period:</BOLD> see T&ea;trault, and <CASEREF><SOC>Boyce v. Toronto (City) Police Services Board</SOC></CASEREF>. [citations omitted]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Unegbu</EM> (S.C.J.), <EM>supra</EM> at para. 22</P1></P>
<P>71. In upholding the motions judge's decision, this Court stated:
<QUOTE><P>The appellant contends that until she received letters in June and October 2011 from the Mutual Fund Dealers Association of Canada responding to her complaint against the defendants, <BOLD>she was not aware that she had a right to sue the defendants.</BOLD> Those letters indicated that if the appellant wished to seek compensation for any loss she had suffered, she could either contact the Ombudsman for Banking Services and Investment or file a lawsuit.</P>
<P>The motion judge did not err in rejecting this argument. As he correctly found at para. 22 of his reasons, <BOLD>those letters did not supply the appellant with any factual or other information that she needed to know in order to assert a claim. The appellant knew she had suffered a loss not later than May 2009 and from that date, she firmly held the view that the appellants had wrongfully cheated her of her money.</BOLD> She had two years from that date to commence an action to bring her claim within the time allowed by the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM>, S.O. 2002, c. 24, sched. B and she failed to do so. <BOLD>It is well-established that a lack of appreciation of the legal significance of the facts grounding a claim does not stop the limitation from running:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Nicholas v. McCarthy Tetrault</SOC></CASEREF>. [citations mitted]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Unegbu</EM> (C.A), <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 3-4</P1></P>
<P>72. Although these decisions do not specifically deal with the concept of the receipt of legal advice in relation to a right which has not previously been recognized, the distinction is immaterial. The key point established by these cases is that the fact that a claimant does not know they have a cause of action does not operate to toll the limitation period.</P>
<P>73. The respondents in this action, who are sophisticated and have knowledge of the law, argued below that they did not know they had a &ldquo;right&rdquo; to sue Ontario because they are asserting a novel cause of action (which is more accurately described as the novel application of a recognized cause of action). This is the same argument made and rejected by this Court in <EM>Nicholas</EM> and <EM>Unegbu</EM>.</P>
<P>74. The &ldquo;novelty&rdquo; of the respondents' claims does not put them in a different position than the plaintiffs in <EM>Nicholas</EM> or <EM>Unegbu</EM>, or any other claimant who does not know the particular cause(s) of action that may be available to them until the receipt of legal advice. The jurisprudence is clear that ignorance of, or an error with respect to, the law cannot serve to extend a limitation period. Discoverability is focused on the knowledge of material facts and not the legal significance of those facts. As such there should be no exception to the discoverability rule for &ldquo;novel&rdquo; claims.</P>
<P>75. The respondents' Claim does not include any pleading about the novelty of the claim or contend that the plaintiffs discovered any additional material facts about the conduct of the Crown Attorneys after they consulted legal counsel. Indeed, it is apparent from the facts pleaded in the Claim that the respondents believed they had been wronged by Ms. Cressman and Mr. Armstrong prior to October 18, 2013, when they took steps to address what they refer to in the Claim as an &ldquo;egregious mistake&rdquo; by raising this matter with Ms. Alyea.</P>
<P>76. Rather than relying on the purported novelty of their cause of action, paragraph 50 of the Claim states:
<QUOTE><P>50. Several months after the Court of Appeal released its judgement in December of 2013, the officers retained counsel, who had the opportunity to review the entire record, and to listen to the audio of the oral arguments that were made in the Court of Appeal. It was only then that the officers were made fully aware of the tortious conduct of the defendant, and discovered their causes of action in negligence and malfeasance in a public office.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 50, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>77. The respondents therefore plead that after consulting with counsel, they learned that the conduct of the trial and the appellate Crowns was tortious and they had causes of action in misfeasance and negligence. In other words, they plead that after consulting with legal counsel they learned the legal effect of the conduct of the Crowns&mdash;not any additional material facts regarding the conduct of the Crowns. All material facts regarding the Crown Attorneys conduct were clearly discovered in 2012 and 2013. It is submitted that the motion judge erred in relying on <EM>Boyce</EM> and in finding that there is an arguable exception to the discoverability rule for &ldquo;novel&rdquo; claims.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>iii)</N><TI>The comment in Boyce misinterprets s. 5(1)(a)(iv) of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM> by focusing on the claimant's knowledge of their prospects rather than the process</TI>
<P>78. Premising the interpretation of s. 5(1)(a)(iv) of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM> on a claimant's legal knowledge misapprehends the meaning and purpose of that provision. Section 5(1)(a)(iv) requires that in order for the claim to be &ldquo;discovered&rdquo; for limitations purposes, the plaintiff must know that &ldquo;having regard to the nature of the injury, loss or damage, a proceeding would be an <BOLD>appropriate</BOLD> means to seek to remedy it&rdquo;.
<P1><EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM>, S.O. 2002 c. 24, Sched. B, at s. 5</P1></P>
<P>79. The provision is concerned with when a claimant knew that a lawsuit was an appropriate process to pursue, not when the claimant knew the particular grounds for the lawsuit; the defences to be contested; and the likelihood of success. While s. 5(1)(a)(iv) can have the effect of &ldquo;delaying the commencement&rdquo; of a limitation period, it does so only until a lawsuit becomes an appropriate means of recovery.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Nasr Hospitaiity Services Inc. v. Intact Insurance</SOC><CITE>[2017] O.J. No. 3552</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras. 27&ndash;35, Book of Authorities, Tab 14</P1></P>
<P>80. The determination of when a lawsuit becomes appropriate is a question of process, not legal knowledge. For example, a lawsuit may become appropriate after other dispute resolution mechanisms are exhausted, or following recourse to statutory remedies. As this Court recently held in <CASEREF><SOC>Tapak v. Non-Marine Underwriters</SOC></CASEREF>, section 5(1)(a)(iv) &ldquo;is intended to address the situation where there may be an avenue of relief outside of a court proceeding that a party can use to remedy their &ldquo;injury, loss or damage&rdquo;.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Tapak v. Non-Marine Underwriters</SOC><CITE>2018 ONCA 168</CITE><PARANUM>13</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 15</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Independence Plaza 1 Associates, L.L.C. v. Figliolini</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 44</CITE><PARANUM>74&ndash;79</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 16</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Brown v. Baum</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 325</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras. 17&ndash;21, Book of Authorities, Tab 17</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Market Insurance Co. of Canada v. ING Insurance Co. of Canada</SOC><CITE>2012 ONCA 218</CITE><PARANUM>34</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 18</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>407 ETR Concession Co. v. Day</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 709</CITE><PARANUM>33&ndash;53</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 19</P1></P>
<P>81. In <EM>Boyce</EM>, Low J. cites the prospect of a &ldquo;&lsquo;new kind of right&rdquo; in considering s. 5(1)(a)(iv) in the context of s. 5(1)(b) of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM>. In doing so, Low. J. was positing a circumstance in which a reasonable person would not know that a lawsuit would be the appropriate means for pursuing a remedy. However, by basing this analysis on the claimant's knowledge of a legal right, rather than his or her awareness that a lawsuit was an appropriate process for recovery, Low J. misapplied s. 5(1)(a)(iv). In elevating this analysis to an exception to discoverability, Stinson J. erred.</P>
<P>82. Reframing s. 5(1)(a)(iv) as a tool for disputing discoverability based on a claimant's legal knowledge runs counter to the goals of establishing certainty, promoting diligence and preventing unfairness which underpin limitations legislation. If this approach were accepted, any claim based on rights which are either not widely known or not yet recognized would no longer be barred by the standard two-year limitation period.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Nasr Hospitality Services Inc. v. Intact Insurance</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 35</P1></P>
<P>83. The instant case demonstrates the unworkability of this approach. In opposing this motion, the respondents rely on rights premised on duties that are not yet recognized or protected in law. In particular, in their negligence claim the respondents assert rights based on an as yet unrecognized duty of care owed by Crown Attorneys to investigating police officers. In their misfeasance claim, the respondents assert a right based on a novel interpretation of the statutory oath sworn by Crown Attorneys.</P>
<P>84. If the approach in <EM>Boyce</EM> and in the Court below were adopted, the respondents and claimants like them could never &lsquo;discover&rsquo; their claim for the purposes of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM>. Under this approach, as long as the right being asserted has not been recognized by a Court, a lawsuit would not be &ldquo;an appropriate means to seek a remedy&rdquo; under s. 5(1)(a)(iv). This approach misinterprets s. 5(1)(a)(iv) and would severely impair the operation of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM> if allowed to stand.</P>
<P>85. The proper interpretation of s. 5(1)(a)(iv) turns on the consideration of whether a lawsuit was an appropriate means for a remedy in light of the other available options. The respondents rely on the meeting with their lawyers detailed at paragraph 50 of the Claim in arguing that the Claim is not statute-barred under s. 4 of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM>. However, that paragraph merely discusses the particulars of a lawsuit: none of the facts pleaded would serve to delay the commencement of the limitation period pursuant to s. 5(1)(a)(iv). Consequently, the limitations period began running in December 2013 at the latest and expired prior to the commencement of the Claim with respect to the allegations made both the trial and appellate Crowns.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>iv)</N><TI>The Respondents' Claim differs from the Medical Malpractice Cases Where Expert Advice was Required to Learn Material Facts</TI>
<P>86. Finally, the respondents' situation differs significantly from the medical malpractice cases in which it was found that an expert opinion was required to provide the claimants with knowledge of material facts required to commence their claims.</P>
<P>87. First, in modern medical malpractice cases the Courts have recognized that, in some cases, a claimant will require advice from someone who is medically trained to assist him or her in discovering the <UNDER>material facts necessary</UNDER> to commence their claim. The Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Lawless v. Anderson</SOC></CASEREF> gives the example of a claimant who only discovered that she had not been an appropriate candidate for the cosmetic procedure she received and that the wrong instrument had been used to perform that procedure after receiving a College of Physicians and Surgeons of Ontario discipline decision regarding her doctor. The Court found that these were material facts necessary to commence her claim.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Lawless v. Anderson</SOC></CASEREF> <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 21&ndash;26</P1></P>
<P>88. This differs from the respondents' case because the respondents do not allege they gained knowledge of additional <UNDER>material facts</UNDER> regarding the conduct or actions of the Crown Attorneys after receiving advice from their counsel. Instead, they gained legal knowledge. As noted above, ignorance or error with respect to the law has no bearing on discoverability and the receipt of leg al advice does not extend the limitation period <UNDER>when all the material facts were already known</UNDER> as they were in this case. It is for this reason that the fact that the respondents claim may be &ldquo;novel&rdquo; is a distinction without a difference.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>3)</N><TI>THE MOTION JUDGE ERRED IN FAILING TO CONSIDER THE EFFECT OF THE RESPONDENTS' FAILURE TO PURSUE THEIR CLAIM WITH DILIGENCE</TI>
<P>89. Finally, Ontario submits that Stinson J. also erred by failing to consider the effect of the respondents' admission in paragraph 50 of their claim that they did not retain counsel until several months after this Court's December 12, 2013 decision on Mr. Singh's appeal.</P>
<P>90. In <CASEREF><SOC>Longo v. McLaren Art Centre</SOC></CASEREF>, this Court stated that a claimant is required to act with due diligence in determining if he has a claim. A limitation period will not be tolled while a claimant sits idle and takes no steps to investigate the matters set out in section 5(1) of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Limitations Act, 2002, S.O. 2002</EM>, c 24, Schedule B at s. 5(1) and (2)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This includes acting with diligence in requesting an expert opinion.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Longo v. McLaren Art Centre</SOC><CITE>2014 ONCA 526</CITE><PARANUM>42</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 20</P1>
<P1>See also <EM>Unegbu</EM> (S.C.J.), <EM>supra</EM> at paras, 12-13, (C.A.), <EM>supra</EM> at paras. 3 - 4</P1></P>
<P>91. The extent of the required action will depend on the circumstances of the case and a consideration of whether the claimant has acted reasonably; this includes an analysis of the nature of the potential claim as well as the particular circumstances of the claimant. In this case, the respondents, who are part of the justice system and are sophisticated, were clearly aggrieved by the conduct of the trial Crowns and knew the material facts necessary to commence their claim regarding their conduct before October 18, 2013. The respondents were clearly aggrieved by the conduct of the appellate Crown and knew all the material facts necessary to commence a claim regarding her conduct at the time the decision of this Court was released or shortly thereafter. Nevertheless, they waited several months after the appeal before even consulting legal counsel regarding a possible claim. This does not meet the diligence standard required of claimants.</P>
<P>92. The motion judge did not conduct any analysis with respect to the fact that the respondents clearly &ldquo;slept on their rights&rdquo;. Even if it were ultimately determined that the respondents' receipt of legal advice is a relevant factor given the &ldquo;novelty&rdquo; of the claim, the respondents failed to seek that advice with reasonable diligence. The failure of Stinson J. to consider this issue and apply the relevant law, even though it was before him, was an error. Further, the fact that the respondents failed to pursue their claim with diligence is a factor that should militate in favour of the Ontario with respect to the expiration of the limitation period.
<P1><EM>Longo</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>. at para. 42</P1>
<P1>See also <EM>Unegbu</EM> (S.C.J.), <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 12&ndash;14, (C.A,), <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 3-4</P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ORDER REQUESTED</TI>
<P>93. Ontario requests an Order allowing Ontario's motion to strike out the respondents' Statement of Claim and dismiss the action because it is statute-barred by s. 4 of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM>, with costs.</P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED.</BOLD></P>
<P>March 22, 2018</P>
<P>&ellip35; <BOLD>Heather Mackay and Ananthan Sinnadurai</BOLD></P>
<P>Counsel for the Attorney General for Ontario</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
