<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">I. OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. The Appellant, Attorney General of Ontario (<BOLD>&ldquo;Attorney General&rdquo;</BOLD>), appeals the decision of the Honourable Justice Stinson dated January 4, 2017, in which His Honour dismissed the Attorney General's motion to strike the claim of the Respondents on the basis of the expiry of the applicable limitation period.</P>
<P>2. The Attorney General's motion to strike the claim on the basis of the expiration of the applicable limitation period was one of three grounds that the Attorney General brought to strike the Respondents' Statement of Claim. The other two were:
<P1>i. That the action had failed to disclose a reasonable cause of action because Crown Attorneys are not liable to negligence or misfeasance in public office. They can have no liability to anyone other than a person they had prosecuted; and</P1>
<P1>ii. Allegations of negligence and misfeasance failed to plead the constituent elements of those torts and failed to plead the necessary material facts to support those causes of action.</P1></P>
<P>3. While Stinson J. bifurcated the Attorney General's motion to strike, in order to determine the Limitations issue first, the entire argument and the position of the Attorney General and the Respondents on all of the issues in the motion strike were before him, including, the Attorney General's position that the Respondents' claim in negligence was not just &ldquo;novel&rdquo;, but rather, it did not exist in law.</P>
<P>4. Therefore, this Appeal by the Attorney General on the limitations period issue raises the obvious question: How can the Attorney General argue that the Respondents should have had knowledge of the material facts to support their claim&mdash;a claim that the Attorney General argues does not exist in law? The obvious answer: it can't.</P>
<P>5. In addition, as important, the Ontario Court of Appeal has repeatedly emphasized that limitations issues should not be determined in the absence of a complete factual record after pleadings have closed unless it is &ldquo;plain and obvious&rdquo; from the Statement of Claim that the limitation period has expired. As Stinson J. correctly found, this case is a novel claim asserting a new kind of right, and the limitation issue involves legal and factual complexities regarding discoverability. For this reason, it is not plain and obvious that the limitation period expired.</P>
<P>6. The Attorney General seeks a determination on a defence which it has not pleaded (as no Statement of Defence has been filed) and in the absence of proper evidence on discoverability. A full hearing on the basis of a comprehensive evidentiary record is required to make a determination on the facts and the complex legal issues.</P>
<P>7. Consequently, it is respectfully submitted that the Attorney General's appeal should be dismissed.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">II. FACTS</TI>
<P>8. The Respondents to this motion rely on the Statement of Claim's more comprehensive version of facts, the most essential of which are provided below.</P>
<P>9. The Plaintiffs, Jamie Clark (<BOLD>&ldquo;Sgt. Clark&rdquo;</BOLD>), Donald Belanger (<BOLD>&ldquo;Det. Sgt. Belanger&rdquo;</BOLD>) and Steven Watts (<BOLD>&ldquo;Det. Sgt. Watts&rdquo;</BOLD>), (collectively, the <BOLD>&ldquo;Officers&rdquo;</BOLD> or <BOLD>&ldquo;Respondents&rdquo;</BOLD>), are police officers with the Toronto Police Service. They were members of the Hold-Up Squad at the relevant time.</P>
<P>10. In February of 2009, the Officers began investigating an armed robbery wherein the perpetrators brandished a firearm, zip-tied the victim, duct-taped his mouth and forcibly confined him while stealing approximately $389,000 of copper tubing.
<P1><BOLD>Officers' <UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER>, June 22, 2016 (&ldquo;<UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER>&rdquo;) at para. 7.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>11. On or about June 11, 2009, the officers arrested Neil Singh (<BOLD>&ldquo;Singh&rdquo;</BOLD>) and Randy Maharaj (<BOLD>&ldquo;Maharaj&rdquo;</BOLD>) in connection with the crime. Singh and Maharaj were charged with armed robbery, forceful confinement and conspiracy to commit both offences. On the night of the arrests, Singh provided a false exculpatory statement to the police. Maharaj confessed to involvement in the crime, which he said was perpetrated with Singh. Both statements were video recorded.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 9&ndash;11.</BOLD></P1></P>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Procedural History</EM></TI>
<P>12. During a June 12, 2009 bail hearing, counsel for Maharaj said that his client had suffered Injuries&mdash;bumps and scratches behind his ear&mdash;during the arrest. Counsel did not allege any assaultive conduct by the Officers and did not allege that there was an injury to Maharaj's rib.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 10&ndash;13.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>13. At the preliminary hearing in the Ontario Court of Justice held between July and November 2010, the video statements were admitted into evidence, and voluntariness was not challenged.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>It was not suggested that the statements should not be admitted on the basis that they were obtained under threats or as a product of oppressive circumstances.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> During the hearing, counsel for Maharaj suggested that his client had been assaulted during the arrest. The Officers were called as Crown witnesses. They gave evidence and vehemently denied the allegations of improper or assaultive conduct. The Crown did not suggest, at that time, that the Officers were committing perjury. Both accused were committed to stand trial in the Superior Court of Justice.</P>
<P>14. At the trial, beginning November 28, 2011, Crown Attorney Sheila Cressman (<BOLD>&ldquo;Ms. Cressman&rdquo;</BOLD>) had carriage of the prosecution. In advance of the trial, Maharaj's counsel brought an application to stay the proceedings and to exclude his confession, based on the doctrines of abuse of process and involuntariness. Maharaj alleged he was seriously beaten by police after his arrest but prior to the confession, and sustained a rib injury. Maharaj's counsel provided Ms. Cressman with an X-Ray purporting to support Marahaj's claim that he had a rib injury. He also provided the Crown with a transcript from the bail hearing. The Crown would have been aware of the allegations of mistreatment based on a review of the preliminary hearing transcript where the accusations were first made.</P>
<P>15. Ms. Cressman consulted Dr. Farley Moss (<BOLD>&ldquo;Dr. Moss&rdquo;</BOLD>) at Scarborough Centenary Hospital regarding the X-Ray. Dr. Moss confirmed the X-Ray showed a fractured rib, and said that this injury would cause excruciating pain if a person moved his upper arms or body. Dr. Moss said it was <BOLD><UNDER>possible</UNDER></BOLD> the rib injury occurred on the day of the arrest.</P>
<P>16. Ms. Cressman failed to take further obvious and appropriate steps to investigate Maharaj's allegation. In particular, Ms. Cressman:
<P1>(a) never asked Dr. Moss to review the video taped statement, in which Maharaj is seen making various movements with his arms that were incompatible with having a fresh rib injury;</P1>
<P1>(b) never asked Dr. Moss further questions regarding other potential time periods in which the injury could have occurred;</P1>
<P1>(c) never made inquiries of staff at Maplehurst Detention Centre (<BOLD>&ldquo;Maplehurst&rdquo;</BOLD>), where Maharaj was incarcerated during his trial, about Maharaj, even though she was in possession of Maharaj's medical records from the facility that showed no complaints about a rib injury any time after his arrest;</P1>
<P1>(d) did not properly review the transcripts of the bail hearing to understand the inconsistent injuries reported then as opposed to those reported at the time of the stay application; and</P1>
<P1>(e) did not seek further advice or comment from the Officers who had testified at the preliminary hearing and adamantly denied assaulting Maharaj.</P1></P>
<P>17. Despite her failure to take any steps to properly investigate the unsubstantiated allegation, Ms. Cressman, in consultation with senior Crown Attorney Frank Armstrong (<BOLD>&ldquo;Mr. Armstrong&rdquo;</BOLD>), decided that Maharaj's statement would not be admissible because of involuntariness and therefore there would be no case against him. Mr. Armstrong did not direct Ms. Cressman or anyone else to conduct a further investigation into the allegation. The Crown decided to stay the charges against Maharaj on November 22, 2011.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 16&ndash;22 and 28.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>18. Singh's trial commenced on November 28, 2011. Singh also sought to stay the proceedings against him on the basis of abusive police conduct. He falsely testified that he had been assaulted by the Officers. He relied on the purported mistreatment of Maharaj at the hands of the police to buttress his claim. On the ensuing application, Maharaj provided false evidence that he had been assaulted by the Officers.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at para. 19.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>19. Although aware that the Plaintiffs had previously testified under oath that they did not engage in any assaultive conduct and would testify to that effect if called as witnesses, Ms. Cressman called no evidence to challenge or contradict the false testimony. Rather, she essentially accepted that the alleged assaults occurred. She did so notwithstanding that she had assured Det. Sgt. Watt that he and the other Officers would be called as witnesses. However, after the first day of hearing, Ms. Cressman informed Det. Sgt. Watt she would not require the Officers' evidence. Though Det. Sgt. Watt expressed his concern to Ms. Cressman about how this decision would adversely affect the outcome of the case and findings that might be made against the Officers, Ms. Cressman would not change her position and the Officers were prevented from testifying.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 19&ndash;21.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>20. The Officers were not parties to the proceeding involving the Defendant and Singh and, to the knowledge of the Crown, had no standing to adduce evidence or make representations to the Court. The Officers relied on the Defendant to ensure that findings of illegal and improper conduct were not made against them in the absence of a full and complete record. Although the Crown could not control whether a Court might make those findings, the Crown could control whether the trial Court had all information relevant to the Officers' conduct given the potential for adverse findings against the Officers.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 20-21, 25.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>21. Ms. Cressman did not require Singh's counsel to prove the nature of the alleged assault, nor did she test the evidence in any way. She simply conceded that the assaultive conduct, as falsely alleged, had occurred and that there had been a serious <EM>Charter</EM> violation. Ms. Cressman knew at the time that doing so would have serious repercussions not only for the case she was prosecuting but for the Officers as well.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at para. 22.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>22. The judgment of Justice Thorburn was released on March 28, 2012. Singh had been convicted by a jury of armed robbery and forceful confinement. In the absence of any evidence from the Crown challenging the false testimony of Singh and Maharaj, Justice Thorburn made findings of fact that the Officers assaulted Singh and Maharaj exactly as alleged, which was described at length in the judgment. Though Justice Thorburn dismissed Singh's stay application, she reduced Singh's sentence because of the Officers' &ldquo;brutality&rdquo; and &ldquo;thoroughly reprehensible&rdquo; behaviour in the case.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 23-24.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>23. After Justice Thorburn's ruling was released, the Officers' reputations were irreparably harmed. Her findings were widely reported in the mainstream media and on the internet.</P>
<P>24. Following the judgment, the Crown Law Office&mdash;Criminal notified the Chief of Police of their concerns about the Officers' conduct. The Special Investigations Unit (<BOLD>&ldquo;SIU&rdquo;</BOLD>) invoked its mandate to conduct an investigation. However, Maharaj refused to be interviewed or to participate in the investigation, and the SIU withdrew its mandate in July 2012.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at para. 29.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>25. After the SIU withdrew its mandate, the Toronto Police Service Professional Standards Unit (<BOLD>&ldquo;TPSPS&rdquo;</BOLD>) conducted a comprehensive and independent review of the allegations of misconduct against the Officers. The investigators concluded that, based on an analysis of all the evidence, the allegations that the Officers used excessive force could not be substantiated.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at para. 30.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>26. In and around November 2012, the Crown Law Office was made aware of these new material facts that demonstrated the serious injustice that had been done to the Officers. The Crown took no action in response.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 31, 43.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>27. Singh appealed the judgment. Before the appeal was argued, Det. Sgt. Watt met with Amy Alyea (<BOLD>&ldquo;Ms. Alyea&rdquo;</BOLD>), who was going to argue the appeal on behalf of the Crown. He told Ms. Alyea that an egregious mistake had occurred. He advised Ms. Alyea of the results of the TPSPS report, of which she had a copy, and of Ms. Cressman's conduct.</P>
<P>28. Despite Det. Sgt. Watt's efforts, Ms. Alyea: (i) took no steps to investigate further, (ii) took no steps to rectify and repair the damage that had been done to the Officers' reputations, and (iii) took no steps to prepare and file an application to introduce fresh evidence before the Court of Appeal. During oral arguments in the appeal, the Court asked several questions about the Officers' behaviour, but Ms. Alyea never adequately advised the Court of the new material facts the Crown had learned or of the TPSPS's exculpatory findings regarding the Officers' conduct. Any attempt made by Ms. Alyea to alert the Court to the TPSPS findings or the substance of the report fell far below what was required in the circumstances. The report was not properly before the Court nor had it been properly disclosed to counsel for Mr. Singh.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 32-33, 35, 43 and 47.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>29. On December 12, 2013, the Court of Appeal released its judgment, in which it granted the appellant's stay application. The Court condemned the &ldquo;egregious nature of the police misconduct,&rdquo; which it equated with &ldquo;torture.&rdquo; It found that the alleged abusive interrogation techniques were &ldquo;calculated, prolonged and skilfully choreographed.&rdquo; The Court stated that Crown counsel was unable to provide any details of the results of the TPSPS investigation. The Court adverted several times to the fact that the Defence's allegations were uncontradicted or uncontested by the Crown. The Court found the case for a stay more compelling because the allegations of &ldquo;serious criminal conduct&rdquo; by the police had gone unchallenged.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at para. 35.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>30. The Court of Appeal's judgment was also widely reported in the mainstream media and on the internet. Articles about the case repeated Singh's and Maharaj's false and defamatory allegations, and condemned the Officers' behaviour.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 36-37.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>31. Following the Court of Appeal judgment, the SIU re-opened their investigation. Maharaj agreed to be interviewed. The investigators reviewed all of the records and obtained opinion evidence. That investigation concluded that Maharaj's injury post-dated the time of arrest, and that his physical demeanour in the videotaped statement was inconsistent with his having sustained any rib injury at the time of arrest (during his video-recorded interview Maharaj is moving about in a way that would not have been possible had he suffered the cracked rib injury he alleged he had suffered at the hands of the Officers). The SIU found that the allegations by Maharaj were not substantiated.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at para. 38.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>32. Also following the Court of Appeal judgment, the Chief of the Toronto Police Service asked the Ontario Provincial Police (<BOLD>&ldquo;OPP&rdquo;</BOLD>) to conduct an independent review of the TPSPS investigation. The OPP review was conducted by an experienced, high-ranking investigator. On April 9, 2015, the OPP investigator concluded the TPSPS review had been thorough and she had no reason to refute its conclusions that the allegations of police misconduct were unsubstantiated.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at para. 39.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The Respondents Commence an Action Against the Attorney General of Ontario</EM></TI>
<P>33. As alleged in the Respondents' Statement of Claim, several months after the Court of Appeal released its judgment, the Officers retained counsel. Counsel had the opportunity to review the entire record and listen to the audio of the oral arguments that were made in the Court of Appeal.</P>
<P>34. After due consideration, counsel formed a legal opinion that they communicated to the Officers: the conduct of the Defendant may be tortious, and a novel claim in negligence and misfeasance in a public office could be pursued. It was only at this point that the Officers discovered that there was a viable claim, albeit a novel one.</P>
<P>35. The Respondents issued their Claim on June 22, 2016. In it, they claim as against the Attorney General damages for negligence and misfeasance in a public office.</P>
<P>36. In particular, the Claim alleges that Crown Attorneys owe a duty of care to investigating police officers and that this duty was breached through the conduct of Ms. Cressman, Ms. Alyea, and their superiors. The Claim also alleges that Ms. Cressman, Ms. Alyea and their superiors engaged in deliberate and unlawful conduct that they knew to be inconsistent with their professional obligations, and that they did so in bad faith, with the knowledge that this misconduct would likely injure the Officers.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The Attorney General's Motion to Strike</EM></TI>
<P>37. The Attorney General brought a motion to strike the Claim pursuant to Rules 21 and 25 on the basis that:
<P1>(a) The action is statute-barred because the limitation period has expired: the Plaintiffs failed to commence it within two years of discovering the material facts on which the Claim is based. In particular, the Plaintiffs were aware of the material facts giving rise to their claim based on the conduct of Ms. Cressman by at least July 2012. The Plaintiffs were aware of the material facts giving rise to their claim based on the conduct of Ms. Alyea by at least December 12, 2013;</P1>
<P1>(b) The claims in negligence and misfeasance are not tenable at law. As Crown Attorneys do not owe a duty of care to investigating police officers, it is plain and obvious that the claim does not disclose a reasonable cause of action in negligence and has no reasonable prospect of success. As the Attorney General states in its factum, &ldquo;[Aside from malicious prosecution,] no other action in tort is available against a Crown Attorney&rdquo;; and</P1>
<P1>(c) The claim in misfeasance is frivolous and vexations, as it did not provide full particulars to support this cause of action.</P1></P>
<P>38. Stinson J. bifurcated the motion, and heard arguments on the limitation issue first. On January 4, 2017, Stinson J. dismissed the Attorney General's motion to strike on the basis of the limitation period argument by finding:
<P1>(a) Plaintiffs should not routinely be deprived of the opportunity to place a complete factual context before the court, by a defendant who asks the court to decide a limitation defence before it is pleaded;</P1>
<P1>(b) The exception to this rule is where it is plain and obvious from a review of a statement of claim that no additional facts could be asserted that would alter the conclusion that a limitation period has expired;</P1>
<P1>(c) The exception will not apply where the case involves legal or factual complexities that bear on questions of discoverability and limitation periods;</P1>
<P1>(d) The central issue regarding the limitation period in this case involves s. 5(1)(a)(iv) of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM>, which provides that &ldquo;a claim is discovered on the earlier of, the day on which the person with the claim first knew... that, having regard to the nature of the injury, loss or damage, a proceeding would be an appropriate means to seek to remedy it&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>(e) While generally, the failure to appreciate the legal significance of discoverable Facts does not stop a limitation period from running, there is an arguable exception for novel claims, as was recognized by Low J. in <CASEREF><SOC>Boyce v. Toronto (City) Police Services</SOC></CASEREF>;</P1>
<P1>(f) As the Plaintiffs assert a novel claim, with &ldquo;a new kind of right,&rdquo; the exception is engaged in this case. Specifically, there is greater legal and factual complexity to the issue of discoverability, as it is not clear the Plaintiffs should have known that a civil remedy was appropriate before they obtained legal advice;</P1>
<P1>(g) It is not plain and obvious that the limitation issue will be decided against the Plaintiffs, and the issue should only be determined after a complete factual context is placed before the Court.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Clark v. Ontario (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 43</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Clark</EM>&rdquo;), Responding Parties' Book of Authorities (&ldquo;Respondent's BOA&rdquo;), Tab 1</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">III. ISSUES AND THE LAW</TI>
<P>39. The sole issue to be determined on this appeal is whether appeal Stinson J. erred in dismissing the Attorney General's motion to strike the Respondents' claim on the basis that the applicable limitation period expired. It is the Respondents' position that he made no error in doing so.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Motion To Strike Based On A Limitation Period Is Not Available In This Particular Case</EM></TI>
<P>40. The Respondents respectfully submit that Stinson J. applied the correct and established legal principles to the facts of this case, and exercised his discretion appropriately.</P>
<P>41. Stinson J. correctly cited binding appellate authority from <CASEREF><SOC>Beardsley v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> for the proposition that, save in exceptional cases, courts do not entertain motions to decide limitation period issues prior to service of a statement of defence. The Court of Appeal in that case explained the principle underlying this policy:
<QUOTE><P>Plaintiffs would be deprived of the opportunity to place a complete factual context before the court if limitation defences were determined, on a routine basis, without being pleaded. Adherence to rules that ensure procedural fairness is an integral component of an appearance of justice. The appearance of justice takes on an even greater significance where claims are made against those who administer the law.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM> at para. 13, citing</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Beardsley v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>57 O.R. (3d) 1</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Beardsley</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 22, Respondent's BOA, Tabs 1 and 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>42. The Court stated that a motion to strike based on the expiry of a limitation period could only prevail in the exceptional instance where it is plain and obvious from the statement of claim that no additional facts could be asserted that would alter the conclusion that a limitation period had expired.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM> at para. 13, citing <EM>Beardsley</EM> at para. 21, Respondent's BOA, Tabs 1 and 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>43. Stinson J. cited Brown J. to explain that this exception can only apply where the material facts are clear and applicable law is well-established:
<QUOTE><P>In <EM>Beardsley</EM> the possibility of bringing a Rule 21.01(1)(a) motion before the close of pleadings was discussed in the context of a determination as to whether an action was statute-barred&mdash;for example, such as in cases where the injuries suffered in a car accident occurred on a date certain and nothing more can be said about that fact. That type of case is a far cry from the complex claim asserted in this proceeding.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM> at para. 14, citing</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Portuguese Canadian Credit Union Ltd v CUMIS General Insurance</SOC><CITE>[2010] O.J. No. 4736</CITE><PARANUM>33</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's BOA, Tabs 1 and 3.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>44. The case at bar is also extremely complex, dealing in uncharted legal waters. As Stinson J. noted, the Ontario Court of Appeal has stated that the &ldquo;plain and obvious&rdquo; exception set out in <EM>Beardsley</EM> must be confined to cases where there are no legal or factual complexities.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM> at para. 15, citing</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Real Estate Association v. American Home Assurance Company</SOC><CITE>2015 ONCA 389</CITE><PARANUM>2</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's BOA, Tabs 1 and 4.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>45. This Court had reason to revisit the &ldquo;exception principle&rdquo; set out in <EM>Beardsley</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, in the recent case of <CASEREF><SOC>Salewski v. Lalonde</SOC></CASEREF>. The Respondents agree and adopt the summary of the factual matrix and underlying principles in <EM>Salweski</EM>, <EM>ibid</EM>, as summarized in paragraphs 43 to 48 of the Appellant's factum.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Salewski v. Lalonde</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 515 (CanLii)</CITE><PARANUM>46</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's BOA, Tab 5.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>46. What is most important is that this Court raises the bar even higher for a defendant who intends to rely on the <EM>Beardsley</EM> exception in context of a rule 21.01(a) motion to strike a claim based on the expiration of a limitation period BEFORE a Statement of Defence has been served and filed. As the Court states:
<QUOTE><P>Plaintiffs would be deprived of the opportunity to place a complete factual context before the court if limitation defences were determined, on a routine basis, without being pleaded. Adherence to rules that ensure procedural fairness is an integral component of an appearance of justice. The appearance of justice takes on an even greater significance where claims are made against those who administer the law.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> at para. 13, citing <EM>Beardsley</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 22, Respondent's BOA, Tabs 1 and 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>47. In addition, and most applicable to the case at bar, this Court further stated that this <EM>Beardsley</EM> exception was never intended to &ldquo;apply in a situation such as this, where the fact situation is not straightforward and has not fully been defined by the pleadings, and where the Respondents seek to advance what may be a novel claim&rdquo;.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Salewski v. Lalonde</SOC></CASEREF>, <BOLD><EM>supra</EM> at para. 46, Respondent's BOA, Tab 5.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>48. This Court applied the principle in the recent case of <CASEREF><SOC>Ridel v. Goldberg</SOC></CASEREF>. The sole issue is whether the motion judge erred in ruling on a rule 21.01(1)(a) motion that the action was barred by a two year limitation period. There is extensive argument before the Court with respect to knowledge and specifically, what the Appellants (Plaintiffs) knew or did not know in relation to the specific requirements as set out in section 5(1)(a)(iv) of the <EM>Limitations Act</EM>. The Court stated that is not appropriate because a more complete record was required to permit the Court to determine the issues raised by the parties on the appeal:
<QUOTE><P>In our view, it would not be appropriate for this court to rule on the issues raised by the parties on the limited record that is before us. As indicated, this was a Rule 21.01(1)(a) motion. We have only the pleadings. There is no evidence before the court concerning what has become the main focus of the appellants' submission, namely, the relationship between e3m and Goldberg and the control he is alleged to have exercised over e3m in relation to the claim advanced by the appellants. Nor is the record adequate to permit us to properly consider the application of <EM>Indcondo</EM> in the specific context of the facts of this case.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ridel v. Goldberg</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 739 (CanLii)</CITE><PARANUM>11</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's BOA, Tab 6.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>49. Finally, in the recent case of <CASEREF><SOC>Sicilian Maceri Services v. OGO Fibers Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>, a motion was brought under rule 21.01(1)(a) to strike a Statement of Claim that had been issued in 2017 to enforce a 2014 judgment of the Italian Court. The Defendants, like the Appellants in this case, argued that there was no need to file a Statement of Defence, that it was plain and obvious from a review of the Statement of Claim that no additional facts could be asserted that would alter the conclusion that a limitation period had expired. Fragomeni J. disagreed, reviewing the principles set out in <EM>Beardsley</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, and <CASEREF><SOC>Salewski v. Lalonde</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, he found that if he granted the motion, it would deprive the plaintiff from introducing facts in response to a limitation defense that could move the expiry date of the limitation period, and that the plaintiff would have an opportunity to introduce facts that could impact on the Court fixing the appropriate date from which the limitation period should commence.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Sicilian Maceri Services v. OGO Fibers Inc.</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 1342 (CanLii)</CITE><PARANUM>17-18</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's BOA, Tab 7.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>50. There is no onus on the Respondents to articulate what facts could be pleaded, that would alter the conclusion that the limitation period expired. As this Court reiterated in <CASEREF><SOC>Salewski v. Lalonde</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM> and <CASEREF><SOC>Ridel v. Goldberg</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, and as Fragomeni J. reiterated in <CASEREF><SOC>Sicilian Maceri Services v. OGO Fibers Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, a complete record is necessary, i.e.: Statement of Defence and Reply pleading to permit a court to determine the issues surrounding the expiration of a limitation period. That record is not present in this case, and therefore it is not plain and obvious that the limitation period had expired before the claim was commenced, and as such, there is a genuine issue of discoverability still to be determined.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The Motion Judge Did Not Err In Finding There Is An Exception To The Discoverability Rule For &ldquo;Novel&rdquo; Claims</EM></TI>
<P>51. Stinson J. was correct in finding that a novel claim may provide an exception to the general rule that failure to appreciate the legal significance of discoverable facts does not stop a limitation period from running.</P>
<P>52. Generally, the failure to appreciate the legal significance of discoverable facts does not stop the limitation period from running. However, as Stinson J. recognized, there is an arguable exception for <UNDER>novel claims</UNDER>. In <CASEREF><SOC>Boyce v. Toronto (City) Police Services</SOC></CASEREF>, Low J. stated:
<QUOTE><P>Section 5(1)(a)(iv) does not import an idiosyncratic period calibrated by the claimant's familiarity with or ignorance of the law. The test is an objective one. <UNDER>While it is possible to envisage that a new kind of right might arise that has not been hitherto protected, thus making it arguable that a civil proceeding might not be seen objectively as an appropriate means to seek to remedy</UNDER>, a battery causing personal injury is a classic example of the kind of wrong that is appropriate for redress by court action. A citizen is presumed to know the law of the land.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM> at para. 18, citing</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Boyce v. Toronto (City) Police Services</SOC><CITE>2011 ONSC 53</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Boyce</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 23, Respondent's BOA, Tabs 1 and 8.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>53. The case at bar meets this exception. The Statement of Claim asserts a novel claim, involving new kinds of rights, with complex legal intricacies that have not yet been recognized by courts. The Claim alleges that courts <UNDER>should</UNDER> recognize that Crown Attorneys owe a duty of care to police officers who are engaged as participants and witnesses in the criminal justice process. On this basis, Stinson J. found that the exception for novel claims posited by Low J. in <EM>Boyce</EM> was engaged in the case at bar.</P>
<P>54. As the Respondents assert a novel claim&mdash;one that has not yet been recognized in law&mdash;they could not have known that a civil remedy was appropriate before they obtained legal advice. The Plaintiffs may have known the underlying facts, but these facts were not &ldquo;discoverable&rdquo; in the sense that is intended by s. 5(1)(a)(iv)&mdash;that the nature of the injury they experienced was such that they would know a legal proceeding would be an appropriate remedy. For this reason, the Plaintiffs assert that the limitation period did not commence until <UNDER>after</UNDER> they obtained legal advice.</P>
<P>55. This case bears some similarity to medical malpractice cases in which plaintiffs are not presumed to know the legal concepts pertaining to the requisite standard of care. In those cases, courts have held there are times when the underlying facts of treatment and loss have occurred but are not discoverable by a layperson because of their technical complexity. Instead, the limitation period did not start until the plaintiffs received advice from another medical practitioner or legal counsel.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gaudet et al v. Levy et al</SOC><CITE>1984 47 O.R. (2d) 577</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's BOA, Tab 9;</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Findlay v. Holmes</SOC><CITE>[1998] O.J. No. 2796</CITE><PARANUM>31</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's BOA, Tab 10;</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>N.C. v. Blank</SOC><CITE>[1998] O.J. No. 2544</CITE><PARANUM>95</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's BOA, Tab 11;</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Anderson v. Laffin</SOC><CITE>[2004] O.J. No. 5390</CITE><PARANUM>36&ndash;40</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's BOA, Tab 12.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>See also,</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Lawless v. Anderson</SOC><CITE>2011 ONCA 102</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Lawless</EM>&rdquo;) at paras. 25&ndash;27, Respondent's BOA, Tab 13.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>56. Indeed, the case at bar presents a stronger argument that the limitation period did not commence until the Plaintiffs had obtained legal advice. In the medical malpractice cases, there was a recognized duty of care and claim for negligence; only a determination of whether the standard of care had been breached was required. In this case, a novel claim is being asserted: as yet, the right that is claimed has not been recognized in law.</P>
<P>57. In <CASEREF><SOC>Unegbu v WFG Securities of Canada Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>, the fact that the claimant's claims were recognized at law and there were no legal complexities (such as whether a professional standard of care was met) <UNDER>means</UNDER> &ldquo;there was no need for any advice of a technical nature to inform her that she had a cause of action.&rdquo; The Court held that the plaintiff could not rely on her ignorance of the law to postpone the commencement of the limitation period. This applies only to claims that are recognized at law, for a claimant can be neither ignorant nor imputed with knowledge of a cause of action that does not yet exist.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Unegbu v. WFG Securities of Canada Inc.</SOC><CITE>[2015] O.J. No. 5682</CITE><PARANUM>22</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's BOA, Tab 14.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>58. <CASEREF><SOC>Nicholas v. McCarthy Tetrault</SOC></CASEREF> and <EM>Lawless</EM> also concerned claims that are recognized at law. In both, the Court of Appeal specifically addressed occasions where claimants may need technical advice before material facts are discoverable. In <CASEREF><SOC>Nicholas v. McCarthy Tetrault</SOC></CASEREF>, the Court agreed with the motions judge but said,
<QUOTE><P>We would only add that at the very least, when the appellant signed the Settlement Agreement with her husband on January 22, 1997, <UNDER>with the benefit of legal advice from her new counsel</UNDER>, she knew or ought to have known of all the material facts giving rise to the impugned claim against the respondents.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Nicholas v. McCarthy Tetrault</SOC><CITE>2009 ONCA 692</CITE><PARANUM>1</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>(emphasis added), Respondent's BOA, Tab 20.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>59. In <EM>Lawless</EM>, the Court of Appeal gave the definition of &ldquo;cause of action&rdquo; as &ldquo;the fact or facts which give a person a right to judicial redress or relief against another.&rdquo; This definition accords with Stinson J.'s focus on s. 5(1)(a)(iv) of the <EM>Limitations Act, 2002</EM>, which ties discoverability to the plaintiff's knowledge that a legal proceeding would be an appropriate means of redress for an injury. The Attorney General does not explain how the cases it cites are authority for the proposition that the Respondents in the case at bar discovered the material facts upon their occurrence, when they could not have known they had a right to judicial redress before getting legal advice. Instead, it merely asserts that, &ldquo;the key point established by these cases is that the fact that a claimant does not know they have a <UNDER>recognized cause of action</UNDER> does not operate to toll the limitation period&rdquo;&mdash;an assertion with which the Respondents agree.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Lawless</EM> at para. 22, Respondent's BOA, Tab 13;</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Moving Party's Factum at para. 77.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The Novelty of the Claim Bears on Discoverability</EM></TI>
<P>60. The Respondents do not dispute that liability or culpability is determined through the trial process. The questions posed by the case at bar are whether a new <EM>basis</EM> for liability or culpability should be recognized at law, and whether such a novel claim could be discovered before the claimants obtained a legal opinion. <CASEREF><SOC>Lochner v. Toronto (City) Police Services Board</SOC></CASEREF>, as referenced in the Attorney General's factum, has no relevance to these issues.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Lochner v. Toronto (City) Police Services Board</SOC><CITE>2015 ONCA 626</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Lochner</EM>&rdquo;), Book of Authorities of the Appellant, Tab 12.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>61. At paragraph 77 of its factum, the Attorney General argues that, &ldquo;although these decisions do not specifically deal with the concept of the receipt of legal advice in relation to a cause of action which has not previously been recognized, the distinction is immaterial.&rdquo; Yet, the Attorney General makes no attempt to explain <UNDER>why</UNDER> the distinction is immaterial, or how a claimant can be imputed with knowledge of a cause of action when the claim it relates to has not been recognized at law.</P>
<P>62. The Respondents did believe a wrong had been done by the Crown Attorneys' egregious behaviour. But they did not know&mdash;and crucially, <EM>could not have known</EM>&mdash;that a legal proceeding was an appropriate means to seek to remedy that wrong because there was no recognized claim at law for the injury.</P>
<P>63. The Respondents' &ldquo;sophistication&rdquo; and &ldquo;knowledge of the law&rdquo; is precisely what informed their belief that they did not have a right that could be vindicated through a legal proceeding, as they were familiar with the concept of Crown immunity in its prosecutorial duties. In any event, the Respondents' familiarity with the law pertained to police investigations and criminal prosecutions. They have no relative sophistication in novel claims in tort. For this reason, they required legal advice before discovering the material facts of their claim.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The Motion Judge Did Not Err In Failing To Consider The Effect Of The Respondents' Failure To Pursue Their Claim With Diligence</EM></TI>
<P>64. The Attorney General has taken a double barrel approach at the motion to strike the Plaintiffs' claim. On the one hand, the Attorney General argues that the claim that the Respondents are bringing amounts to no reasonable cause of action, and indeed argues that there is no such claim in law. At the same time, the Attorney General argues that the Respondents did not act with due diligence in starting an action with respect to a claim that the Attorney General argues does not even exist in law.</P>
<P>65. The Attorney General's double barreled attempts to strike the claim cannot be reconciled. The novelty of the claim and the complexity of the legal and factual issues clearly have a bearing on the limitation period, i.e.: the Respondents could not have known there was a cause of action of a novel claim until after they had obtained legal advice.</P>
<P>66. If the material facts were not discoverable until after the Respondents obtained legal advice, then their diligence in pursuing their claim should be measured from the time they received that advice. Determining whether they were diligent at that point requires an evidentiary record.</P>
<P>67. It is submitted that this fact alone is enough for this Court to dismiss the Attorney General's appeal on the issue of whether the limitation period has expired. However, even if the material facts were discoverable earlier, it is not clear why waiting several months would necessarily imply the Respondents did not act diligently. As the Attorney General again points out at paragraph 82, the Respondents &ldquo;are part of the justice system and are sophisticated.&rdquo; This &ldquo;sophistication&rdquo; and familiarity with Crown immunity may have suppressed or delayed their intention to investigate further. What is clear is that a comprehensive factual record is needed to determine this issue.</P>
<P>68. Whether the Respondents acted diligently in pursuing their claim is a question of fact or of mixed fact and law that can only be determined on the basis of an extensive evidentiary record. In this proceeding, there is no evidentiary record&mdash;indeed, there is not even a statement of defence&mdash;substantiating the assertion that the Respondents did not act diligently and &ldquo;slept on their rights.&rdquo; That allegation would have to be set out in the Statement of Defence and cannot be determined before pleadings have closed, if relevant at all.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Unegbu</EM> at para. 15, Respondent's BOA, Tab 14;</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Smyth v. Waterfall</SOC><CITE>50 O.R. (3d) 481</CITE><COURTJUR>ONCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at para. 8, Respondent's BOA, Tab 16;</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Soper v. Southcott</SOC><CITE>39 O.R. (3d) 737</CITE><COURTJUR>ONCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>, citing</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Findlay v. Holmes</SOC></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Respondent's BOA, Tab 17.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">IV. ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>69. For the reasons above, the Respondents respectfully request that this Honourable Court dismiss the Attorney General's motion for an order that the action is statute barred by the <EM>Limitations Act</EM>, with costs.</P>
<P>Dated: May 23, 2018</P>
