<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. This is an appeal by the Attorney General for Ontario (Ontario) from the June 13, 2017 decision of the Honourable Mr. Justice Stinson which dismissed, in part, Ontario's motion to strike out the respondents' statement of claim and dismiss the respondents' action for the failure to disclose a reasonable cause of action. Stinson J. struck the respondents' allegations in negligence, but allowed the respondents' allegations in misfeasance in public office to proceed. Ontario submits that Stinson J. erred in permitting the allegations in misfeasance to proceed and the appeal should be granted.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>On March 7, 2018, this Court ordered that this appeal be heard at the same time as Ontario's appeal from the January 4, 2017 decision of Stinson J. which dismissed Ontario's motion to strike out the respondents' action as being statute -barred, and the respondents' appeal from the dismissal of their allegations in negligence arising from Stinson J.'s June 13, 2017 decision.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>2. The respondents are police officers with the Toronto Police Service (TPS) and were the investigating police officers with respect to a complaint of armed robbery and forcible confinement which took place in 2009. Two individuals were charged. The Deputy Crown Attorney and Assistant Crown Attorney (Crowns) assigned to the prosecutions stayed the charges against one of the accused (Mr. Maharaj) because he alleged that his confession was involuntary as a result of an assault by two of the respondents. The other accused (Mr. Singh) was convicted, but his sentence was reduced when the trial judge found that he had also been assaulted by one of the respondents while another stood by and did not intervene. The trial Crowns exercised their prosecutorial discretion not to challenge the allegations of assault and not to call the respondents to testify at Mr. Singh's trial.</P>
<P>3. Subsequent to the trial, the Professional Standards Unit of the Toronto Police Service (PSU) investigated the complaints of assault. Neither Mr. Singh or Mr. Maharaj, nor the respondents, agreed to be interviewed as part of the investigation. The PSU found that the allegations of assault could not be substantiated. At the appeal of Mr. Singh's conviction, Crown counsel with carriage of the appeal advised this Court of the existence of the review by the PSU, but the Court declined to consider it. This Court found that the trial judge had erred in failing to stay Mr. Singh's conviction due to the conduct of the respondents and his conviction was overturned.</P>
<P>4. The respondents later commenced an action alleging that Ontario is liable to them in negligence and misfeasance in public office because of the conduct of the three Crowns with carriage of the prosecutions and appeal. The respondents allege that the Crowns were negligent and misfeasant in failing to further investigate the claims of assault and for not calling evidence (including their testimony) to refute the allegations. They further allege that the appellate Crown should have brought a fresh evidence application to file the PSU report with this Court on Mr. Singh's appeal.</P>
<P>5. Ontario moved to strike the action on the basis that the action was statute-barred and because the action failed to disclose a reasonable cause of action in that Crown Attorneys are not liable in negligence or misfeasance in public office, and the Claim failed to properly plead the constituent elements of negligence or misfeasance,</P>
<P>6. Stinson J. bifurcated Ontario's motion and decided the limitations issue first. On January 4, 2017, Stinson J. dismissed Ontario's motion on the limitations issue. The balance of Ontario's motion to strike was heard on February 21 and 22, 2017. On June 13, 2017, Stinson J. allowed the motion in part, striking the allegations in negligence, but allowing the misfeasance allegations to proceed.</P>
<P>7. Ontario's appeal with respect to the misfeasance allegations should be granted because Stinson J. erred:
<P1>i) In finding that misfeasance in public office is a viable cause of action arising from the conduct of a Crown Attorney;</P1>
<P1>ii) In failing to conduct any analysis regarding the policy reasons militating against the expansion of Crown Attorney liability set out in <CASEREF><SOC>Nelles v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC></CASEREF> in the context of the misfeasance claim;</P1>
<P1>iii) In finding that the claim in misfeasance had been properly pleaded and, particularly, in failing to conduct any analysis of the alleged &ldquo;unlawful act&rdquo; or &ldquo;bad faith&rdquo; which are required to establish the tort.</P1>
<P1>iv) Relying on <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, when the Divisional Court granted leave to appeal that decision on the basis that there was good reason to doubt its correctness<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>The decision of the motion judge in <EM>Smith</EM> was overturned by the Divisional Court on February 21, 2018 (<CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 993</CITE></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities Tab 20).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>; and,</P1>
<P1>v) Declining to consider the documents incorporated by reference in the statement of claim in deciding the motion, even though the consideration of such evidence is permissible on Rule 21 and Rule 25 motions.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;FACTS<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>On a motion to strike, and any appeal therefrom, the Court must assume that the facts pleaded in the Claim are true. The facts pleaded may be disputed should the action proceed.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>CRIMINAL PROSECUTION GIVING RISE TO THE ACTION</TI>
<P>8. The respondents investigated an armed robbery which took place in February 2009. On June 11, 2009, the respondents arrested Neil Singh and Randy Maharaj. Mr. Singh was interviewed and provided an exculpatory statement to the respondents Mr. Watts and Mr. Clark. Mr. Maharaj confessed to the crime to the respondents Mr. Watts and Mr. Belanger.
<P1>Statement of Claim, paras. 7&ndash;9, Appeal Book and Compendium of the Attorney General (Appeal Book), Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>9. At his bail hearing on June 12, 2009, Mr. Maharaj's lawyer put on the record that his client had been injured during his arrest and had very visible bumps and scratches.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 10, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>10. The preliminary hearing for both accused was held between July 16, 2010 and November 9, 2010. The respondents were called as witnesses. Counsel for Mr. Maharaj questioned the respondents about his client's accusations of being assaulted (kicked in the head and beaten) during his arrest. They denied the assault. Mr. Singh and Mr. Maharaj were committed to stand trial.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 11, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>11. The trial commenced on November 28, 2011. Deputy Crown Attorney Sheila Cressman had carriage of the prosecution. In advance of the trial, counsel for Mr. Maharaj brought an application to stay the proceedings against him and to exclude his confession, relying on doctrines of abuse of process and voluntariness based on the allegation that he was assaulted by two of the respondents prior to his confession.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 13, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>12. Counsel for Mr. Maharaj advised Ms. Cressman that Mr. Maharaj received a serious rib injury due to an alleged assault by police after his arrest and before he gave his statement. Mr. Maharaj does not appear to have complained about this specific issue when he was admitted to Maplehurst Correctional Centre (Maplehurst) prior to trial. Counsel for Mr. Maharaj provided Ms. Cressman with a CD containing an X-ray purporting to support his allegations. Ms. Cressman spoke to Dr. Moss, a doctor at the hospital where Mr. Maharaj had been treated, who advised her that he had viewed the X-rays with a thoracic surgeon and that it was possible that the injuries could have occurred on the day of Mr. Maharaj's arrest. Dr. Moss also advised that such an injury could result in pain if a person were to move their arms or upper body. In his videotaped statements, Mr. Maharaj is seen moving his arms. Ms. Cressman did not seek Dr. Moss' opinion regarding whether the movements on the video were consistent with the injury having occurred on the day of the arrest.
<P1>Statement of Claim, paras. 13&ndash;17, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>13. Ms. Cressman consulted with senior Assistant Crown Attorney Frank Armstrong, who agreed with her that Mr. Maharaj's statement would not be admissible as it could not be proven to be voluntary due to all of the injuries he allegedly suffered. As a result, on November 22, 2011, Mr. Armstrong stayed the charges against Mr. Maharaj.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 18, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>14. On November 28, 2012, the trial of Mr. Singh proceeded before the Honourable Madam Justice Thorburn. Mr. Singh was convicted of armed robbery with a firearm and forcible confinement. Mr. Singh's counsel brought a <EM>Charter</EM> application to stay the conviction, relying on the evidence of his client and that of Mr. Maharaj. Mr. Maharaj testified he had been assaulted by the respondents Mr. Belanger and Mr. Clark. Mr. Singh testified that he had been assaulted by Mr. Clark while Mr. Watts stood by and did not intervene. In the Claim, the respondents allege that the testimony of Mr. Maharaj and Mr. Singh was false.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 19, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1>
<P1>Judgment, Thorburn J., <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Singh</SOC><PARANUM>1-2</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Exhibit D to the Affidavit of Matthew Howe, sworn September 19, 2016 (Howe Affidavit), Appeal Book, Tab 14D</P1></P>
<P>15. Ms. Cressman determined that she would not call any evidence in response to the allegations. She advised the Court that the evidence demonstrated that whatever happened to Mr. Singh was not as extreme as he suggested, but that the evidence did meet the low threshold required to establish a <EM>Charter</EM> breach. She suggested the proper remedy was not a stay of proceedings, but a reduction of sentence.
<P1>Statement of Claim, paras. 21 - 22, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1>
<P1>Transcript, <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Singh</SOC></CASEREF>, March 27, 2012, at p. 92, Exhibit C to the Howe Affidavit, Appeal Book, Tab 14C</P1></P>
<P>16. On March 28, 2012, Thorburn J. dismissed Mr. Singh's stay application. Thorburn J. noted that the evidence of the accused had not been contradicted and found that while a stay was not warranted, Mr. Singh's sentence should be reduced due to the assault he suffered at the hands of the respondents.
<P1>Judgment, Thorburn J., <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Singh</SOC><PARANUM>46&ndash;51</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Exhibit D to the Howe Affidavit, Tab 14D</P1>
<P1>Statement of Claim, paras. 23-24, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>17. Mr. Singh appealed his conviction and sentence. Before the appeal was heard, the Crown Law Office&mdash;Criminal notified the Chief of the TPS about concerns regarding the respondents' conduct. The Special Investigations Unit (SIU) was notified and invoked its mandate. However, Mr. Maharaj refused to be interviewed or participate in the investigation and the SIU withdrew its mandate. However, between July 4, 2012 and October 31, 2012, the PSU conducted a review of the allegations of misconduct and use of excessive force. In a written report, the PSU concluded the use of excessive force &ldquo;could not be substantiated&rdquo;. Neither Mr. Singh or Mr. Maharaj, nor the respondents, were interviewed as part of the PSU investigation.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 30, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1>
<P1>Toronto Police Service Court Review, dated October 31, 2012, Exhibit &ldquo;F&rdquo; to the Howe Affidavit, Appeal Book, Tab 14F</P1></P>
<P>18. The Claim alleges that prior to the argument of Mr. Singh's appeal, the respondent Mr. Watt spoke to appellate Crown counsel Amy Alyea and advised her that an &ldquo;egregious mistake had occurred&rdquo;. The Claim states he also advised her about, <EM>inter alia</EM>, what the respondents had learned about Ms. Cressman's alleged failure to investigate the allegations of assault and the contents of the PSU report.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 32, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>19. Neither the respondents nor the Toronto Police Association moved to intervene in the appeal of Mr. Singh's conviction.
<P1>Judgment, <CASEREF><SOC>R v. Singh</SOC></CASEREF>, Ontario Court of Appeal, dated December 13, 2013, Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo; to the Howe Affidavit, Appeal Book, Tab 14H</P1></P>
<P>20. On December 12, 2013, this Court released its decision staying Mr. Singh's conviction, finding that he was a victim of conduct &ldquo;which might well be characterized as torture&rdquo; at the hands of the respondent Mr. Clark. In the Claim, the respondents allege that this was a result of the failure of the Crowns to apprise the Court of the &ldquo;new material facts that established that Mr. Maharaj and Mr. Singh had most certainly fabricated the allegations of assault by the officers&rdquo;. Articles regarding the decision appeared in the media on December 12 and 13, 2013.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 35&ndash;37, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1>
<P1>Judgment, <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Singh</SOC></CASEREF>, December 12, 2013 at pg. 16, Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo; to the Howe Affidavit, Tab 14 H</P1>
<P1>Newspaper Articles, Exhibits &ldquo;A&rdquo; and &ldquo;L&rdquo; to the Howe Affidavit, Tabs 14A and 14L</P1></P>
<P>21. The Claim states that after the release of this Court's decision, the SIU re-opened their investigation and that this time Mr. Maharaj agreed to be interviewed. The Claim states that the SIU investigators reviewed all the records, including the videotape of Mr. Maharaj, and determined the rib injury post-dated the time of arrest and his physical demeanour during his videotaped statement was inconsistent with having sustained any rib injury. As such, the allegations were not substantiated. The report is not in evidence and it is unclear whether the report dealt with the allegations of abuse by Mr. Maharaj beyond the rib injury or with the allegations of Mr. Singh. It does not appear that the respondents were interviewed as part of the investigation.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para, 38, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1>
<P1>Howe Affidavit, para. 5, Appeal Book, Tab 14</P1></P>
<P>22. On May 26, 2014, the Chief of the TPS asked the Ontario Provincial Police (OPP) to conduct an independent review of the review conducted by the PSU. In her report dated April 9, 2015, the OPP investigator concluded she had no reason to refute the conclusion of the PSU that the allegations could not be substantiated. It is unclear whether any additional witnesses were interviewed or evidence gathered. Ontario does not have a copy of this report.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 39, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1>
<P1>Howe Affidavit, para. 5, Appeal Book, Tab 14</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>THE RESPONDENTS' ACTION</TI>
<P>23. On June 22, 2016, the respondents commenced a claim against the Attorney General, alleging that but for the negligent and misfeasant conduct of the Crowns, the Superior Court and this Court would not have made the findings they did and the respondents' reputations would not have been damaged.
<P1>Notice, <EM>Proceedings Against the Crown Act</EM>, s. 7(1), served October 20, 2015, Exhibit &ldquo;I&rdquo; to the Howe Affidavit, Tab 14I</P1>
<P1>Section 7(1)(2), <EM>Proceedings Against the Crown Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. P. 27</P1>
<P1>Statement of Claim, paras. 42 - 43, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>24. Specifically, the Claim alleges that the trial Crowns did not properly investigate the allegations of assault; did not call the respondents to testify regarding the allegations; and did not present other evidence to refute the allegations.
<P1>Statement of Claim, para. 28, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>25. With respect to the appellate Crown, the Claim alleges that she failed to bring a fresh evidence application with respect to the PSU report and failed to properly advise this Court of the alleged &ldquo;exculpatory findings&rdquo; made with respect to the respondents in that report. The transcript of the hearing before this Court reveals that in fact Ms. Alyea advised the Court of the existence of the PSU report and repeatedly offered to provide it for the Court's review but the panel hearing the appeal ultimately declined to consider it.
<P1>Statement of Claim, paras. 24&ndash;28 and 31&ndash;33, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1>
<P1>Transcript, <CASEREF><SOC>R v. Singh</SOC></CASEREF>, Ontario Court of Appeal, December 13, 2013, at pgs. 62 - 63, Exhibit &ldquo;G&rdquo; to the Howe Affidavit, Appeal Book, Tab 14G</P1></P>
<P>26. The respondents appear to ground their misfeasance allegations in an alleged breach of the statutory obligations of Crown Attorneys under the <EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM>. In paragraphs 45 and 46 of the Claim the respondents state
<QUOTE><P>45. Ms. Cressman, Mr. Armstrong, Ms. Alyea, and the other crown law officers who had direct or indirect knowledge of this case, conduct their duties as crown attorneys, pursuant to the statutory obligations set out in the <EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. C. 49;</P>
<P>46. Pursuant to the Act, the crown attorneys, swear an oath before entering upon their duties that they will truly and faithfully according to their skills and the best of their abilities execute the duties, the powers and trust of the provincial prosecutor for Ontario <BOLD><UNDER>without favour or affection to any party;</UNDER></BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1>Statement of Claim, at paras. 45 and 46, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>27. The oath referred to in these paragraphs is set out in section 8 of the <EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM>;
<QUOTE><SEC><N>8.</N><TI>Oath of office</TI>
<SECP>Every Crown Attorney and every assistant Crown Attorney, before entering upon his or her duties, shall take and subscribe before a judge of the Superior Court of Justice the following oath: I swear (or affirm) that I will truly and faithfully, according to the best of my skill and ability, execute the duties, powers and trusts of Crown Attorney (or assistant Crown Attorney) without favour or affection to any party: So help me God. (Delete if affirmed)</SECP></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. C. 49, s, 8</P1></P>
<P>28. The plaintiffs assert that the following allegations, which are excerpted from the Claim, were deliberate and constitute unlawful conduct because they purportedly contravene the &ldquo;sworn statutory duty&rdquo; of Crown Attorneys, thus giving rise to their claim in misfeasance:
<P1>i. They failed to properly ascertain the veracity of Mr. Maharaj and Mr. Singh's allegations of abuse;</P1>
<P1>ii. They failed to call the police officers as witnesses in order to refute the false and defamatory allegations;</P1>
<P1>iii. They ignored key facts or were wilfully blind to them;</P1>
<P1>iv. They knew or ought to have known that there was good medical evidence to say, at the very least, that the injury suffered by Mr. Maharaj was older than the arrest day contrary to what was alleged;</P1>
<P1>v. They knew that the treating physician of Mr. Maharaj would have raised serious questions about the truth of what Mr. Maharaj was stating, had he been aware of video taken at the time of the arrest, that showed Mr. Maharaj moving in a manner inconsistent with having a cracked rib at the time;</P1>
<P1>vi. They knew that the transcript at the bail hearing clearly demonstrated inconsistent and contradictory allegations about the alleged injuries Mr. Maharaj claimed he suffered;</P1>
<P1>vii. They knew that the documentation from Maplehurst clearly indicated that Mr. Maharaj lied when he said that he sought treatment at Maplehurst for 3 (three) weeks with respect to a rib injury;</P1>
<P1>viii. The new material facts Ms. Alyea and her superiors became aware of which clearly exonerated the police officers and implicated Ms. Cressman's conduct, were suppressed by senior Crown law officers, and were kept from the judges of the Court of Appeal.
<P2>Statement of Claim, para. 47, Appeal Book, Tab 10</P2></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>THE ATTORNEY GENERAL'S MOTION TO STRIKE</TI>
<P>29. The Attorney General brought a motion to strike out the respondents' Claim and dismiss their action pursuant to Rules 21 and 25 on the basis that it was statute-barred; the action failed to disclose a reasonable cause of action in that the conduct of the Crowns could not give rise to liability in negligence or misfeasance, and the Claim failed to properly plead the constituent elements of negligence or misfeasance.</P>
<BLOCK4><N>1.</N><TI>Motion on the Limitations Issue</TI>
<P>30. Stinson J. bifurcated Ontario's motion and determined he would decide the limitations issue first. On January 4, 2017, he dismissed that portion of Ontario's motion. Leave to appeal that decision was granted by the Divisional Court on January 26, 2018, and the appeal from this decision is being heard at the same time as this appeal.
<P1>Endorsement, Stinson J., January 4, 2017, at paras. 16 and 19&ndash;22; Appeal Book, Tab 9</P1>
<P1>Endorsements, Divisional Court, January 26, 2018 and February 6, 2018, Appeal Book, Tab 5</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>2.</N><TI>Motion to Strike for the Failure to Plead a Reasonable Cause of Action</TI>
<P>31. On this portion of the motion, Ontario argued that Crowns are immune from claims in negligence and misfeasance and could not be liable to anyone other than an individual they had prosecuted; that the claim in misfeasance was not properly pleaded and that the decision to stay the prosecution against Mr. Maharaj was an exercise of core prosecutorial discretion and consequently was not renewable absent flagrant impropriety.</P>
<P>32. Ontario's attack on the allegations of misfeasance was fourfold:
<P1>1) The Courts had repeatedly held that the only tort for which Crown Attorneys were liable was malicious prosecution, and this was so even where the tort of misfeasance in public office had been pleaded;</P1>
<P1>2) The same policy reasons which negated a duty of care in negligence also negated the imposition of liability in misfeasance in public office to investigating police officers as the imposition of this liability would engage all of the same concerns outlined by the Supreme Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC></CASEREF>;</P1>
<P1>3) In the criminal context, Courts are loath to review the decisions of prosecutors in the conduct of a prosecution (such as the decision to commence or discontinue a prosecution, or which witnesses should be called at trial), and will only do so where such conduct amounts to an abuse of process, is a <EM>Charter</EM> violation, or where the fairness of the trial is affected. Civil courts should be equally loath to review such conduct of prosecutors; and,</P1>
<P1>4) The respondents had failed to plead the requisite elements of the tort because, <EM>inter alia</EM>, they could not establish the &ldquo;unlawful act&rdquo; required to establish the tort of misfeasance in public office.
<P2>Factum of the Moving Party, Appeal Book, Tab 12</P2></P1></P>
<P>33. The respondents argued that the test for misfeasance was made out because: the conduct of the Crowns was deliberate in that Ms. Cressman knew of the available evidence and the consequences of failing to put it before the Court and Ms. Alyea knew of the alleged errors and the consequences of failing to correct the record; they both acted unlawfully in violation of their duties under the <EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM>; they did so for an improper purpose to protect their own agents; and they were willfully blind or reckless to the harm that would be caused to the respondents.
<P1>Factum of the Responding Party, Appeal Book, Tab 13</P1></P>
<P>34. On June 13, 2017, Stinson J. released his decision allowing Ontario's motion in part. Stinson J. struck the negligence allegations from the Claim, but allowed the misfeasance claim to proceed. With respect to the Claim in negligence, Stinson J. found that the respondents had no cause of action for the same policy reasons relied on by the Supreme Court of Canada in its quartet of cases on Crown Attorney liability which limit liability to malicious prosecution and the intentional failure to disclose exculpatory evidence to an accused person.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>In <CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court found that Crown Attorney liability should not be expanded beyond its current scope because the expansion of liability i) Would undermine the ability of prosecutors to discharge their important public duties, with adverse consequences for the administration of justice; ii) May influence the decision-making of prosecutors and make them more &ldquo;defensive&rdquo; in their approach. The public interest is not well served when Crown counsel are motivated by fear of civil liability, rather than their sworn duty to fairly and effectively prosecute crime; and iii) Would open up the floodgates of civil liability and force prosecutors to spend undue amounts of time and energy defending their conduct in court instead of performing their duties.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<P1>Reasons for Decision, Stinson J., June 13, 2017, Appeal Book, Tab 7</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Nelles v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[1989] 2 S.C.R. 170</CITE><PARANUM>55</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 1</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Proulx v. Quebec</SOC><CITE>[2001] 3 S.C.R. 9</CITE><PARANUM>35</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 2</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Miazga v. Kvello Estate</SOC><CITE>[2009] 3 S.C.R. 339</CITE><PARANUM>4&ndash;7, 44, 46&ndash;51 and 80</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 3</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>[2015] 2 S.C.R. 214</CITE><PARANUM>74</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 4</P1></P>
<P>35. However, Stinson J. did not conduct any analysis of the policy considerations outlined in the Supreme Court jurisprudence with respect to the allegations of misfeasance, despite acknowledging that Ontario was arguing that the same policy considerations applied to both the claim in negligence and the claim in misfeasance. Further, with respect to whether the &ldquo;unlawful act&rdquo; required to establish misfeasance existed in this case, Stinson J. found that this this was a matter of dispute between the parties, and on a motion to strike he was not called upon to determine whether allegations can be proven, but instead must assume that they could be. Stinson J. conducted no analysis of the particular statutory duty relied on by the respondents in their Claim and failed to recognize that this was a legal, not a factual issue. His Honour further found that the defence that the Crowns acted within the scope of their duties was a matter properly determined in a hearing on the merits and that the permissible review of a Crown Attorney's conduct in the criminal context was broader than the scope argued by Ontario. Finally, he found that there were enough facts pleaded to make out a claim in misfeasance.
<P1>Reasons for Decision, Stinson J., June 13, 2017, at paras. 138&ndash;152, Appeal Book, Tab 7</P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;LAW and ARGUMENT</TI>
<P>36. The issue to be determined on this appeal is whether Stinson J. erred in failing to strike out the respondents' allegations of misfeasance. The appeal should be granted because Stinson J. erred:
<P1>1. In finding that misfeasance is a viable cause of action arising from the conduct of a Crown Attorney;</P1>
<P1>2. In failing to conduct any analysis regarding the policy reasons militating against the expansion of Crown Attorney liability set out in <CASEREF><SOC>Nelles v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC></CASEREF> in the context of the misfeasance claim;</P1>
<P1>3. In finding that the claim in misfeasance had been properly pleaded and, particularly, in failing to conduct any analysis of the alleged &ldquo;unlawful act&rdquo; which is required to establish the tort;</P1>
<P1>4. Relying on <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> when the Divisional Court granted leave to appeal that decision on the basis that there was good reason to doubt its correctness; and</P1>
<P1>5. Declining to consider the documents incorporated by reference in the statement of claim in deciding the motion, even though the consideration of such evidence is permissible on a Rule 21 motion or a Rule 25 motion.</P1></P>
<BLOCK3><N>1.</N><TI>THE GOVERNING JURISPRUDENCE ESTABLISHES THAT MISFEASANCE IS NOT A VIABLE CAUSE OF ACTION ARISING FROM THE CONDUCT OF A CROWN ATTORNEY</TI>
<P>37. This Court and the Superior Court of Justice have repeatedly found that the only tort for which a Crown Attorney is liable is malicious prosecution; this is so even in cases where the tort of misfeasance in public office was pleaded.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Two decisions of the Superior Court of Justice, <CASEREF><SOC>Whitty v. Wells</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Ferron v. Goodier</SOC></CASEREF> suggest that a cause of action in misfeasance may exist regarding Crown Attorney conduct. However, it is submitted that the <CASEREF><SOC>Whitty v. Wells</SOC><CITE>[2014] O.J. No. 4625</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> which found that it is not &ldquo;plain and obvious&rdquo; that there is no cause of action in misfeasance in public office against a Crown Attorney, was wrongly decided. In <EM>Whitty</EM>, which was released approximately six weeks before this Court's decision in <EM>Brummell</EM>, the Court held that it was not plain and obvious that misfeasance in public office should be struck out on a Rule 21 motion based on prosecutorial immunity. The Court found that it was bound by this Court's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Folland v. Ontario</SOC><YEAR>2003</YEAR><CITE>64 O.R. (3d) 89</CITE></CASEREF> as &ldquo;the latest appellate guidance on whether claims other than malicious prosecution may be brought against a Crown prosecutor&rdquo;. That finding was incorrect as <EM>Folland</EM>, which held that the law had not been settled on whether there was a cause of action in misfeasance in public office against Crown Attorneys, was decided before this Court's decisions in <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. Gilkinson</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Miguna v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>. In any event, it is submitted that much of the reasoning in <EM>Folland</EM> was overturned by the Supreme Court in <EM>Miazga</EM>. Finally, <EM>Whitty</EM> and <EM>Folland</EM> have now been superseded by this Court's decisions in <EM>Brummell</EM> and <EM>Abernethy</EM>. In <CASEREF><SOC>Ferron v. Goodier</SOC><CITE>[2010] O.J. No. 329</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, the motion judge appears to have assumed that a tort in misfeasance in public office is available against a Crown Attorney, but did not conduct any analysis in that regard. In any event, the correctness of <EM>Ferron</EM> and the Manitoba case of <CASEREF><SOC>Driskell v. Dangerfield</SOC><CITE>2007 MBQB 142</CITE></CASEREF> on which the Court in <EM>Ferron</EM> relied, was questioned by the Superior Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Baltovich v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 6991</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>,which stated that the Courts' findings in those cases are based on a misreading of the Supreme Court of Canada's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Krieger v. Law Society of Alberta</SOC><CITE>[2002] 3 S.C.R. 372</CITE></CASEREF> and that the Court in <EM>Ferron</EM> failed to consider the Supreme Court's decision in <EM>Miazga</EM>. Finally, again the findings in <EM>Ferron</EM> have been superseded by <EM>Brummell</EM> and <EM>Abernethy</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Abernethy v. Canada</SOC><CITE>[2017] O.J. No. 2142</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 5, Reasons for Decision, Gunsolus J. delivered orally, August 29, 2016 (unreported), Book of Authorities, Tabs 5 and 6.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Brummell v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[2014] O.J. No. 5566</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 7</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ciavarella v. Schwartz</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 5061</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at paras, 2 &amp; 22, Book of Authorities, Tab 9</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Fragomeni v. Greater Sudbury Police Service</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 3985</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at paras. 80&ndash;82, Book of Authorities, Tab 10</P1>
<P1>See also <CASEREF><SOC>Baltovich v. Ontario (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 6991</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at paras. 35&ndash;37, Book of Authorities, Tab 11 and <CASEREF><SOC>Thompson v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[1998] O.J. No. 3917</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 56, Book of Authorities, Tab 12</P1></P>
<P>38. In <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. Gilkinson</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Miguna v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, released by this Court by the same panel on the same day in 2005, the Court found that it was not clear from the authorities whether a claimant had to establish all four of the constituent elements of the tort of malicious prosecution (particularly, the requirement that the prior proceedings must have been determined in favour of the plaintiff) before civil liability could be imposed on a Crown Attorney. However, it is submitted that the Supreme Court's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Miazga v. Kvello Estate</SOC></CASEREF>, released in 2009, confirmed that all four elements of the test for malicious prosecution must be met before civil liability can be imposed on a Crown Attorney. <EM>Miazga</EM> also confirmed that the purpose of the narrow exception to immunity from civil liability in the form of liability for malicious prosecution was to provide &ldquo;a remedy to individuals who have been wrongly and maliciously prosecuted&rdquo;.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. Gilkinson</SOC><CITE>[2005] O.J. No. 5347</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 13</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Miguna v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[2005] O.J. No. 5346</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 14</P1>
<P1><EM>Miazga</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 53&ndash;57 and 78&ndash;81</P1></P>
<P>39. In any event, in both <EM>Gilbert</EM> and <EM>Miguna</EM>, this Court confirmed that whatever nominate tort was pleaded, liability could not be imposed on a Crown Attorney unless a claimant established &ldquo;malice&rdquo; as defined by the Supreme Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Nelles v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Prouix v. Quebec</SOC></CASEREF>: &ldquo;a deliberate and improper use of the office of the Attorney-General or Crown Attorney, a use inconsistent with the status of &lsquo;minister of justice&rsquo;&rdquo; and one in which the defendant &ldquo;perpetrated a fraud on the process of criminal justice and in doing so has perverted or abused his office and the process of criminal justice&rdquo;. Neither case considered the availability of a remedy for anyone other than an individual who had been prosecuted.</P>
<P>40. Since the release of <EM>Gilbert</EM> and <EM>Miguna</EM>, there have been significant developments in the law regarding Crown Attorney liability and it is submitted that this Court's findings in <EM>Abemethy</EM>, which was released after the Supreme Court's decisions in both <EM>Miazga</EM> and <EM>Henry</EM> (and after the decision of Stinson J. on the motion below) and <CASEREF><SOC>Brummell v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, which was released after <EM>Miazga</EM>, supersede <EM>Gilbert</EM> and <EM>Miguna</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>The decisions of this Court in <EM>Gilbert, Miguna</EM> were authored by the Honourable Mr. Justice Blair J.A. who was also on the panel that decided <EM>Abernethy</EM>, a decision authored by the Court.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>41. In <CASEREF><SOC>Abernethy v. Canada</SOC></CASEREF>, the plaintiff sued the Crown Attorney defendants for &ldquo;conspiracy, misfeasance in public office, breach of trust, intentional infliction of mental distress, obstruction of justice, intentional <EM>Charter</EM> and statutory violations and, in some cases, false arrest, false imprisonment and fabricating evidence&rdquo;.
<P1><EM>Abernethy (C.A.)</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 5</P1></P>
<P>42. Ontario brought a motion to strike the claim as failing to disclose a reasonable cause of action. The motion judge granted the motion and held with the exception of a claim for malicious prosecution, which the plaintiff acknowledged she was not pursuing, the Crown Attorney defendants were protected by Crown immunity under section 8 of the <EM>Ministry of the Attorney General Act</EM>, and by common law Crown immunity. On appeal from that decision, this Court held that the motion judge's finding in this regard was correct:
<QUOTE><P>The Crown Attorneys are protected from suit against them by the statutory and common law immunity outlined above. Ms. Abernethy candidly conceded that she is not asserting a claim for malicious prosecution. It follows that no action can be brought against these defendants in their personal capacities in these circumstances. See <CASEREF><SOC>Nelles v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, <CASEREF><SOC>Miazga v. Kvello Estate</SOC></CASEREF>, <CASEREF><SOC>Thompson v. Ontario</SOC><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. Gilkinson</SOC><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, leave to appeal refused [citations omitted] ...</P>
<P>In addition, on the basis that Ms. Abernethy's pleading discloses no factually material basis for a cause of action against the personal Crown Defendants, the claims against the Crown, itself, based as they are on vicarious liability, must fail too.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Abernethy (C.A.)</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 5, 7 and 12</P1>
<P1><EM>Ministry of the Attorney General Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. M.17, s. 8</P1></P>
<P>43. It is submitted therefore, that the only ways in which the civil liability of the Attorney General can be engaged arising from the conduct of a Crown Attorney is an action for malicious prosecution; and since the Supreme Court's decision in <EM>Henry</EM>, an action for <EM>Charter</EM> damages arising out of a Crown Attorney's intentional failure to disclose exculpatory evidence to an accused, knowing the failure to disclose would cause harm. As such, the respondents' claim in misfeasance cannot stand because there is no such cause of action against a Crown Attorney.</P>
<P>44. On the motion below, Ontario relied on <EM>Brummell</EM> as being binding appellate authority on the question of whether there was a cause of action in misfeasance arising from a Crown Attorney's conduct. In <EM>Brummell</EM>, Ontario brought a motion to strike out the plaintiff's action on a number of grounds; one of which was that the claim alleged torts for which Crown Attorneys were not liable, including misfeasance in public office, conspiracy and intentional infliction of emotional harm. The motion judge agreed with Ontario, striking the action for various reasons including that &ldquo;the Crown Attorney was immune from suit, excepting for malicious prosecution&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Brummell</EM> was decided before the Supreme Court of Canada decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>[2015] 2 S.C.R. 214</CITE></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 8, which created the new <EM>Charter</EM> claim for damages for the intentional failure to disclose exculpatory evidence.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This Court upheld that decision, finding that the claim was &ldquo;fatally flawed&rdquo; for the reasons set out by the motions judge. As a result, Ontario argued that <EM>Brummell</EM> was binding appellate authority for the proposition that Crown Attorneys could only be liable for malicious prosecution and not for misfeasance in public office.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Brummell v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[2014] O.J. No. 4809</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 47, aff'd [2014] O.J. No, 5566 (C.A.), Book of Authorities, Tabs 7 and 8</P1>
<P1>Second Amended Statement of Claim, <CASEREF><SOC>Brummell v. Ontario</SOC><PARANUM>2 and 160&ndash;165</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Exhibit A to the Supplementary Affidavit of Matthew Howe, sworn October 24, 2016 (Supplementary Howe Affidavit), Appeal Book, Tab 14A</P1></P>
<P>45. However, the respondents argued that <EM>Brummell</EM> was not binding appellate authority for the proposition that there is no cause of action in misfeasance arising from a Crown's conduct because &ldquo;the appeal decision turned on a procedural matter unrelated to Crown Attorney liability&rdquo;. Stinson J. agreed. Ontario submits that this is a misreading of <EM>Brummell</EM> because this Court clearly found the claim to be fatally flawed for the reasons of the motions judge and the appeal did not turn on a procedural matter unrelated to Crown Attorney liability. As a result, Stinson J.'s finding that the <EM>Brummell</EM> was not binding authority for the proposition that Crown Attorneys are not liable in misfeasance is an error. In any event, it is submitted that the subsequent release of <CASEREF><SOC>Abernethy v. Canada</SOC></CASEREF> answers this question in favour of Ontario's position.
<P1><EM>Brummell</EM> (C.A.), <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 7&ndash;12, Book of Authorities, Tab 7</P1></P>
<P>46. Further, it is submitted that even if Stinson J. was correct in determining that the existing jurisprudence regarding Crown Attorney liability was not determinative in the case before him, he was required to determine whether <EM>these particular plaintiffs</EM> have a cause of action in misfeasance. In other words, he was required to determine whether Crown Attorney liability should be extended to a new class of claimants: investigating police officers. However, Stinson J. erred in framing the question before him with respect to the claim in misfeasance:
<QUOTE><P>Finally, I must consider the officers' claim against the AG for misfeasance in public office. In particular, the AG asks me to find that that the plaintiffs have not made out the elements of the tort of misfeasance in public office in their pleading. My approach to assessing this claim differs from the officers' negligence claim, in that misfeasance in public office is a recognized cause of action, whereas in the former instance the plaintiffs were asking me to extend the liability of Crown Attorneys into a new sphere. This analysis is thus different, in that my task is to review the statement of claim and determine whether it contains sufficient allegations that, if proven, would establish the cause of action. As well, the statement of claim is to be read generously with allowance for inadequacies due to drafting deficiencies: see <CASEREF><SOC>Toronto-Dominion Bank v. Deloitte Haskins &amp; Sells</SOC><YEAR>1991</YEAR><CITE>5 O.R. (3d) 417</CITE><COURTJUR>Gen. Div.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Reasons for Decision, Stinson J., June 13, 2017, at para. 138, Appeal Book, Tab 7</P1></P>
<P>47. Later in his judgment, Stinson J. recognizes that Ontario is arguing that the same policy reasons that negate the imposition of a duty of care in negligence also negate a cause of action in misfeasance in public office:
<QUOTE><P>The AG submits that the same policy concerns against expanding Crown Attorney civil liability to include negligence claims by investigating police officers should apply to bar the expansion of the tort of misfeasance of public office. The AG submits that, in the criminal context, courts do not review prosecutors' tactical decisions, such as whether to present certain evidence or call certain evidence unless there is an abuse of process or the accused's fair trial rights are violated. The AG cites the following decisions in support of this proposition: <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Hillis</SOC><PARANUM>41</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>R v. L.L.</SOC><PARANUM>13</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <EM>Miazga</EM>, at para. 51. [citations omitted]</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Reasons for Decision, Stinson J., June 13, 2017, at para. 143, Appeal Book, Tab 7</P1></P>
<P>48. However, ultimately, Stinson J. failed to apply the policy considerations in <EM>Henry</EM> to the misfeasance claim and limited his analysis to the permissible scope of review of a prosecutor's tactical decisions in the criminal context. Pursuant to the <EM>dicta</EM> of the Supreme Court in <EM>Henry</EM>, which states that the policy considerations noted by the Court in that case are relevant whenever the potential civil liability of Crown Attorneys is engaged, the failure to conduct a full policy analysis was an error. Moreover, Stinson J.'s entire approach to the misfeasance allegations is predicated on the error that misfeasance is a recognized cause of action against a Crown Attorney, and that the main thrust of Ontario's submission was that the tort was not properly pleaded. As set out below, when the <EM>Henry</EM> policy analysis is conducted in the context of the misfeasance claim, it is clear that there is no difference between a claim in negligence and a claim in misfeasance from a policy perspective. The respondents should have no cause of action in negligence or misfeasance in public office against the Attorney General.
<P1><EM>Henry</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 76.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>2.</N><TI>POLICY CONSIDERATIONS NEGATE A CAUSE OF ACTION OF MISFEASANCE IN PUBLIC OFFICE FOR THE RESPONDENTS</TI>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>i)</EM></N><TI><EM>The prospect of liability for misfeasance would divert Crowns from their duties and have a chilling effect on their conduct</EM></TI>
<P>49. In <EM>Henry</EM>, the Supreme Court considered whether the liability arising out of a Crown Attorney's conduct should be expanded to include a claim for <EM>Charter</EM> damages for the failure to disclose exculpatory evidence to an accused person and, if it was to be so expanded, what the threshold of liability should be. The Court found that the tort of malicious prosecution involved the discretionary decision of a prosecutor to commence, continue or conclude a prosecution and because disclosure to an accused person was not discretionary, but instead was a constitutional obligation, it did not fit well within the rubric of malicious prosecution. Further, the high standard of malice required in respect of a Crown Attorney's tort liability was not appropriate for a <EM>Charter</EM> claim for damages for the intentional failure to disclose exculpatory evidence to an accused person. However, in so finding the Court recognized that important policy considerations were engaged when determining the &ldquo;spectre of liability&rdquo; of Crown Attorneys:
<QUOTE><P>There are two policy considerations from the malicious prosecution trilogy that I wish to emphasize. First, the liability threshold must ensure that Crown counsel will not be diverted from their important public duties by having to defend against a litany of civil claims. Second, the liability threshold must avoid a widespread &ldquo;chilling effect&rdquo; on the behaviour of prosecutors. [...]</P>
<P>The policy concerns raised in the malicious prosecution trilogy are not confined to the exercise of core prosecutorial discretion. In my view, those concerns have a broader reach and are implicated wherever there is a risk of undue interference with the ability of prosecutors to freely carry out their duties in furtherance of the administration of justice.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Henry</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 70-71, 76</P1></P>
<P>50. With respect to the first concern&mdash;diversion from duties&mdash;the Supreme Court found that expanding liability by departing from a high liability threshold would result in Crown Attorneys being &ldquo;constantly enmeshed in an avalanche of interlocutory civil proceedings and civil trials&rdquo;, an outcome that &ldquo;bode[s] ill for the efficiency of [Crown prosecutors] and the quality of our criminal justice system&rdquo;.
<P1><EM>Henry</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 72</P1></P>
<P>51. The Supreme Court further found that the second concern&mdash;the chilling effect on Crown counsel&mdash;also supported a high liability threshold because fear of civil liability may lead to defensive lawyering by prosecutors. It could result in decisions &ldquo;motivated less by leg al principle than by a calculated effort to ward off the spectre of liability&rdquo;. The Court found that &ldquo;the public interest is undermined when prosecutorial decision-making is influenced by considerations extraneous to the Crown's role as a quasi-judicial officer&rdquo;.
<P1><EM>Henry</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 73</P1></P>
<P>52. It is important to note that the <EM>Henry</EM> decision deals only with the appropriate threshold for liability with respect to a <EM>Charter</EM> claim against the state for damages for non-malicious conduct of a Crown Attorney. The Court made clear that its decision did not in any way seek to undercut the Court's malicious prosecution jurisprudence, the basis of which is that Crown Attorneys enjoy a qualified immunity from tort liability and are exposed only to a claim in malicious prosecution, that malice in the form of an improper purpose is the key to proving malicious prosecution, and that the high standard of establishing malice is justified by the need to give prosecutors a sphere of independence from judicial scrutiny. The Court noted, in support of the need for independence in prosecutorial decision-making, that the same policy considerations outlined above would be engaged whenever the expansion of Crown Attorney liability is being considered.
<P1><EM>Henry</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras 45&ndash;49 and 66, 76</P1></P>
<P>53. Certainly, Stinson J. found the policy considerations set out in the Supreme Court jurisprudence to be relevant and determinative on the issue of whether the respondents' have a cause of action in negligence against Ontario:
<QUOTE><P>It is clear that the policy concerns from the malicious prosecution trilogy, echoed in <EM>Henry</EM>, are &ldquo;implicated&rdquo; when there is a risk of interference with prosecutors' ability to carry out their duties. That is precisely the situation in the present case. The type of liability the officers are asking the court to impose would create a whole new class of potential claimants. It would require Crown Attorneys to consider, in each case, whether the reputational interests of the police dictate a certain approach to a particular case. It would divert Crown Attorneys from their basic responsibilities of assessing whether there are reasonable and probable grounds to prosecute a case, deciding whether it is the public interest to do so, and protecting and respecting the rights of the accused. Adding a separate private law duty to concerned police officers would add a consideration that is extraneous to those primary responsibilities.</P>
<P>An expansion of the responsibilities of Crown Attorneys to include such a duty could result in cases proceeding to trial merely to resolve the concerns of the police. It would alter what should be a co-operative relationship between the police and Crown Attorneys into a potentially adversarial one, in which police would become not just investigators and witnesses, but also litigants with a stake in the outcome, as well as potential claimants against the Crown Attorneys. The potential for conflict and disruption to the relationship is apparent. Moreover, in this era of strained judicial and court resources, the expansion of Crown Attorneys' duties in the fashion proposed by the officers carries with it the risk of increased time spent litigating criminal cases for non-core reasons, a most undesirable consequence.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Reasons for Decision, Stinson J., June 13, 2017, at paras. 134-135; Appeal Book, Tab 7</P1></P>
<P>54. There is no reason why the findings above would not apply with equal force to a cause of action in misfeasance. The relevant factor in determining whether the policy considerations are engaged is not the name of the cause of action, but the very fact that a Crown Attorney could have any sort of liability to anyone other than a person they had prosecuted. Although Stinson J. acknowledged that it was Ontario's position that the policy considerations negated both a cause of action in negligence and in misfeasance, he conducted no analysis of the policy considerations in relation to the misfeasance allegations and made no finding with respect to whether or not these policy reasons applied. This was an error.</P>
<P>55. Moreover, the policy considerations are particularly important in this case because the respondents are not only seeking to extend the liability of Crown Attorneys to a new tort, but also, for the first time, to a new class of claimants: investigating police officers. The failure of Stinson J. to do any policy analysis with respect to the misfeasance claim is significant because it is difficult to ascertain how the recognition of a cause of action by a new class of claimants, whether it is in negligence or misfeasance, will not engage both of the policy considerations set out by the Supreme Court in <EM>Henry</EM>. First, expanding potential liability to investigating police officers raises the spectre of liability wherever a police officer may disagree with a Crown Attorney's handling of a prosecution, substantially increasing the potential number of civil actions Crowns will be forced to defend. Second, the spectre of potential liability to investigating police officers (or other participants in the justice system such as complainants or witnesses) could influence the exercise of a Crown Attorney's discretion, and cause them to consider their potential liability when deciding whether and how to proceed with a prosecution, making them more defensive in their approach to important prosecutorial decisions.</P>
<P>56. As mandated by the Crown Policy Manual and recognized in <EM>Miazga</EM>, when a Crown Attorney is deciding whether to proceed with a prosecution his or her only focus should be on whether there are reasonable grounds to continue the prosecution and whether it is in the public interest to do so. Stinson J. recognized the inherent conflict in duties that would result from the imposition of a duty of care in negligence to the respondents and that the interests of the respondents should not factor into the decision whether to continue a prosecution, or how to conduct that prosecution. The same issue and the same conflict arises where the claim is for misfeasance.
<P1>Crown Policy Manual, Excerpts, Book of Authorities, Tab 30</P1>
<P1><EM>Miazga</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 62 and 64</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>ii)</N><TI>The limited scope of judicial review of Crown conduct further militates against the expansion of Crown liability to a new tort and to individuals other than the accused</TI>
<P>57. On the motion below, Ontario argued that the limited review available to the Court with respect to a Crown Attorney's conduct and discretionary and tactical decisions in the criminal sphere was another factor militating against the imposition of civil liability for those decisions. Ontario argued:
<QUOTE><P>In the criminal context, the discretionary decisions of a prosecutor, such as the decision to commence, continue or stay a prosecution, are not reviewable by the Court short of an &ldquo;abuse of process&rdquo; or &ldquo;flagrant impropriety&rdquo;. Such abuses of process will only be found in the clearest of cases. The tactical decisions of a prosecutor, such as the decision to present certain evidence or call certain witnesses, will only be reviewable if there is an abuse of process or the accused's fair trial rights are affected. These standards of review demonstrate that the Courts are loathe to interfere in the conduct of the case by a prosecutor. Further, these standards militate against the imposition of civil liability regarding the discretionary and tactical decisions of Crown Attorneys for which the Court shows &ldquo;considerable deference&rdquo;. At the very least, these standards militate against the imposition of liability for anything less than malicious or deliberate conduct towards an accused person. As stated by the Supreme Court in <EM>Miazga</EM>, the review of prosecutorial conduct for abuse of process and malicious prosecution are two sides of the same coin. There is no case law to support a finding that a Crown Attorney's conduct with respect to anyone other than an accused or former accused person is reviewable in the civil or criminal context.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Factum of the Moving Party, Motion to Strike at para. 80, Appeal Book, Tab 12</P1></P>
<P>58. However, Stinson J. appears to have misapprehended Ontario's arguments, and the prevailing law, in finding that the Supreme Court of Canada's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>R v. Anderson</SOC></CASEREF> held the tactics and conduct of the Crown Attorneys before the court are subject to a wider range of review than suggested by Ontario. However, Ontario's arguments accorded with the prevailing law. As set out above, Ontario recognized that the threshold for the review of the tactics and conduct of a Crown Attorney was lower than that for a matter of prosecutorial discretion and does not require an abuse of process before the Court will intervene.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Anderson</SOC><CITE>[2014] 2 S.C.R. 167</CITE><PARANUM>57&ndash;61</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 15</P1></P>
<P>59. Ontario relied on the cases of <CASEREF><SOC>R v. Hillis</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. L.L.</SOC></CASEREF> for the specific proposition that a decision whether or not to call a certain witness, which is directly relevant to this case, was subject to only limited review by the Courts. As stated in <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Hillis</SOC></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>Relying on <EM>Felderhoff, Kreiger</EM>, and <EM>Anderson</EM>, I find that the decision of the prosecution to call or not call certain witnesses at trial is a matter of Crown tactics, reviewable under the court's trial management authority. These decisions are, like all prosecutorial decisions, subject to review where the product of oblique motive. But they are also subject to judicial review on a lesser standard relating to the fairness of trial.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>As stated in <CASEREF><SOC>R v. L.L.</SOC></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>The Crown's decision to call the mother, is a matter of litigation strategy. Such a decision does not relate to the nature and extent of the prosecution and the Attorney General's participation in it. It therefore falls into the &ldquo;tactics and conduct&rdquo; category. Although this category of conduct is reviewable on a standard less than abuse of process, litigation strategy is also entitled to considerable deference. As the Supreme Court stated in <CASEREF><SOC>R v. T(SG)</SOC><CITE>[2010] 1 S.C.R. 688</CITE><PARANUM>36</PARANUM></CASEREF>, trial judges, barring exceptional circumstances, must defer to the tactical decisions of counsel. Trial judges should not second guess the decisions of counsel who appear before them. Indeed, counsel are entitled to have a trial strategy and to modify it as the trial unfolds, provided there is no unfairness to the accused (<EM>Anderson</EM>, at para. 60).</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R v. Hillis</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 451</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at para. 41, Book of Authorities, Tab 16</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. L.L</SOC><CITE>2015 ABCA 222</CITE><PARANUM>13</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 17</P1></P>
<P>60. In any event, Courts will only review the conduct of Crown Attorneys or their discretionary or tactical decisions in very limited circumstances in the criminal context, and the same caution should be employed in the civil context. Further, as stated in <EM>Miazga</EM>, in the civil context that review should be very circumscribed:
<QUOTE><P>... the public law doctrine of abuse of process and the tort of malicious prosecution may be seen as two sides of the same coin: both provide remedies when a Crown prosecutor's actions are so egregious that they take the prosecutor outside his or her proper role as minister of justice, such that the general rule of judicial non-intervention with Crown discretion is no longer justified. Both abuse of process and malicious prosecution have been narrowly crafted, employing stringent tests, to ensure that liability will attach in only the most exceptional circumstances, so that Crown discretion remains intact.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Miazga</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 51</P1></P>
<P>61. Ontario submits that Stinson J. erred in failing to consider this limited scope of review in imposing potential liability on the Crowns for misfeasance in relation to an investigating police officer. The respondents complain that the Crowns acted improperly in determining that the prosecution against Mr. Maharaj should not proceed. However, the decision to proceed with or discontinue a prosecution is clearly an exercise of prosecutorial discretion and therefore will only be reviewed by the criminal courts if there is an abuse of process amounting to flagrant impropriety. Of course, there is no suggestion in the criminal context that anyone other than an accused person would have any sort of remedy regarding a Crown Attorney's exercise of discretion. Stinson J. agreed with this proposition finding that he did not think the respondents had a claim with respect to the decision not to proceed with the prosecution of Mr. Maharaj.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Anderson</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 48&ndash;51</P1>
<P1>Reasons for Decision, Stinson J., June 13, 2017, at para. 105, Appeal Book, Tab 7</P1></P>
<P>62. The respondents also complain that Ms. Cressman acted improperly in failing to call them as witnesses in the prosecution against Mr. Singh. The decision regarding which witnesses to call in a prosecution is a matter of tactics and conduct before the Court and will only be reviewable if the conduct is an abuse of process, trial fairness is affected or there is a potential <EM>Charter</EM> violation <EM>vis a vis</EM> an accused person. Again, there is no suggestion in the criminal context that anyone other than an accused person would have any sort of remedy regarding a Crown Attorney's tactics or conduct before the Court.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Anderson</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 36, 57&ndash;61</P1></P>
<P>63. Ontario submits that Stinson J. erred in failing to consider the specific conduct complained of and the limited review of that conduct permitted by the criminal court, which militates against the imposition of civil liability for the same conduct, particularly where the claimant is someone other than an accused person.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>iii)</N><TI>Motion Judge Erred in Relying on <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF></TI>
<P>64. It is not entirely clear to what extent Stinson J. relied on the decision of Matheson J, in <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> with respect to his findings regarding the allegations in misfeasance. However, to the extent that he found that the existing jurisprudence regarding Crown Attorney liability did not apply in this case because the respondents are police officers and not individuals who were prosecuted, it is submitted that he was in error. On appeal from Matheson J's decision, the Divisional Court found that the policy considerations which negated a cause of action in negligence against a Crown Attorney <EM>vis a vis</EM> a person they had prosecuted applied with equal force to the police officer defendants alleging a duty of care against the co-defendant Crown Attorneys, and that these policy considerations were engaged whenever Crown Attorney liability was being considered. Further, while the Divisional Court was clear that the only issue before it in <EM>Smith</EM> was whether the plaintiffs had a claim in negligence against the Attorney General, the Court noted that the binding appellate authority in Ontario required a Crown Attorney to act with malice before liability could be imposed. The Court did not refer to the <EM>Abernethy</EM> or <EM>Brummell</EM> decisions, which is not surprising, given that the issue of whether there is a viable cause of action in misfeasance arising from the conduct of a Crown Attorney was not at issue in <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>; the sole issue was whether there was a cause of action in negligence.
<P1>Reasons for Decision Stinson J. June 13 2017 at paras. 36 39-40 64 71&ndash;74 and 90 Appeal book Tab 7</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Smith v Ontario</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 7222</CITE><PARANUM>173</PARANUM><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>leave to appeal granted</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>[2017] O.J. No. 2370</CITE><COURTJUR>Div. Crt.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF> at paras. 13&ndash;15, appeal granted 2018 ONSC 993, (Div. Crt), at paras. 28, 31&ndash;34, Book of Authorities, Tabs 18, 19, 20</P1>
<P1><EM>Nelles</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 89</P1></P>
<BLOCK5><TI>THE RESPONDENTS FAILED TO PROPERLY PLEAD MATERIAL FACTS WHICH WOULD ESTABLISH A CAUSE OF ACTION IN MISFEASANCE</TI>
<P>65. In <CASEREF><SOC>Odhavji v. Woodhouse</SOC></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court determined that misfeasance in public office will be established where:
<P1>i) A public officer engaged in deliberate conduct in his or her capacity as a public officer;</P1>
<P1>ii) The conduct was unlawful;</P1>
<P1>iii) The public officer was aware that his conduct was unlawful;</P1>
<P1>iv) The public officer was also aware that the conduct was likely to harm the plaintiff; and</P1>
<P1>v) The unlawful conduct caused the damages.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Odhavji Estate v. Woodhouse</SOC><CITE>[2003] 3 S.C.R. 263</CITE><PARANUM>32</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 21</P1></P>
<P>66. There are two ways in which misfeasance can be committed. Category A involves conduct by a public officer that is specifically intended to injure a person or class of persons. Category B involves a public officer who acts with knowledge both that she has no power to do the act complained of and that the act is likely to injure the plaintiff. There are two common elements to both categories of the tort: 1) the public officer must have engaged in deliberate and unlawful conduct in his or her capacity as a public officer; and 2) the public officer must have been aware both that his or her conduct was unlawful and that it was likely to harm the plaintiff.</P>
<P>67. The difference in the categories of the tort is the manner in which they are proven. Category A is proven by simply establishing that the public officer has acted for the express purpose of harming the plaintiff. To prove Category B, the plaintiff must establish the two ingredients of the tort independently of one another. For both categories, the &ldquo;essential question to be determined is not whether the officer has unlawfully exercised a power actually possessed, but whether the alleged misconduct is deliberate and unlawful&rdquo;.
<P1><EM>Odhavji</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 32</P1></P>
<P>68. In <EM>Odhavji</EM>, the Supreme Court emphasized that the heart of the tort of misfeasance is unlawful conduct: either the unlawful exercise of a particular statutory or prerogative power; or &ldquo;more broadly based&rdquo; unlawful conduct in the exercise of public functions generally. The defendant must also be aware the conduct is unlawful. The Court noted:
<QUOTE><P>The requirement that the defendant must have been aware that his or her conduct was unlawful reflects the well-established principle that misfeasance in a public office requires an element of &ldquo;bad faith&rdquo; or &ldquo;dishonesty&rdquo;. In a democracy, public officers must retain the authority to make decisions that, where appropriate, are adverse to the interests of certain citizens. Knowledge of harm is thus an insufficient basis on which to conclude that the defendant has acted in bad faith or dishonestly. A public officer may in good faith make a decision that she or he knows to be adverse to interests of certain members of the public. In order for the conduct to fall within the scope of the tort, the officer must deliberately engage in conduct that he or she knows to be inconsistent with the obligations of the office.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>It is submitted that in this case, the respondents have failed to plead the required materials facts to establish bad faith, dishonesty, unlawful conduct or an intention to harm and therefore cannot establish Category A or B of the tort.
<P1><EM>Odhavji</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 32</P1></P>
<P>69. With respect to the statutory duty alleged by the respondents Stinson J. found:
<QUOTE><P>The dispute between the parties largely relates to the proper construction of the statutory duties of the Crown Attorneys and whether they were in fact breached in this case. At this stage, on a motion to strike, I am not called upon to decide if the plaintiffs can prove their allegations; instead I am required to assume that they can. The AG's defence that the Crown Attorneys acted within the scope of their duties and did not breach any legal obligations is a matter properly determined at a hearing on the merits.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Reasons for Decision, Stinson J. June 13, 2017, at para. 150, Appeal Book, Tab 7</P1></P>
<P>70. However, Ontario did not argue that the Claim should be struck because the allegations could not be proven, (which will be its position should this lawsuit proceed), but instead that it should be struck because there were no material facts pleaded to support the respondents' alleged &ldquo;unlawful act&rdquo; and that the alleged &ldquo;unlawful act&rdquo; (even if it was accepted that the Crowns had breached their oath of office during the prosecutions at issue) could never be an &ldquo;unlawful act&rdquo; <EM>vis a vis</EM> the respondents:
<QUOTE><P>First, the statement of claim fails to set out any material facts to support the allegation that the Crown Attorneys acted partially. Nor does the Claim plead any material facts to support an allegation that Crown counsel knew they were acting unlawfully. Further, with respect to the plaintiffs, there can be no unlawful act. A Crown Attorney swears to conduct a prosecution without partiality to any party. The parties to a prosecution are the Crown and the accused. An investigating police officer is not a party to a prosecution.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Factum of the Moving Party, Motion to Strike at para. 85, Appeal Book, Tab 12</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Bank of Nova Scotia</SOC><CITE>[1984] S.J. No. 956</CITE><COURTJUR>Q.B.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at paras. 3&ndash;5, Book of Authorities, Tab 22</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R v. S.G.</SOC><CITE>[2012] O.J. No. 1428</CITE><COURTJUR>O.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at para. 27, Book of Authorities, Tab 23</P1></P>
<P>71. It is submitted that the oath of office of a Crown Attorney does not create any duty to an investigating police officer to defend them against allegations of assault. It clearly sets out a duty to the public to act objectively. Further, it is submitted that the decision not to continue with a prosecution or not to call certain evidence in a prosecution because of the belief that an accused's <EM>Charter</EM> rights have been violated is not, and cannot be, an unlawful act. This conduct is the type of conduct that will only be reviewed by the Courts in the criminal context if there is an abuse of process or the fair trial rights of an accused person are affected. Moreover, it is submitted that a Crown's exercise of his or her discretion not to bring a fresh evidence application on appeal can similarly not be an unlawful act. Consequently, even if all of the allegations of the conduct of the Crowns in this case (which sound more in negligence than misfeasance in any event) are accepted as true, they cannot give rise to any remedy for these respondents.</P>
<P>72. The tenuous nature of the unlawful act alleged by the respondents is evident when it is contrasted with the unlawful act alleged in <EM>Odhavji</EM>. In that case, it was pleaded that the police officer defendants had breached their specific and express statutory duty to &ldquo;cooperate fully&rdquo; with the members of the SIU &ldquo;in the conduct of investigations&rdquo; pursuant to section 113(9) of the <EM>Police Services Act</EM> by failing to co-operate with and frustrating the SIU's investigation. The statutory duty allegedly breached was direct and specific and clearly applied to the defendants. In this case, the statutory duty relied on is owed to the public and the parties to a prosecution and is a broad duty to act impartially, rather than a specific requirement to conduct a prosecution in a particular way, or to defend an investigating police officer in the course of a prosecution.</P>
<P>73. Further, while the respondents plead &ldquo;bad faith&rdquo;, they fail to particularize it in any way. As recently noted by this Court in <EM>Taylor</EM>, the tort of misfeasance cannot be made out by simply referencing bad faith in a Claim:
<QUOTE><P>...although bad faith may go towards demonstrating that a government official's conduct was unlawful, bad faith alone is not sufficient to make out the tort: <EM>Odhavji</EM>, at para. 28. Taylor's pleadings do not satisfy the other components of the tort: that the unlawful conduct alleged was deliberate and carried out by a specific, named official; or that any such conduct was knowingly unlawful and specifically intended to harm Taylor.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>In any event, simply alleging someone acted in bad faith in carrying out their statutory duties is &ldquo;wholly inadequate to sustain a pleading of bad faith. Bad faith must be pled with particularity&rdquo;. The pleading of bad faith in paragraph 48 of the respondent's Claim is completely bald.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Taylor v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[2018] O.J. No. 611</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 17, Book of Authorities, Tab 24</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Portuguese Canadian Credit Union Ltd. v. 1141931 Ontario Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2012] O.J. No. 1861</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 8, Book of Authorities, Tab 25</P1></P>
<P>74. Further, there are no material facts pleaded in the Claim to support an allegation that the Crowns exercised their discretion in the manner that they did for the purpose of harming the respondents.</P>
<P>75. Ontario submits that Stinson J. was required to determine whether all of the requisite elements of the tort of misfeasance were made out in this case and whether adequate material facts were pleaded. With respect to the required elements of bad faith, dishonesty, an unlawful act and an intention to harm, it is submitted that Stinson J. failed to do so, and this was in error. Further, the Claim is deficient in each of these respects and the allegations of misfeasance should have been struck on that basis.</P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>4.</N><TI>MOTION JUDGE ERRED IN FAILING TO CONSIDER DOCUMENTS INCORPORATED BY REFERENCE INTO THE STATEMENT OF CLAIM</TI>
<P>76. Finally, Ontario submits Stinson J. erred in failing to consider evidence on the motion below. Evidence will be admissible on a motion under both Rule 21.01(1) (a) and (b) where that evidence is incorporated into a statement of claim by reference. Further, where prior Court proceedings are referred to in a claim, the Court may consider materials from those proceedings for certain basic facts when determining whether the claim discloses a reasonable cause of action. Finally, the Court may also consider documents in addition to the statement of claim where they provide an &ldquo;essential factual context&rdquo; omitted from the claim, or are necessary to determine the &ldquo;substantive adequacy&rdquo; of the Claim.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Leadbeater v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[2001] O.J. No. 3472</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at para. 8, Book of Authorities, Tab 26</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Beardsley v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[2001] O.J. No. 4574</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 24, Book of Authorities, Tab 27</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Montreal Trust Co. of Canada v. Toronto-Dominion Bank</SOC><YEAR>1992</YEAR><CITE>40 C.P.C. (3d) 389</CITE><COURTJUR>Gen. Div.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at p. 6, Book of Authorities, Tab 28</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>McCreight v. Canada</SOC><CITE>[2013] O.J. No. 3263</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, Book of Authorities, Tab 29</P1></P>
<P>77. Despite this well-established law, in his decision below, Stinson J. found:
<QUOTE><P>I note that one procedural issue arose at the hearing when the AG sought to refer to Ms. Cress man's conduct at trial as evidenced in a transcript of the proceedings. While the AG argued that the transcript was incorporated by reference into the statement of claim, I ruled that it was evidence that was not admissible on this motion to strike pursuant to rule 21.01(2)(b) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Reasons for Decision, Stinson J., June 13, 2017, at para. 31, Appeal Book, Tab 7</P1></P>
<P>78. Stinson J. conducted no analysis of the prevailing law in coming to this conclusion so it is unknown why he made this finding. It is submitted that the finding is in error and cannot stand. Further, it is submitted that the transcripts of the Court proceedings giving rise to this matter are necessary to determine the substantive adequacy of the respondents' claims and to provide an essential factual context omitted from the Claim.
<P1>Rule 21.01 (2)(a),(b)</P1>
<P1><EM>Leadbeater</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para, 8</P1>
<P1><EM>Beardsley</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 24.</P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ORDER REQUESTED</TI>
<P>79. Ontario requests an Order allowing its appeal regarding the misfeasance allegations, with costs.</P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULY SUBMITTED.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>March 22, 2018</BOLD></P>
