<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">I. NATURE OF THIS APPEAL</TI>
<P>1. The Plaintiffs/Respondents, Jamie Clark, Donald Belanger and Steven Watts (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Respondents&rdquo;</BOLD>) respond to the Attorney General of Ontario's (<BOLD>&ldquo;Attorney General&rdquo;</BOLD> or <BOLD>&ldquo;Appellant&rdquo;</BOLD>) appeal of the decision of the Honourable Justice Stinson of the Superior Court of Justice, dated June 13, 2017, refusing to strike the Respondents' claim for misfeasance in a public office.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">II. OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>2. This action is about the liability of the Attorney General for the misconduct of Crown Attorneys in carrying out the prosecutions of two individuals for serious crimes.</P>
<P>3. It is the Respondents' position that during these prosecutions, Crown Attorneys acted deliberately, in bad faith and unlawfully by violating their sworn duties under the <EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM>.</P>
<P>4. In particular, the Crown Attorneys failed to call crucial, available evidence to rebut allegations by the accused that investigating police officers had committed egregious <EM>Charter</EM> violations while working on the case. The Respondents allege that the Crown Attorneys' misconduct was motivated by an improper purpose. The Crown Attorneys were aware of the harm their misconduct would cause the police officers, and their unlawful acts in fact resulted in irreparable reputational harm to the officers, whom this Honourable Court labelled &ldquo;torturers.&rdquo; On this basis, the Respondents' claim against the Attorney General for the Crown Attorneys' misfeasance in a public office.</P>
<P>5. In the court below, Stinson J. dismissed the Attorney General's motion to strike and allowed the claim in misfeasance to proceed to trial.</P>
<P>6. The Respondents submit that Stinson J. was correct in ruling that: (i) the Attorney General can be held liable for Crown Attorneys' misfeasant actions; (ii) the Respondents have pleaded the essential elements of the tort of misfeasance in a public office as well as the material facts to support those elements; and (iii) that the issues of the scope of Crown Attorneys' duties and whether they were breached in this case (along with complex policy considerations about the effects of imposing liability) are matters that ought to be determined on the basis of a complete evidentiary record at trial.</P>
<P>7. For these reasons, the Attorney General's appeal should be dismissed, and the Respondents' action should proceed to a trial on the merits.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">III. FACTS</TI>
<P>8. The Respondents rely on the Statement of Claim's more comprehensive version of facts, the most essential of which are provided below.</P>
<P>9. The Respondents, Jamie Clark (<BOLD>&ldquo;Sgt. Clark&rdquo;</BOLD>), Donald Belanger (<BOLD>&ldquo;Det. Sgt. Belanger&rdquo;</BOLD>) and Steven Watts (<BOLD>&ldquo;Det. Sgt. Watts&rdquo;</BOLD>), (collectively, the <BOLD>&ldquo;Officers&rdquo;</BOLD>), are police officers with the Toronto Police Service. They were members of the Hold-Up Squad at the relevant time.</P>
<P>10. In February 2009, the Officers investigated a very serious robbery and forcible confinement at a commercial establishment. The perpetrators had brandished a firearm, zip-tied the victim, duct-taped his mouth and forcibly confined him while stealing approximately $389,000 of copper tubing.
<P1><BOLD>Officers' <UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER>, June 22, 2016 (&ldquo;<UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER>&rdquo;) at para. 7.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>11. On or about June 11, 2009, after a thorough investigation, the Officers formulated reasonable and probable grounds to arrest Neil Singh (<BOLD>&ldquo;Singh&rdquo;</BOLD>) and Randy Maharaj (<BOLD>&ldquo;Maharaj&rdquo;</BOLD>) and charge them with various offences in connection with the crime. Upon their arrest, both accused gave statements, which were video recorded. The accused elected to have a preliminary inquiry following which they were committed to stand trial.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 9&ndash;11.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>12. For the first time, over two and a half years later<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>During a June 12, 2009 bail hearing, counsel for Maharaj said that his client had suffered injuries&mdash;bumps and scratches behind his ear&mdash;during the arrest. Counsel did not allege any assaultive conduct by the Officers during the interrogations. Nor was it alleged that there was any injury to Maharaj's rib. During the preliminary inquiry, counsel asked the police witnesses about physically assaulting the accused, and the Officers categorically denied the assault had taken place (see <UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at para. 10).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, at the trial in the Superior Court of Justice before Justice Thorburn, the two accused brought applications to stay proceedings based on alleged physical mistreatment at the hands of the Officers following their arrest. Maharaj alleged that he had been physically assaulted before he provided his inculpatory statement. The nature of the assault was so vicious that he alleged he had suffered a &ldquo;cracked rib&rdquo; in the process. To attempt to buttress his claim, his counsel provided the Crown with an X-ray of Maharaj's chest taken after his arrest.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 10&ndash;13.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>13. The Crown assigned to the case, Sheila Cressman (<BOLD>&ldquo;Ms. Cressman&rdquo;</BOLD>), consulted Dr. Farley Moss (<BOLD>&ldquo;Dr. Moss&rdquo;</BOLD>) at Scarborough Centenary Hospital regarding the X-Ray. Dr. Moss confirmed the X-Ray showed a fractured rib, and said that this injury would cause excruciating pain if a person moved his upper arms or body. Dr. Moss said it was <BOLD><UNDER>possible</UNDER></BOLD> the rib injury occurred on the day of the arrest.</P>
<P>14. Dr. Moss was not provided with a copy of Maharaj's videotaped statement to assess whether or not it was consistent with someone having just had their rib broken, as Maharaj had alleged. During that videotaped statement, Maharaj is seen freely using his arms and carrying on in such a way that it was not possible he had sustained the rib injury at the time (this will be dealt with more fully below).
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 14&ndash;16.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>15. The Respondents have pleaded that Ms. Cressman failed to take further obvious and appropriate steps to investigate Maharaj's allegation. In particular, Ms. Cressman:
<P1>(a) never asked Dr. Moss to review the videotaped statement, in which Maharaj is seen making various movements with his arms that were incompatible with having a fresh rib injury;</P1>
<P1>(b) never asked Dr. Moss further questions regarding other potential time periods in which the injury could have occurred;</P1>
<P1>(c) never made inquiries of staff at Maplehurst Detention Centre (<BOLD>&ldquo;Maplehurst&rdquo;</BOLD>), where Maharaj was incarcerated during his trial, about Maharaj, even though she was in possession of Maharaj's medical records from the facility that showed no complaints about a rib injury any time after his arrest;</P1>
<P1>(d) did not properly review the transcripts of the bail hearing to understand the inconsistent injuries reported then as opposed to those reported at the time of the stay application; and</P1>
<P1>(e) did not seek further advice or comment from the Officers who had testified at the preliminary hearing and adamantly denied assaulting Maharaj.</P1></P>
<P>16. Despite her failure to take any steps to properly investigate the unsubstantiated allegation, Ms. Cressman, in consultation with senior Crown Attorney Frank Armstrong (<BOLD>&ldquo;Mr. Armstrong&rdquo;</BOLD>), decided that Maharaj's statement would not be admissible because of involuntariness and therefore there would be no case against him. Mr. Armstrong did not direct Ms. Cressman or anyone else to conduct a further investigation into the allegation. The Crown decided to stay the charges against Maharaj on November 22, 2011.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 16&ndash;22 and 28.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>17. Singh's trial commenced on November 28, 2011. Singh also sought to stay the proceedings against him on the basis of abusive police conduct. He falsely testified that he also had been assaulted by the Officers. He relied on the purported mistreatment of Maharaj at the hands of the police to buttress his claim. On the ensuing application, Maharaj provided <EM>viva voce</EM> evidence that he had been assaulted by the Officers.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at para. 19.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>18. Although aware that the Officers had previously testified under oath that they did not engage in any assaultive conduct and would testify to that effect if called as witnesses, Ms. Cressman called no evidence to challenge or contradict the false testimony. Rather, she essentially accepted that the alleged assaults had occurred. She did so notwithstanding that she had assured Det. Sgt. Watt that he and the other Officers would be called as witnesses. However, after the first day of hearing, Ms. Cressman informed Det. Sgt. Watt she would not require the Officers' evidence. Though Det. Sgt. Watt expressed his concern to Ms. Cressman about how this decision would adversely affect the outcome of the case and findings that might be made against the Officers, Ms. Cressman would not change her position and the Officers were prevented from testifying.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 19&ndash;21.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>19. The Officers were not parties to the proceeding involving the Appellant and Singh and, to the knowledge of the Crown, had no standing to adduce evidence or make representations to the Court. The Officers relied on the Appellant to ensure that findings of illegal and improper conduct were not made against them in the absence of a full and complete record. Although the Crown could not control whether a Court might make those findings, the Crown could control whether the trial Court had all information relevant to the Officers' conduct given the potential for adverse findings against the Officers.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 20-21, 25.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>20. Ms. Cressman did not require Singh's counsel to prove the nature of the alleged assault, nor did she test the evidence in any way. She simply conceded that the assaultive conduct, as falsely alleged, had occurred and that there had been a serious <EM>Charter</EM> violation. Ms. Cressman knew at the time that doing so would have serious repercussions not only for the case she was prosecuting but for the Officers as well.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at para. 22.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>21. In the face of the Crown's factual and legal concessions, Justice Thorburn concluded that the conduct alleged by Maharaj and Singh had occurred as they alleged. Essentially, it was the Court's view that in the absence of any competing evidence, the only conclusion available was to accept the evidence of Maharaj and Singh, which the Court did in a judgement released on March 28, 2012.</P>
<P>22. However, Thorburn J. did not stay the proceedings. Singh was subsequently convicted by a jury of armed robbery and forceful confinement. Though Justice Thorburn dismissed Singh's stay application, she reduced Singh's sentence because of the Officers' &ldquo;brutality&rdquo; and &ldquo;thoroughly reprehensible&rdquo; behaviour in the case. The Court's findings were widely reported in the mainstream media and on the internet. Singh appealed the decision of Thorburn J. refusing to stay the proceedings to this Honourable Court.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 23-24.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>23. Following the judgment, the Crown Law Office&mdash;Criminal notified the Chief of Police of their concerns about the Officers' conduct. The Special Investigations Unit (<BOLD>&ldquo;SIU&rdquo;</BOLD>) invoked its mandate to conduct an investigation. However, Maharaj refused to be interviewed or to participate in the investigation, and the SIU withdrew its mandate in July 2012.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at para. 29.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>24. After the SIU withdrew its mandate, the Toronto Police Service Professional Standards Unit (<BOLD>&ldquo;TPSPS&rdquo;</BOLD>) conducted a comprehensive and independent review of the allegations of misconduct against the Officers. The investigators concluded that, based on an analysis of all the evidence, the allegations that the Officers used excessive force could not be substantiated.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at para. 30.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>25. In and around November 2012, the Crown Law Office was made aware of these new material facts that demonstrated the serious injustice that had been done to the Officers. The Crown took no action in response.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 31, 43.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>26. Before Singh's appeal was argued, Det. Sgt. Watt met with Amy Alyea (<BOLD>&ldquo;Ms. Alyea&rdquo;</BOLD>), who was going to argue the appeal on behalf of the Crown. He told Ms. Alyea that an egregious mistake had occurred. He advised Ms. Alyea of the results of the TPSPS report, of which she had a copy, and of Ms. Cressman's conduct. He asked Ms. Alyea to correct the injustice that had occurred in the lower court in whatever manner was appropriate.</P>
<P>27. Despite Det. Sgt. Watt's efforts, Ms. Alyea: (i) took no steps to investigate further, (ii) took no steps to rectify and repair the damage that had been done to the Officers' reputations, and (iii) took no steps to prepare and file an application to introduce fresh evidence before the Court of Appeal. During oral arguments in the appeal, the Court asked several questions about the Officers' behaviour, but Ms. Alyea never adequately advised the Court of the new material facts the Crown had learned or of the TPSPS's exculpatory findings regarding the Officers' conduct. Any attempt made by Ms. Alyea to alert the Court to the TPSPS findings or the substance of the report fell far below what was required in the circumstances. The report was not properly before the Court nor had it been properly disclosed to counsel for Mr. Singh.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 32-33, 35, 43 and 47.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>28. On December 12, 2013, the Court of Appeal released its judgment, in which it granted the appellant's stay application. The Court condemned the &ldquo;egregious nature of the police misconduct,&rdquo; which it equated with &ldquo;torture.&rdquo; It found that the alleged abusive interrogation techniques were &ldquo;calculated, prolonged and skilfully choreographed.&rdquo; The Court stated that Crown counsel was unable to provide any details of the results of the TPSPS investigation. The Court adverted several times to the fact that the Defence's allegations were uncontradicted or uncontested by the Crown. The Court found the case for a stay more compelling because the allegations of &ldquo;serious criminal conduct&rdquo; by the police had gone unchallenged.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at para. 35.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>29. The Court of Appeal's judgment was also widely reported in the mainstream media and on the internet. Articles about the case repeated Singh's and Maharaj's false and defamatory allegations, and condemned the Officers' behaviour.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at paras. 36-37.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>30. Following the Court of Appeal judgment, the SIU re-opened their investigation. Maharaj agreed to be interviewed. The investigators reviewed all of the records and obtained opinion evidence. That investigation concluded that Maharaj's rib injury post-dated the time of arrest, and that his physical demeanour in the videotaped statement was inconsistent with his having sustained any rib injury at the time of arrest (during his video-recorded interview Maharaj is moving about in a way that would not have been possible had he suffered the cracked rib injury he alleged he had suffered at the hands of the Officers). The SIU found that the allegations by Maharaj were not substantiated.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at para. 38.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>31. Also following the Court of Appeal judgment, the Chief of the Toronto Police Service asked the Ontario Provincial Police (<BOLD>&ldquo;OPP&rdquo;</BOLD>) to conduct an independent review of the TPSPS investigation. The OPP review was conducted by an experienced, high-ranking investigator. On April 9, 2015, the OPP investigator concluded the TPSPS review had been thorough and she had no reason to refute its conclusions that the allegations of police misconduct were unsubstantiated.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at para. 39.</BOLD></P1></P>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>The Officers Commence an Action Against the Attorney General of Ontario</EM></TI>
<P>32. As alleged in the Statement of Claim, several months after the Court of Appeal released its judgment, the Officers retained counsel. Counsel had the opportunity to review the entire record and listen to the audio of the oral arguments that were made in the Court of Appeal.</P>
<P>33. After due consideration, counsel formed a legal opinion that they communicated to the Officers: the conduct of the Appellant may be tortious, and a novel claim in negligence and misfeasance in a public office could be pursued. It was only at this point that the Officers discovered that there was a viable claim, albeit a novel one.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Statement of Claim</UNDER> at para. 50.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>34. The Officers issued their Claim on June 22, 2016. In it, they claim as against the Attorney General damages for negligence and misfeasance in a public office.</P>
<P>35. In particular, the Claim alleges that Crown Attorneys owe a duty of care to investigating police officers and that this duty was breached through the conduct of Ms. Cressman, Ms. Alyea, and their superiors. The Claim also alleges that Ms. Cressman, Ms. Alyea and their superiors engaged in deliberate and unlawful conduct that they knew to be inconsistent with their professional obligations, and that they did so in bad faith, with the knowledge that this misconduct would likely injure the Officers.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>The Attorney General's Motion to Strike</EM></TI>
<P>36. The Attorney General brought a motion to strike the Claim pursuant to Rules 21 and 25 on the basis that:
<P1>(a) The action is statute-barred because the limitation period has expired: the Plaintiffs failed to commence it within two years of discovering the material facts on which the Claim is based. In particular, the Plaintiffs were aware of the material facts giving rise to their claim based on the conduct of Ms. Cressman by at least July 2012. The Plaintiffs were aware of the material facts giving rise to their claim based on the conduct of Ms. Alyea by at least December 12, 2013;</P1>
<P1>(b) The claims in negligence and misfeasance are not tenable at law. As Crown Attorneys do not owe a duty of care to investigating police officers, it is plain and obvious that the claim does not disclose a reasonable cause of action in negligence and has no reasonable prospect of success. As the Attorney General states in its factum, &ldquo;[Aside from malicious prosecution,] no other action in tort is available against a Crown Attorney&rdquo;; and</P1>
<P1>(c) The claim in misfeasance is frivolous and vexations, as it did not provide full particulars to support this cause of action.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>The Decisions of the Motions Judge</EM></TI>
<P>37. Stinson J. bifurcated the motion, and heard arguments on the limitation issue first. On January 4, 2017, Stinson J. dismissed the Attorney General's motion to strike on the basis of the limitation period argument by finding, <EM>inter alia</EM>: due to the legal and factual complexities of the case, it was not plain and obvious that the limitation issue would be decided against the Plaintiffs and the issue should only be determined after a complete factual context is placed before the Court.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Clark v. Ontario (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 43</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD><UNDER>Respondents' Book of Authorities</UNDER> (&ldquo;<UNDER>BOA</UNDER>&rdquo;). Tab 1.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>38. On June 13, 2017, Stinson J. released his decision on the second part of the Attorney General's motion, i.e. to strike the Appellants' claim for no reasonable cause of action with respect to the claims of negligence and misfeasance in a public office.</P>
<P>39. In regard to both claims, Stinson J. held that it was not plain and obvious that Crown Attorneys have absolute immunity from civil claims, other than claims for malicious prosecution and intentional non-disclosure of exculpatory evidence. He therefore declined to strike the Officers' Claim on the basis of common-law Crown Attorney immunity.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Clark v. Ontario (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 3683</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Clark</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 77, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>40. In regard to the claim in negligence, Stinson J. held that it is not plain and obvious that there is no <EM>prima facie</EM> duty owed by trial Crown Attorneys to investigating police officers to take reasonable care in the course of investigating and defending <EM>Charter</EM> motions alleging serious misconduct by police officers. However, at the second stage of the <EM>Anns</EM> test, Stinson J. found, in the absence of any evidence and on pure speculation, that policy concerns would negate the <EM>prima facie</EM> duty of care Crown Attorneys owe to investigating police officers.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM> at paras. 104, 113, 134&ndash;137, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>41. The Officers appeal of Stinson J.'s judgment regarding the negligence issue has been joined with the Attorney General's appeal of Stinson J.'s judgments regarding the limitations and misfeasance issues.</P>
<P>42. In regard to the claim of misfeasance, Stinson J. reviewed the Statement of Claim thoroughly and held that the Officers had pleaded the essential elements of the tort by asserting that the Crown Attorneys acted knowingly and deliberately, in bad faith and unlawfully&mdash;in contravention of their sworn duties under the <EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. C. 49&mdash;with knowledge that their misconduct was likely to injure the Officers.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM> at paras. 148-149, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>43. Stinson J. found that a determination of whether the Crown Attorneys acted within the scope of their duties and did not breach any legal obligations is a matter properly determined at trial. As on a motion to strike, it is assumed that the plaintiffs can prove their allegations, Stinson J. declined to strike the claim of misfeasance.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM> at para. 150, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">IV. ISSUES AND THE LAW</TI>
<P>44. The sole issue to be determined in this appeal is whether Stinson J. made errors of law and/or mixed fact and law in allowing the Officers' claim in misfeasance to proceed to trial.</P>
<P>45. The Respondents submit Stinson J. properly analyzed the elements of the tort of misfeasance in a public office, and was correct in determining that the Officers' pleading satisfied those elements. Stinson J. applied the correct test to determine whether the claim should proceed, and appropriately held that the issue of whether the Crown Attorneys breached their legal duties is a matter that should be determined at a hearing on the merits, with the benefit of a full evidentiary record.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>The Law on a Motion to Strike</EM></TI>
<P>46. The Supreme Court has stated that the test applicable to a motion to strike is that,
<QUOTE><P>[I]t is plain and obvious, assuming the facts pleaded to be true, that the pleading discloses no reasonable cause of action.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Imperial Tobacco Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2011 SCC 42</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Imperial Tobacco</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 17, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 3.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>47. A motion to strike is designed to weed out claims that are &ldquo;hopeless,&rdquo; &ldquo;certain to fail,&rdquo; or &ldquo;could not possibly succeed.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD><EM>Imperial Tobacco</EM> at para. 19;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Paton Estate v. Ontario Lottery and Gaming Commission</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 458</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Paton Estate</EM>&rdquo;) at paras. 2 and 48;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Addison Chevrolet Buick GMC Ltd. v. General Motors of Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 324</CITE><PARANUM>23</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>; <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tabs 3, 4 and 5.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>48. The motion to strike is a tool that must be used with care. This is especially the case where the Court considers novel claims, including recognized causes of action that are brought for the first time by a particular class of claimant or in a new context. In these cases, courts must be generous and err on the side of permitting the novel but arguable claim to proceed to trial.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Imperial Tobacco</EM> at para. 21; <EM>Paton Estate</EM> at paras. 11-12, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tabs 3 and 4.</BOLD></P1></P>
<BLOCK4><N>(1)</N><TI><EM>The Jurisprudence Does Not Preclude an Action in Misfeasance Against the Attorney General</EM></TI>
<P>49. Contrary to the Attorney General's argument, a review of the relevant judgments from the Supreme Court, this Honourable Court and other courts does not support the proposition that actions for misfeasance (or other torts) against the Attorney General arising from the conduct of Crown Attorneys are precluded. While it is true that, thus far, only claims for malicious prosecution and intentional nondisclosure of exculpatory evidence against the Attorney General have succeeded, that does not entail that other claims are precluded. Moreover, the appellate case law the Attorney General cites does not support its argument.</P>
<P>50. The decisions of this Honourable Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Abernethy v. Canada</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Brummell v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> do not preclude an action for misfeasance arising from the misconduct of Crown Attorneys. In <CASEREF><SOC>Abernethy v. Canada</SOC></CASEREF>, the Court upheld the motion judge's conclusion that, aside from an action for malicious prosecution, Crown Attorneys are protected from suit <UNDER>in their personal capacities</UNDER> by statutory and common-law immunity.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Abernethy v. Canada</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 340</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Abernethy</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 12, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 6.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>51. The Respondents have never claimed as against the Crown Attorneys in their personal capacities. The Respondents do not challenge that section 8 of the <EM>Ministry of the Attorney General Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. M. 17 provides immunity to Crown Attorneys in their personal capacities for acts done in the performance of their duties, nor do they challenge that Crown Attorneys are protected from suit in their personal capacities (except for malicious prosecution) by common-law immunity.</P>
<P>52. In fact, the Respondents have relied on Crown Attorneys' personal immunity to argue against the policy concern that imposing liability in the circumstances of this case would have a &ldquo;chilling effect.&rdquo; The Respondents argue that Crown Attorneys' indemnification from personal civil liability significantly reduces the prospect that their fear of civil liability will make them more defensive in prosecuting cases.</P>
<P>53. When this Honourable Court upheld the motion judge's dismissal of claims of vicarious liability against the Crown in <EM>Abernethy</EM>, it did so because the causes of action were not properly pleaded, as there was &ldquo;no factually material basis&rdquo; to support the claims. It did not dismiss the claims against the Crown because causes of action other than malicious prosecution were precluded.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Abernethy</EM>, at paras. 13-14, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 6.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>54. This Honourable Court's findings in <CASEREF><SOC>Brummell v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> were substantially similar to <EM>Abernethy</EM>. The motions judge in <EM>Brummell</EM> held that Crown Attorneys were generally immune from suit, excepting malicious prosecution, but this was meant in the sense that they are immune in their personal capacities&mdash;<EM>not</EM> in the sense that all other causes of action brought vicariously against the Attorney General are precluded. The remainder of allegations against the Crown Attorneys, which could only proceed vicariously through the Attorney General, were struck because they were not viable, either because they we re not properly pleaded or did not exist at law.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Brummell v. Ontario (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 486</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Brummell</EM>&rdquo;), at paras. 47-48 and paras. 49&ndash;67, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 7.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>55. As found by Stinson J., the appeal in <EM>Brummell</EM> turned on a procedural matter, i.e. whether the respondents had brought their Rule 21 motion in time, and whether the motions judge had erred in hearing the matter despite the delay. While this Honourable Court did note that the motions judge concluded the claim was &ldquo;fatally flawed,&rdquo; the fatal flaws concerned deficient pleadings in that the plaintiff did not plead material facts or alleged causes of action that did not exist at law (such as &ldquo;non-feasance,&rdquo; &ldquo;alienation of affection&rdquo; and &ldquo;false criminal allegations&rdquo;). The &ldquo;fatal flaws&rdquo; were <UNDER>not</UNDER> that the plaintiff had pleaded causes of action from which the Attorney General was immune.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM>, at para. 67, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 2;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Brummell v. Ontario (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2014 ONCA 828</CITE><PARANUM>5, 7&ndash;11</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 7.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>56. For these reasons, neither <EM>Abernethy</EM> nor <EM>Brummell</EM> supersede previous decisions, as the Attorney General contends, nor do they stand for the proposition that the Attorney General is immune from all actions arising from Crown Attorney misconduct except for malicious prosecution or intentional nondisclosure of exculpatory evidence.
<P1><BOLD><UNDER>Factum of the Attorney General</UNDER> at para. 37n.5.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>57. The other cases relied on by the Attorney General also do not stand for the proposition that all causes of action other than malicious prosecution and intentional nondisclosure of exculpatory evidence are precluded. Nowhere in <CASEREF><SOC>Miazga v. Kvello Estate</SOC></CASEREF> does the Supreme Court preclude claims other than malicious prosecution against the Attorney General for the conduct of Crown Attorneys. Instead, the Court clarified the meaning of the &ldquo;malice&rdquo; requirement as requiring proof that a prosecutor commenced or continued a prosecution with an &ldquo;improper purpose&rdquo; that is inconsistent with her role as a &ldquo;minister of justice.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Miazga v. Kvello Estate</SOC><CITE>2009 SCC 51</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Miazga</EM>&rdquo;), at paras. 81, 89, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 8.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>58. Likewise, the decisions of this Honourable Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. Gilkinson</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Miguna v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> do not preclude claims other than malicious prosecution against the Attorney General for Crown Attorneys' misconduct. Instead, both decisions focus on the requirement that the high threshold of malice is necessary to establish liability against Crown Attorneys when exercising their prosecutorial functions. In fact, both decisions indicate that causes of action other than malicious prosecution&mdash;including misfeasance in a public office&mdash;may be available if the high threshold of malice is properly pleaded:
<QUOTE><P>[If the allegations are] appropriately supported by material facts, and proven, they&mdash;and other facts pleaded&mdash;could support claims for malicious prosecution, breach of the Charter and misfeasance in public office as against the Crown Attorney and Police defendants.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Miguna v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[2005] O.J. No. 5346</CITE><COURTJUR>ONCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 9 at paras. 11, 17;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Gilbert v. Gilkinson</SOC><CITE>[2005] O.J. No. 5347</CITE><COURTJUR>ONCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 10 at para. 7.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>59. This Honourable Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Folland v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> and the Superior Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Whitty v. Wells</SOC></CASEREF>, which followed <EM>Folland</EM>, both found that the malice requirement articulated in the <EM>Nelles</EM> trilogy did not preclude actions other than malicious prosecution. Both found that <EM>Miazga</EM> did not address whether allegations of bad faith or malice could give rise to other causes of action, such as misfeasance in public office, and found that Crown liability for torts involving bad faith would not threaten the &ldquo;effective and uninhibited prosecution of criminal wrongdoing&rdquo; recognized in <EM>Miazga</EM> and <CASEREF><SOC>Proulx v. Quebec (Attorney General)</SOC></CASEREF>.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Folland v. Ontario</SOC><YEAR>2003</YEAR><CITE>64 O.R. (3d) 89</CITE><COURTJUR>ONCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Folland</EM>&rdquo;) at paras. 18&ndash;22, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 11;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Whitty v. Wells</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 4920</CITE><PARANUM>27&ndash;29</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, BOA Tab 12.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>60. In addition, several cases decided since <EM>Miazga</EM> have demonstrated not only that the Attorney General may be liable for causes of action other than malicious prosecution, but also that malice may not be a requirement for framing Crown liability. The most prominent example is <CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC></CASEREF>, wherein the Supreme Court recognized Crown liability for <EM>Charter</EM> damages for intentional nondisclosure; of exculpatory evidence on a standard that was lower than malice.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Henry v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>2015 SCC 24</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Henry</EM>&rdquo;) at paras. 66, 82, BOA Tab 13.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>61. There is also a line of cases following <CASEREF><SOC>Krieger v. Law Society of Alberta</SOC></CASEREF> that suggests both that other causes of action against Crown Attorneys may be available, and that malice is not a required element of these claims. In <EM>Krieger</EM>, the Supreme Court defined &ldquo;prosecutorial discretion&rdquo; as encompassing &ldquo;core&rdquo; elements, including &ldquo;ultimate decisions as to whether a prosecution should be brought, continued or ceased, and what the prosecution ought to be for.&rdquo; It is only for actions that fall within the scope of this prosecutorial discretion that the <EM>Nelles</EM> trilogy limited liability to malicious prosecution. Where a prosecutor's conduct falls outside the ambit of these &ldquo;core&rdquo; functions&mdash;for instance, where the prosecutor's <EM>tactics</EM> violate her statutory or common-law duties&mdash;it may not be necessary to demonstrate malice or bad faith as a prerequisite to liability.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>The example considered in <EM>Krieger</EM> was where the prosecutor failed to disclose relevant evidence. The Supreme Court found that such disclosure was a prosecutorial duty, and not a matter of prosecutorial discretion. In running afoul of its duty, the prosecutor was subject to review and discipline by the provincial law society. In this sense, <EM>Krieger</EM> can be seen as the key predecessor case to <EM>Henry</EM>, which cited the former for this proposition at para. 62. (Indeed, even <EM>Miazga</EM>, which is the central case defining the &ldquo;malice&rdquo; requirement, employs the language of a prosecutor's &ldquo;core&rdquo; functions to delineate where malicious prosecution lies: it is where the Crown prosecutor &ldquo;<EM>commenced</EM> or <EM>continued</EM>&rdquo; the impugned prosecution with malice (<EM>Miazga</EM> at para. 89)). In the case at bar, the Officers claim against the Attorney General for negligence and misfeasance for the Crown Attorneys' violation of their statutory and common-law duties, such as their duty &ldquo;to cause charges to be further investigated, and additional evidence to be collected, and further information that is likely to shed light on what did or did not happen to be provided, with the assistance of police, so that prosecutions may not fail for want of proof&rdquo;; to see that all available legal proof of the facts is presented before the court for a determination on the merits; to be firm while being fair in prosecuting the accused so that the Court will not be duped by defences which are not thoroughly examined in Court; to call all material witnesses essential to the unfolding of the narrative of events; and to see to it that every material point is made which supports the prosecution's case (see para. 68 of the Officers' <UNDER>Amended Factum of the Appellants</UNDER> in the appeal concerning negligence). It is the Officers' position that, by acting in violation of their sworn duties under the <EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. C. 49 as well as their common-law duties, the Crown Attorneys were not acting within the ambit of prosecutorial discretion and that they may therefore be liable for negligence in addition to misfeasance.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In both <CASEREF><SOC>Driskell v. Dangerfield</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Ferron v. Goodier</SOC></CASEREF>, courts followed <EM>Krieger</EM> in finding that prosecutors may be liable for conduct that falls outside the scope of prosecutorial discretion (such as nondisclosure of relevant evidence), and refused to strike claims for negligence against the Crown for this reason.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Krieger v. Law Society of Alberta</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 65</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Krieger</EM>&rdquo;) at paras. 4-5, 43&ndash;47, 49, 54, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 14;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Driskell v. Dangerfield</SOC><CITE>2007 MBQB 142</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Driskell</EM>&rdquo;) at paras. 42-43, 58, 67&ndash;72 and 83-84, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 15 (varied on appeal, [2008] M.J. No. 165 (MBCA)), <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 16;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Ferron v. Goodier</SOC><CITE>2010 ONSC 540</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Ferron</EM>&rdquo;) at paras. 74, 78-79, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 17.</BOLD><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>To the extent that <CASEREF><SOC>Baltovich v. Ontario (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 6991</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Baltovich</EM>&rdquo;), cited by the Attorney General in its appeal factum, found that the reasoning in <EM>Krieger</EM> <UNDER>did not</UNDER> show that claims other than malicious prosecution <EM>may</EM> be available against prosecutors when they act outside the scope of prosecutorial discretion and in violation of their duties, it is incorrect, and <EM>Ferron</EM> is to be preferred. There is nothing in <EM>Krieger</EM> that would limit the application of its reasoning to the context of law society investigations of prosecutors' misconduct, as the Court in <EM>Baltovich</EM> suggests at para. 33. While <EM>Krieger</EM> did not expand the scope of tenable civil actions against Crown Attorneys, its reasoning shows that such actions may not be precluded. Moreover, the Court in <EM>Baltovich</EM> clearly errs in reading <EM>Miazga</EM> as stating that &ldquo;<UNDER>only</UNDER> &lsquo;individuals who have been wrongly and maliciously prosecuted&rsquo; can bring a tenable civil action against a Crown attorney&rdquo; (para. 37, emphasis added). This proposition is nowhere to be found in <EM>Miazga</EM>. Both statute and appellate case law are silent on the question of whether parties other than accused individuals, such as investigating police, may bring actions against the Attorney General for prosecutors' misconduct.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>62. In any case, in regard to the Attorney General's appeal concerning misfeasance, the question of whether malice is required is moot because the Officers have pleaded malice and bad faith as elements of this cause of action.</P>
<P>63. Contrary to the Attorney General's argument at paragraph 46 of its factum, Stinson J. was not required to &ldquo;determine whether <EM>these particular plaintiffs</EM> have a cause of action in misfeasance... whether Crown Attorney liability should be extended to a new class of claimants: investigating police officers&rdquo; in ruling on the motion to strike. The tort of misfeasance in a public office, as set out in <CASEREF><SOC>Odhavji v. Woodhouse</SOC></CASEREF> and subsequent case law, is not defined by any particular class of claimants. As the Officers have pleaded the required elements of the tort, the action should be permitted to proceed to trial.</P>
<P>64. For the above reasons, Stinson J.'s analysis of Crown Attorney civil liability is correct, and the decision not to strike the claim in misfeasance should be upheld and the matter should be allowed to proceed to trial.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM> at paras. 60&ndash;70 and 77-78, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>65. At the very least, case law is unsettled on the issue of the scope of the Attorney General's liability for Crown Attorneys' misconduct, including for misfeasance in a public office, and therefore the point is not properly resolved on a motion to strike.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Nash v. Ontario</SOC><YEAR>1995</YEAR><CITE>27 O.R. (3d) 1</CITE><COURTJUR>ONCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 18;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Addison Chevrolet Buick GMC Ltd. V. General Motors of Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 324</CITE><PARANUM>53</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 19; <EM>Folland</EM> at para. 11, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 10; <EM>Driskell</EM> at para. 71-72, 83, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 15.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>(2)</N><TI><EM>Policy Considerations Were Not Appropriate on This Motion to Strike, and Would Not Have Negated a Cause of Action for Misfeasance in Any Case</EM></TI>
<P>66. Stinson J. was correct not to address complex policy considerations that might bear on the Attorney General's liability for Crown prosecutors' misfeasance in their public office. While such policy considerations are relevant, they are not properly considered on a pleadings motion.</P>
<P>67. In the context of negligence claims involving a novel duty of care, the Supreme Court has stated, &ldquo;policy concerns raised against imposing a duty of care <UNDER>must be more than speculative; a real potential for negative consequences must be apparent</UNDER>.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hill v. Hamilton-Wentworth Regional Police Services Board</SOC><CITE>2007 SCC 41</CITE><PARANUM>48</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 20;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Fullowka v. Pinkerton's of Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2010 SCC 5</CITE><PARANUM>57</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>(emphasis added), <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 21.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>68. The Respondents submit that the same principle is applicable in the context of a claim against the Attorney General for the misfeasance of Crown Attorneys. While the claim against Crown Attorneys for misfeasance itself is not novel, the context of investigating police as claimants and the misconduct that gave rise to the cause of action are novel. For these reasons, policy issues that bear on liability should only be considered on the basis of a full trial record.</P>
<P>69. To decide whether policy considerations negate or limit an action for Crown Attorneys' misfeasance without evidence would be a legal error. It is the Respondents' position that Stinson J. erred in law in his negligence analysis by finding the <EM>prima facie</EM> duty of care Crown Attorneys owe investigating police was negated by policy concerns without any factual basis. This is because policy judgments involve determinations of mixed fact and law. To make such determinations at the pleadings stage, in the absence of an evidentiary record, is to err in law by applying the wrong legal test.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Patrus v. Alberta</SOC><CITE>2011 ABQB 523</CITE><PARANUM>22-23</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER>, Tab 22.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>70. This Honourable Court has repeatedly emphasized that courts should not strike claims on the basis of policy considerations without an evidentiary record. This is especially the case where a novel claim is asserted. Without an evidentiary record, a court cannot analyze the strengths and weaknesses of competing policy arguments, and cannot confidently make judgments about legal and policy issues raised by the parties. To attempt to apply policy considerations without the benefit of a factual record is contrary to the principles on which case law has been understood to develop.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Haskett v. Equifax Canada Inc.</SOC><CITE>[2003] O.J. No. 771</CITE><COURTJUR>ONCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Haskett</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 52, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 23; <EM>Paton Estate</EM> at paras. 35-36 and 48, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 4;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Anger v. Berkshire Investment Group Inc.</SOC><CITE>[2001] O.J. No. 379</CITE><COURTJUR>ONCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at para. 15, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 24;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Rausch v. Pickering (City)</SOC><CITE>2013 ONCA 740</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Rausch</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 74 <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 25.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>71. Even if it were possible to evaluate policy issues on the Officers' pleadings, the policy considerations that are cited in the <EM>Nelles</EM> trilogy and <EM>Henry</EM> would not negate the cause of action for misfeasance. As the Officers argued at paragraphs 64&ndash;73 of their <UNDER>Amended Factum</UNDER> re: negligence, recognizing a cause of action for misfeasance by investigating police would neither divert Crown Attorneys from their prosecutorial duties nor have a &ldquo;chilling effect&rdquo; on their prosecutorial behaviour.</P>
<P>72. The kind of misfeasance at issue in this case does not relate to the exercise of &ldquo;core&rdquo; prosecutorial discretion&mdash;&ldquo;ultimate&rdquo; decisions such as whether a prosecution should be brought, continued or ceased; whether it is in the public interest to prosecute a case; and protecting or respecting the rights of the accused. Instead, it relates to the statutory and common-law duties of Crown Attorneys. These duties&mdash;including the duty to cause charges (like allegations of egregious <EM>Charter</EM> violations) to be further investigated, to adduce available evidence to ensure that cases do not fail for want of proof, etc.&mdash;are essential to the fair and effective administration of justice. When prosecutors violate these duties in bad faith and for improper purposes, and this causes foreseeable injury to others, they ought to be held accountable for this misfeasance.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>For a more exhaustive explanation of these duties and this argument, see paras. 60&ndash;79 of the <UNDER>Amended Factum of the Appellants</UNDER>, appealing the Order of Justice Stinson, dated June 13, 2017, with respect to the ruling on negligence.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>73. Far from diverting Crown Attorneys from their duties, a finding of liability for misfeasance in the circumstances of this case would cause prosecutors to do exactly what they are supposed to do, indeed what they have sworn to do pursuant to the <EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM>: carry out their statutory and common-law duties.</P>
<P>74. Far from having a &ldquo;chilling effect&rdquo; on prosecutors' behaviour, a finding of liability for the Crown Attorneys' misfeasance in the circumstances of this case would motivate prosecutors to actively investigate allegations of egregious <EM>Charter</EM> breaches that can undermine a prosecution, bring the administration of justice into disrepute, and cause grievous and irreparable harm to investigating police officers.</P>
<P>75. As the Officers argue in their appeal concerning Stinson J.'s judgment on the issue of negligence, it is inappropriate to import policy arguments from the context of suits brought by accused persons against Crown Attorneys to the context of this case. The relationship between Crown Attorneys and accused persons is inherently adversarial. Setting the liability threshold too low in that context could risk a flood of litigation from persons who were subject to prosecution. By contrast, the relationship between Crown Attorneys and investigating police is complimentary, as the two must work together closely, in a relationship of trust and reliance, to ensure the effective administration of justice.</P>
<P>76. Even the context of the case, <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, in which police claimed against Crown Attorneys for the provision of negligent legal advice, is not comparable to the context of the case at bar. As Crown Attorneys are routinely called upon to provide legal advice on proper procedure to police, there are legitimate concerns that a low liability threshold could make prosecutors more defensive when they provide such advice. In contrast, it is extremely rare that Crown Attorneys would in bad faith violate their legal duties and concede egregious <EM>Charter</EM> violations that undermine a prosecution and cause irreparable harm to police, without adequate investigation.</P>
<P>77. The Respondents could find no reported case where similar misfeasant conduct was alleged against Crown Attorneys by investigating police. It is therefore highly improbable that the policy concerns about liability from the <EM>Nelles</EM> trilogy and <EM>Henry</EM> would have the same bearing in the case at bar. In any case, in the absence of an evidentiary record, there is no basis for comparison.</P>
<P>78. Finally, the policy considerations cited by the Attorney General must be balanced against other important policy concerns. As the Supreme Court said in justification of recognizing the tort of malicious prosecution,
<QUOTE><P>Against [considerations that support setting a high liability threshold for prosecutorial misconduct] is the principle that the Ministry of the Attorney General and its Prosecutors are not above the law and must be held accountable. Individuals caught up in the justice system must be protected from abuses of power.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>The results of the prosecutors' misfeasance were: the reputations of investigating police officers were irreparably damaged, and they suffered serious personal harm; the administration of justice was brought into disrepute and public confidence in the Crown and police force was eroded; the charges against Maharaj were stayed; and the conviction of Singh was overturned.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Proulx v. Quebec (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2001 SCC 66</CITE><PARANUM>4</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 26; <EM>Driskell</EM> at paras. 75-76, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 15.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>79. Setting the liability threshold too high could undermine the relationship of trust between two complementary parts of the justice system&mdash;investigating police and Crown prosecutors. It would allow Crown Attorneys to get away with misfeasant and bad-faith conduct in violation of their sworn legal duties. It would be an invitation to every accused to allege serious <EM>Charter</EM> violations in the hope that prosecutors will fail to investigate and the cases against them will be discontinued.</P>
<P>80. For the above reasons, the Respondents submit that the policy considerations raised by the Attorney General would not be dispositive in the case at bar. At the very least, policy determinations should be made after an evidentiary record has been established, and not on the basis of speculation or by importing policy concerns from other, dissimilar contexts.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>(3)</N><TI><EM>Stinson J. Was Correct to Consider the Crown Attorneys' Conduct in Allowing the Claim in Misfeasance to Proceed</EM></TI>
<P>81. Stinson J.'s analysis of the Attorney General's arguments concerning courts' review of prosecutorial misconduct at paragraphs 143-144 of his judgment is correct.</P>
<P>82. The case, <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Anderson</SOC></CASEREF> does not stand for the proposition that prosecutorial tactics, such as whether to call relevant and essential evidence, are subject to the very limited review suggested by the Attorney General. The Court in <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Anderson</SOC></CASEREF> states,
<QUOTE><P>All Crown decision making is reviewable for abuse of process. However... exercises of prosecutorial discretion are <EM>only</EM> reviewable for abuse of process. In contrast, tactics and conduct before the court are subject to a wider range of review. The court may exercise its inherent jurisdiction to control its own processes even in the absence of abuse of process.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Anderson</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 41</CITE><PARANUM>36</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 27; see also</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Hillis</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 451</CITE><PARANUM>35&ndash;41</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 28.</BOLD><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>The Respondents recognize that the case at bar exemplifies the highly unusual circumstance of Crown Attorneys' failing to call essential evidence that would help the prosecution, rather than evidence that would help the defence (the salient consideration in <CASEREF><SOC>R v. Hillis</SOC></CASEREF>). Nevertheless, as the Court made clear in relying on <CASEREF><SOC>R v. Felderhoff</SOC><CITE>[2003] O.J. No. 4819</CITE></CASEREF>, <CASEREF><SOC>R v. Anderson</SOC></CASEREF> and <EM>Krieger</EM>, such a decision still constitutes trial tactics and is reviewable on a lower standard than decisions that fall under the umbrella of &ldquo;prosecutorial discretion.&rdquo; In <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. L.L.</SOC><CITE>2015 ABCA 222</CITE></CASEREF>, cited by the Attorney General, the Court also recognized that the decision not to call a witness was a matter of &ldquo;tactics and conduct&rdquo; that was reviewable on a lower standard than matters falling under prosecutorial discretion. The Respondents submit that the trial tactics in the case at bar constitute the &ldquo;exceptional circumstances&rdquo; referred to at para. 13 of that decision.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>83. The impugned &ldquo;tactics&rdquo; of the Crown Attorneys in this case, which include the bad-faith failure to call essential, available evidence to rebut allegations of egregious <EM>Charter</EM> violations, are therefore reviewable by courts. This misfeasance was in violation of Crown Attorneys' legal duties, and was not a matter of prosecutorial discretion: section 11(a) of the <EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM> does not say &ldquo;every Crown Attorney <UNDER>may</UNDER>&rdquo;: it says,
<QUOTE><P>[E]very Crown Attorney <UNDER>shall</UNDER>... cause such charges to be further investigated, and additional evidence to be collected, and sue out process to compel the attendance of witnesses and the production of papers, so that prosecutions may not be delayed unnecessarily or fail through want of proof. (Emphasis added)</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. C. 49.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>84. Moreover, nowhere in any of the case law cited by the Attorney General do courts suggest that persons other than the accused are precluded from bringing claims against the Attorney General for Crown Attorneys' misfeasant trial tactics. The fact that investigating police have not previously brought such a claim speaks to the egregiousness of prosecutors' misfeasance in this case&mdash;not to any prohibition recognized by courts.</P>
<P>85. For these reasons, Stinson J. was correct in determining the case law cited by the Attorney General does not support the proposition that preventing unfairness to the accused is the <UNDER>only</UNDER> ground other than abuse of process on which courts can review Crown Attorneys' tactical decisions.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM> at para. 144, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER>, Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>(4)</N><TI><EM>Stinson J. Did not Rely on</EM> <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>Which in Any Case is Irrelevant to the Issue of Misfeasance</EM></TI>
<P>86. Stinson J. made clear in his judgment that, while he had read the decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>, he had conducted his own analysis of the case law and come to his own conclusions. Nowhere in his judgment does he state that he is relying on Matheson J.'s decision.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Clark</EM> at paras. 39 and 77-78, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>87. Moreover, as argued above, the Respondents do not dispute that policy considerations are engaged whenever Crown liability is being considered. The Respondents respectfully submit that, in novel claims (involving new torts, or new claimants, or a new context), policy considerations should be based on a full evidentiary record and should not be dispositive at the pleadings stage. Even if the policy issues are considered at this stage, as argued above, they would not militate against recognizing the causes of action pleaded by the Officers.</P>
<P>88. The Respondents respectfully submit that the Divisional Court's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> was erroneous and, even if it were not, it is distinguishable from the case at bar.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>For the Officers' arguments distinguishing the Divisional Court decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 993</CITE></CASEREF>, see paras. 84&ndash;95 of the <UNDER>Amended Factum of the Appellants</UNDER>, appealing the Order of Justice Stinson, dated June 13, 2017, with respect to the ruling on negligence.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> However, as the Respondents have pleaded malice (in the sense of an &ldquo;improper purpose&rdquo;) as an element of their claim in misfeasance, the Divisional Court decision is not applicable to the instant appeal.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>(5)</N><TI><EM>The Respondents Properly Pleaded Material Facts That Establish Misfeasance in a Public Office</EM></TI>
<P>89. In response to the Attorney General's arguments at paragraphs 65&ndash;75 of its factum, the Respondents submit that Stinson J. identified all of the elements of the tort of misfeasance in a public office and correctly found that the Officers pleaded the material facts necessary to satisfy those elements.</P>
<P>90. The relevant elements of the tort of misfeasance in a public office are:
<P1>(a) The public officer must have engaged in deliberate and unlawful conduct in his or her capacity as a public officer; and</P1>
<P1>(b) The public officer was aware that his or her conduct was unlawful and that it was likely to harm the plaintiff(s).
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Odhavji Estate v. Woodhouse</SOC><CITE>[2003] 3 S.C.R. 263</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Odhavji</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 23, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 29.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>91. The following legal principles apply to the tort of misfeasance:
<P1>(a) If there is a legal duty on the public officer to act, and the public officer decides not to act or fails to act in breach of the duty, that omission can amount to misfeasance;</P1>
<P1>(b) Reckless indifference or wilful blindness to the illegality of his or her act satisfies the &ldquo;deliberate and unlawful&rdquo; conduct of the first element of the tort;</P1>
<P1>(c) Reckless indifference or wilful blindness as to the probable consequences of the unlawful act satisfies the second element of the tort; and</P1>
<P1>(d) The tort requires an element of bad faith or dishonesty, such that the public officer exercised her powers for an improper or ulterior purpose, or engaged in conduct that he or she knew to be inconsistent with the obligations of the office.
<P2><BOLD><EM>Odhavji</EM> at paras. 24, 28 and 38, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 29;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>O'Dwyer v. Ontario (Racing Commission)</SOC><CITE>2008 ONCA 446</CITE><PARANUM>42 and 48</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 30;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Trillium Power Wind Corp. v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>2013 ONCA 683</CITE><PARANUM>39</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 31;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Rain Coast Water Crop. v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>2016 BCSC 845</CITE><PARANUM>154-155</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, BOA Tab 32.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>92. The Officers clearly pleaded the &ldquo;unlawful act&rdquo; in their Claim: by failing to properly investigate the serious and unfounded allegations made by the accused against the police, by failing to challenge those allegations in Court with evidence that was readily available, and by failing to conduct the prosecution to the best of their skills and abilities, the Crown Attorneys in this case acted unlawfully and in violation of their sworn duties under the <EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM>. These duties are detailed at section 11 of the <EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM>, and the Crown Attorney's oath to uphold them is at section 8.</P>
<P>93. The facts as pleaded demonstrate that this unlawful conduct was deliberate. Ms. Cressman was fully aware of the Officers' testimony from the preliminary hearing, which vehemently contradicted the allegations of misconduct. Ms. Cressman was made aware of the Officers' concern about the adverse effects of not calling them as witnesses to challenge the allegations. The Crown Law Office was aware of the findings of the TPSPS report that concluded the allegations were unsubstantiated. Det. Sgt. Watt advised Ms. Alyea of the mistakes that had been made, and informed her of Ms. Cressman's conduct. In the face of all of this information, the Crown Attorneys still failed to take the required steps to comply with their statutory obligations, and simply conceded a <EM>Charter</EM> breach that brought the administration of justice into disrepute. At the very least, the Crown attorneys were recklessly indifferent or wilfully blind to the unlawfulness of their conduct.</P>
<P>94. The facts as pleaded in the Claim set out that the Crown Attorneys abdicated their statutory duties for an <UNDER>improper purpose</UNDER>: their failure to take appropriate steps to inform the Court of new evidence and mistakes in the prosecution of the case was an attempt to protect their own agents' conduct rather than pursue the administration of justice. The Crown Attorneys knew this conduct to be inconsistent with their oath of office and in bad faith.</P>
<P>95. The Crown Attorneys were aware or were recklessly indifferent or wilfully blind to the probable consequence that allowing the allegations to go unchallenged would irreparably harm the Officers' reputations and cause them severe distress. The allegations were of the most serious and egregious misconduct, condemned by the Superior Court and Ontario Court of Appeal. The Officers expressed their concern to the Crown Attorneys, but to no avail. The facts as pleaded in the Claim therefore establish the second element of misfeasance.</P>
<P>96. Finally, the Claim pleads the facts necessary to establish that the unlawful conduct of the Crown Attorneys was the cause of the harms experienced by the officers (including irreparable damage to their reputations, and severe emotional distress), all of which are compensable in tort law.</P>
<P>97. The Attorney General's arguments that &ldquo;the alleged &lsquo;unlawful act&rsquo;... could never be an &lsquo;unlawful act&rsquo; <EM>vis a vis</EM> the respondents,&rdquo; and that a Crown Attorney's oath &ldquo;does not create any duty to an investigating police officer to defend them against allegations of assault&rdquo; are puzzling and without merit. Contrary to the Attorney General's assertion, nowhere in the <EM>Crown Attorneys Act</EM> does it specify that a Crown Attorney's duties are owed only to the parties to a prosecution.</P>
<P>98. Moreover, the Supreme Court has made clear that, for the tort of misfeasance, the nexus between the parties (the torfeasor and the victim) is created by the tortfeasor's &ldquo;conscious disregard for the interests of those who will be affected by the misconduct in question.&rdquo; This nexus falls under the second element of the tort: knowledge that the conduct was unlawful and was likely to harm the plaintiff(s). As described above, the Officers pleaded the facts necessary to establish this second element. Contrary to the Attorney General's contention that the Officers failed to plead facts supporting the &ldquo;required element&rdquo; of &ldquo;intention to harm,&rdquo; the Officers note that this is not a required element of the tort under &ldquo;Category B,&rdquo; as explained by the Supreme Court.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Odhavji</EM> at paras. 22, 29, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 29.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>99. The Attorney General's submission at paragraph 71 of its factum that the acts complained of cannot be unlawful acts and are not reviewable by courts is incorrect. The Officers pleaded malice (as &ldquo;improper purpose&rdquo;) in their claim. As noted above, the jurisprudence is not settled on whether actions taken pursuant to prosecutorial discretion are subject to review when malice is alleged, nor on whether accused persons are the only potential claimants against the Crown for misfeasance. Furthermore, the Officers have alleged misfeasance with respect to actions that do not fall under prosecutorial discretion, but are instead matters of trial tactics, which are subject to a lower standard of review.</P>
<P>100. Finally, the Officers adequately pleaded facts to demonstrate bad faith, in the sense that Crown Attorneys engaged in conduct they knew to be inconsistent with the obligations of their office for an improper purpose. As demonstrated by case law, &ldquo;bad faith&rdquo; does not require that the tortfeasor act with intent to cause harm.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Odhavji</EM> at para. 28, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 29;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Finney v. Barreau du Quebec</SOC><CITE>2004 SCC 36</CITE><PARANUM>39-40</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, BOA Tab 33;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Enterprises Sibeca Inc. v. Frelishsburg (Municipality)</SOC><CITE>2004 SCC 61</CITE><PARANUM>26</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, BOA Tab 34;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Bennett v. Bennett Environment Inc.</SOC><CITE>2009 ONCA 198</CITE><PARANUM>30</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 35;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Sparks (Litigation Guardian of) v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>2010 ONSC 4234</CITE><PARANUM>23-24, 26</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 36.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>101. For all of these reasons, Stinson J. was correct to conclude that the Officers have pleaded the essential elements of the tort of misfeasance and the facts necessary to support those elements.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>(6)</N><TI><EM>Stinson J.'s Decision Not to Allow Evidence on the Motion to Strike Was Correct</EM></TI>
<P>102. The Attorney General has not provided any grounds to support its assertion that the transcripts of Court proceedings referenced in the Statement of Claim were &ldquo;necessary to determine the substantive adequacy&rdquo; of the Respondents' claims and &ldquo;to provide an essential factual context&rdquo; to the Claim. There is therefore no reason to disturb Stinson J.'s finding that the transcript was evidence that was not admissible on the motion to strike.</P>
<P>103. No evidence is admissible on a Rule 21.01(1)(b) motion. No evidence is admissible on a Rule 21.01(1)(a) motion without leave of the Court or on consent of the parties.
<P1><BOLD>Rules of Civil Procedure, R.R.O. 1990, Reg. 194, Rule 21.01(2).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>104. While there is precedent to support the notion that evidence can be admitted in a Rule 21.01 motion&mdash;even a 21.01(1)(b) motion&mdash;if it is incorporated by reference in the Statement of Claim, courts have emphasized the limited use of such evidence: it may be referenced to establish basic facts, such as the date charges were laid, the exact wording of the charges, the time when the trial occurred, etc. It may not be used to determine the viability of a Claim:
<QUOTE><P>I am of the view that, with the exception of basic factual matters of the type to which I have referred, it is not proper to have reference to other evidence on a motion such as this for the purpose of trying to establish that the plaintiff's claim has no chance of success. On the contrary, I must look solely at the pleading and determine whether the necessary facts are pleaded to support any or all of the causes of action alleged. The issue of whether those facts can successfully prove the claims alleged when confronted with other facts is a matter that must be dealt with at a later date. To do otherwise is to muddy what is otherwise a clear line between motions such as this and summary judgment motions to the obvious detriment of the plaintiff.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Leadbeater v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[2001] O.J. No. 3472</CITE><PARANUM>8-9</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 37.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>105. At no point in his judgment does Stinson J. mention the need for evidence to establish basic facts or the substantive adequacy of the Officers' claims. As the decision about whether to admit such evidence is at the discretion of the Court, it is not clear why Stinson J. should have admitted evidence he did not deem necessary or appropriate to admit on a motion to strike.</P>
<P>106. Moreover, one of the reasons the Attorney General sought to have documents referenced in the Statement of Claim admitted was to &ldquo;establish when the plaintiffs knew the material facts necessary to commence their claim.&rdquo; Precedent has established that evidence bearing on the issue of discoverability should not be admitted on a Rule 21 motion:
<QUOTE><P>The purpose of Rule 21 is to determine questions of law prior to trial and to strike out pleadings if they disclose no reasonable cause of action. To allow the admission of evidence to deal with the discoverability issues, as proposed by the Defendants, goes well beyond the purpose of Rule 21. If I were to allow in evidence proposed by the Defendants, I would also have to allow in evidence on these issues from the Plaintiffs. Based on the submissions I have received from counsel, it is apparent that there will be many differences with respect to certain facts as they relate to the discoverability' issues. This result would go well beyond the intent of Rule 21. The application for leave is therefore dismissed.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gloor v. Anderson</SOC><YEAR>2008</YEAR><CITE>CarswellOnt 7359</CITE><PARANUM>6</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>, <UNDER>BOA</UNDER> Tab 38; Factum of the Attorney General in the Motion to Strike, <UNDER>Attorney General's Appeal Book and Compendium</UNDER>, Volume 1, Tab 12 at para. 35.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>107. For these reasons, the Respondents submit that there is no basis for a finding that Stinson J . exercised his discretion on this issue in error, and his ruling should stand.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Conclusion</EM></TI>
<P>108. Stinson J. was correct in finding that case law authority does not preclude Crown liability for actions other than malicious prosecution and intentional nondisclosure of exculpatory evidence.</P>
<P>109. He was also correct in ruling that the Officers had pleaded the requisite elements of the tort of misfeasance in a public office and had included the material facts necessary to support those elements.</P>
<P>110. The issues of the scope of Crown Attorneys' duties and whether they were breached in this case, and the complex policy considerations about the effects of imposing liability for Crown Attorney' misconduct are matters that ought to be determined on the basis of a complete evidentiary record at trial. For these reasons, the Respondents respectfully submit that this Honourable Court should uphold Stinson J.'s judgment concerning misfeasance and allow the action to proceed to trial.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">V. ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>111. For the above reasons, the Respondents seek:
<P1>(a) An Order dismissing the Appellants' appeal;</P1>
<P1>(b) An Order granting the Respondents the costs of this Appeal;</P1>
<P1>(c) Such further and other relief as this Honourable Court deems just.</P1></P>
